\u00c9 Archives |publisher=Stills Library |date= |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 | {{Esc|United Kingdom}}\n| [[Pete Murray (DJ)|Pete Murray]]\n| ([[BBC Radio 2]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/7664bed6c9804fab89cfb316e010173a|title=Eurovision Song Contest 1973 - BBC Radio 2 - 7 April 1973|publisher=[[BBC Genome Project]]|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Richard Astbury\n| ([[British Forces Broadcasting Service|British Forces Radio]])<ref name=\"Roxburgh\">{{cite book|last=Roxburgh|first=Gordon|title=Songs For Europe \u2013 The United Kingdom at the Eurovision Song Contest Volume Two: The 1970's|publisher=[[Telos Publishing]]|location=UK|year=2014|isbn=978-1-84583-065-6}}</ref>{{rp|116}}\n|-\n| {{Esc|France}} - N/A\n| TBC\n| TBC\n|-\n| {{Esc|Israel}} - N/A\n| TBC\n| TBC\n|}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n\n=== Non-participating countries ===\n* {{Esc|Austria}} (Non-participating country) \u2013 [[Ernst Grissemann]] ([[ORF2|FS2]])\n* {{Esc|Greece|1970}} (Non-participating country) \u2013 Mako Georgiadou ([[ET1 (Greece)|EIRT]])\n* {{Esc|Iceland}} (Non-participating country) \u2013 J\u00f3n O. Edwald ([[R\u00daV]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?issId=264691&pageId=3732090&lang=is&q=Eurovision|title=Timarit.is|first=Landsb\u00f3kasafn \u00cdslands -|last=H\u00e1sk\u00f3lab\u00f3kasafn|website=timarit.is}}</ref>\n* {{Esc|Malta}} (Non-participating country) \u2013 Charles Saliba\n* {{Esc|Turkey}} (Non-participating country) \u2013 [[B\u00fclend \u00d6zveren]] ([[TRT 1|Ankara Television]])\n{{Col-2}}\n\n=== National jury members ===\n* {{flag|Finland}} - Kristiina Kauhtio (under 25) and Heikki Sarmanto (over 25)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viisukuppila.fi/muistathan-eurovision-laulukilpailu-1973/ |title=Muistathan: Eurovision laulukilpailu 1973 |publisher=Viisukuppila.fi |date=2012-01-09 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Portugal}} - Jos\u00e9 Calv\u00e1rio (under 25) and Teresa Silva Carvalho (over 25)\n* {{flag|Norway}} - Inger Ann Folkvord (under 25) and Johannes Bergh (over 25) <ref name=\"Eriksen, Espen page 14, 6\"/> \n* {{flag|Spain|1945}} - Teresa Gonz\u00e1lez (under 25) and Jos\u00e9 Luis Balb\u00edn (over 25)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r4m9g9tIlXk |title=Eurovisi\u00f3n 1978 Jurado TVE (I) |publisher=YouTube |date=2008-01-25 |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Switzerland}} - [[Paola del Medico]] (under 25) and [[Yor Milano]] (over 25)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FkaRCNbtTHk |title=ESC 1973 - French comments (ORTF) - The voting |publisher=YouTube |date=2015-01-16 |accessdate=2015-01-16}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Yugoslavia}} - Du\u0161an Leki\u0107, student from Titograd(now Podgorica in Montenegro,under 25) and Ivan Antonov, presenter in TV Skopje  (over 25)<ref>Vladimir Pinzovski.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ogaemacedonia.org.mk/2006/jugovizija |title=OGAE Macedonia |publisher=OGAE Macedonia |accessdate=2012-08-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214000822/http://www.ogaemacedonia.org.mk/2006/jugovizija |archivedate=2013-12-14 }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Sweden}} - [[Lena Andersson (singer)|Lena Andersson]] (under 25) and Lars Samuelson (over 25)<ref name=\"Leif Thorsson 2006 p. 102\" />\n* {{flag| United Kingdom}} - Catherine Woodfield (under 25) and Pat Williams (over 25)<ref name=\"Roxburgh\" />{{rp|124}}\n* {{flag|France}} - Adeline Estragnat (under 25) and Dani\u00e8le Heymann (over 25)\n{{Col-end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Eurovision Song Contest 1973}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.eurovision.tv/}}\n\n{{Eurovision years}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest 1973}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest's Greatest Hits}}\n\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest 1973| ]]\n[[Category:1973 in Luxembourg]]\n[[Category:1973 in music]]\n[[Category:20th century in Luxembourg City]]\n[[Category:April 1973 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest by year]]\n[[Category:Events in Luxembourg City]]\n[[Category:Music in Luxembourg City]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Song Contest\n| name         = Eurovision Song Contest\n| year         = 1973\n| theme        =\n| size         = 230px\n| logo         = Eurovision Song Contest 1973 logo.png\n| semi1        =\n| semi2        =\n| final        = 7 April 1973\n| presenters   = [[Helga Guitton]]\n| conductor    = [[Pierre Cao]]\n| director     =\n| exsupervisor = [[Clifford Brown (scrutineer)|Clifford Brown]]\n| winner       = {{esc|Luxembourg|y=1973}}<br />\"[[Tu te reconna\u00eetras]]\"\n| vote         = Two-member juries (one aged 16 to 25 and the other 25 to 55) rated songs between one and five points.\n| host         = [[Compagnie Luxembourgeoise de T\u00e9l\u00e9diffusion]] (CLT)\n| venue        = [[Grand Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de Luxembourg|Grand Th\u00e9\u00e2tre]]<br />Luxembourg City, Luxembourg\n| entries      = 17\n| debut        = {{Esc|Israel}}\n| return       = None\n| nonreturn     = {{unbulleted list|{{Esc|Austria}}|{{Esc|Malta}}}}\n| null         = None\n| interval     = [[Charlie Rivel]]\n| opening      = Pierre Cao and the orchestra performing \"Apr\u00e9s toi\" to a montage of views of Luxembourg and behind the scenes.\n<!-- Map Legend Colours -->\n| Green    = Y\n| Green SA = \n| Purple   = \n| Red      = \n| Yellow   = Y\n}}\nThe '''Eurovision Song Contest 1973''' was the 18th edition of the annual [[Eurovision Song Contest]].\n\nIt was held in [[Luxembourg (city)|Luxembourg]]. In a back-to-back victory,the country won the contest with the song \"[[Tu te reconna\u00eetras]]\", this being Luxembourg's fourth win. The voting was a very close one, with Spain finishing only 4 points behind and [[Cliff Richard]] of the United Kingdom (who had come second in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1968|1968]]) another 2 points further back. The winning song scored the highest score ever achieved in Eurovision under any voting format until 1975, recording 129 points out of a possible 160, which represented almost 81% of the possible maximum. This was partly due to a scoring system which guaranteed all countries at least two points from each other country.<ref>O'Connor, John Kennedy. The Eurovision Song Contest \u2013 The Official History. Carlton Books. {{ISBN|978-1-84732-521-1}} April 2010</ref>\n\n== Location ==\n{{details|topic=the host city|Luxembourg (city)}}\n[[File:Luxemburg Grand Theatre 2.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Grand Th\u00e9\u00e2tre, Luxembourg City \u2013 host venue of the 1973 contest.]]\nThe city of Luxembourg, also known as '''Luxembourg City''', is a [[Communes of Luxembourg|commune]] with [[List of cities in Luxembourg|city status]], and the [[Capital (political)|capital]] of the [[Luxembourg|Grand Duchy of Luxembourg]]. It is located at the [[confluence]] of the [[Alzette]] and [[P\u00e9trusse]] Rivers in southern Luxembourg. The city contains the historic '''Luxembourg Castle''', established by the [[Franks]] in the [[Early Middle Ages]], around which a settlement developed.\n\nThe Grand Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de Luxembourg, inaugurated in 1964 as the Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Municipal de la Ville de Luxembourg, became the venue for the 1973 contest. It is the city's major venue for drama, opera and ballet.<ref>[http://salesguide.lu/press-en-4-321.html \"The \"Grand Th\u00e9\u00e2tre\" of Luxembourg City offers high quality cultural events\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722160736/http://salesguide.lu/press-en-4-321.html |date=2011-07-22 }}, ''Luxembourg National Tourist Office, London''. Retrieved 27 December 2010.</ref><ref name=\"theatreinfo\">[http://www.theatreinfo.lu/spip.php?article23 \"Grand Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de Luxembourg\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722161150/http://www.theatreinfo.lu/spip.php?article23 |date=2011-07-22 }}, ''Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Info Luxembourg''. {{in lang|fr}} Retrieved 27 December 2010.</ref>\n\n== Format ==\nThe language rule forcing countries to enter songs sung in any of their national languages was dropped, so performers from some countries sang in [[English language|English]].  The event was marked by controversy when the [[Spain|Spanish]] song, \"Eres t\u00fa\" (by Mocedades), was accused of [[plagiarism]] due to reasonable similarities in the melody with the [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] entry from the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1966|1966 contest]] (\"[[Brez besed]]\" sung by [[Berta Ambro\u017e]]); however, \"Eres t\u00fa\" was not disqualified. After finishing second in the contest, the song went on to become a huge international hit.\n\nThe somewhat elliptical lyrics to Portugal's entry \"[[Tourada]]\" provided sufficient cover for a song that was clearly understood as a blistering assault on the country's decaying dictatorship. Also, the word \"breasts\" was used during Sweden's song entry. However, no action was taken by the EBU.  An argument broke out between the singer [[Maxi (singer)|Maxi]] and her [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] delegation over how the song should be performed. During rehearsals she repeatedly stopped performing in frustration. When it began to appear possible that Maxi might withdraw from the contest, [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]] immediately sent over another singer, [[Tina Reynolds]], to take her place just in case. In the end Miss Reynolds wasn't needed as Maxi did perform, with her entry earning 10th place on the scoreboard. (Reynolds would perform [[Eurovision Song Contest 1974|the following year]].)\n\nThis contest holds the record for the most watched Eurovision Song Contest in the [[United Kingdom]], and is also the 18th [[List of most-watched television broadcasts#Most watched programmes|most watched television show]] in the same country, with an estimated 21.54 million tuning in on the night. [[Cliff Richard]] represented the [[United Kingdom|UK]] with the song [[Power to All Our Friends]]. He came 3rd with 123 points. The winner though was [[Anne-Marie David]] with '[[Tu te reconna\u00eetras]]'. In the UK it was released in English under the title \"Wonderful Dream\" and released on Epic. It made number 13.\n\nIn the light of events at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]] in Munich, there were fears of a terrorist threat, particularly directed against Israel's first-ever entrant, leading to unusually tight security for the contest.  This gave rise to one of the best-known Eurovision anecdotes, frequently recounted by the UK's long-serving commentator [[Terry Wogan]].  He recalled that the floor manager strongly advised the audience to remain seated while applauding the performances, otherwise they risked being shot by security forces.<ref>O'Connor, John Kennedy. The Eurovision Song Contest \u2013 The Official History. Carlton Books, UK. 2007 {{ISBN|978-1-84442-994-3}}</ref>\n\n=== Voting ===\nEach country had two jury members, one aged between 16 and 25 and one aged between 26 and 55. They each awarded 1 to 5 points for each song (other than the song from their own country) immediately after it was performed and the votes were collected and counted as soon as they were cast. The juries watched the show on TV from the Ville du Louvigny TV Studios of CLT and appeared on screen to confirm their scores.\n\n== Participating countries ==\nSeventeen nations took part in this year's contest.  [[Malta]] was drawn to perform in 6th place between [[Norway]] and [[Monaco]], but the Maltese broadcaster withdrew before the deadline to select an entry.<ref name=\"eurovisionsongs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurovisionsongs.net/nononever.htm|title=No, No, Never!!! - Songs That Did Not Make It To Eurovision|website=eurovisionsongs.net|accessdate=2009-07-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090301032000/http://www.eurovisionsongs.net/nononever.htm|archivedate=2009-03-01}}</ref>  \nThis was the first year [[Israel in the Eurovision Song Contest|Israel]] competed in the contest.\nThe 1973 contest marked the first time that women conducted the ESC orchestra. [[Monica Dominique]] conducted the Swedish entry and [[Nurit Hirsh]] conducted the Israeli entry.\n\n=== Conductors ===\nEach performance had a [[conducted|conductor]] who was the [[maestro]] of the orchestra.<ref name=Conductors>{{cite web|title=Conductors 1973|url=http://4lyrics.eu/eurovision/esc-1973/|publisher=4Lyrics.com|accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* {{Esc|Finland}} - [[Ossi Runne]]\n* {{Esc|Belgium}} - Francis Bay\n* {{Esc|Portugal}} - Jorge Costa Pinto\n* {{Esc|Germany}} - G\u00fcnther-Eric Th\u00f6ner\n* {{Esc|Norway}} - [[Carsten Klouman]]\n* {{Esc|Monaco}} - Jean-Claude Vannier\n* {{Esc|Spain|1945}} - [[Juan Carlos Calder\u00f3n]]\n* {{Esc|Switzerland}} - Herv\u00e9 Roy\n* {{Esc|Yugoslavia}} - Esad Arnautali\u0107\n* {{Esc|Italy}} - Enrico Polito\n* {{Esc|Luxembourg}} - [[Pierre Cao]]\n* {{Esc|Sweden}} - [[Monica Dominique]]\n* {{Esc|Netherlands}} - [[Harry van Hoof]]\n* {{Esc|Ireland}} - [[Colman Pearce]]\n* {{Esc|United Kingdom}} - [[David Mackay (producer)|David Mackay]]\n* {{Esc|France}} - Jean Claudric\n* {{Esc|Israel}} - [[Nurit Hirsh]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n=== Returning artists ===\nThree artists returned to the 1973 contest, [[Finland in the Eurovision Song Contest|Finland]]'s [[Marion Rung]], who last represented the nation in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1962|1962]]; [[Eurovision Song Contest 1971|1971]] entrant [[Massimo Ranieri]] from [[Italy in the Eurovision Song Contest|Italy]]; and [[Cliff Richard]], who last performed \"[[Congratulations (Cliff Richard song)|Congratulations]]\" for the [[United Kingdom in the Eurovision Song Contest|United Kingdom]] in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1968|1968]].\n\n== Results ==\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n! Draw\n! Country\n! Artist\n! Song\n! Language<ref>{{cite web|title=Eurovision Song Contest 1973|url=http://www.diggiloo.net/?1973|publisher=The Diggiloo Thrush|accessdate=4 March 2012}}</ref>\n! Place\n! Points\n|-\n| 01\n| {{Esc|Finland|y=1973}}\n| [[Marion Rung]]\n| \"[[Tom Tom Tom]]\"\n| [[English language|English]]\n| 6\n| 93\n|-\n| 02\n| {{Esc|Belgium|y=1973}}\n| [[Nicole & Hugo]]\n| \"[[Baby, Baby (Nicole & Hugo song)|Baby, Baby]]\"\n| [[Dutch language|Dutch]]{{ref|a|1}}\n| 17\n| 58\n|-\n| 03\n| {{Esc|Portugal|y=1973}}\n| [[Fernando Tordo]]\n| \"[[Tourada]]\"\n| [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]\n| 10\n| 80\n|-\n| 04\n| {{Esc|Germany|y=1973}}\n| [[Gitte H\u00e6nning|Gitte]]\n| \"[[Junger Tag]]\"\n| [[German language|German]]\n| 8\n| 85\n|-\n| 05\n| {{Esc|Norway|y=1973}}\n| [[Bendik Singers]]\n| \"[[It's Just A Game]]\"\n| English, [[French language|French]]{{ref|b|2}}\n| 7\n| 89\n|-\n| 06\n| {{Esc|Monaco|y=1973}}\n| [[Marie-France Dufour|Marie]]\n| \"[[Un train qui part]]\"\n| French\n| 8\n| 85\n|-\n| 07\n| {{Esc|Spain|1945|y=1973}}\n| [[Mocedades]]\n| \"[[Eres t\u00fa]]\"\n| [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| 2\n| 125\n|-\n| 08\n| {{Esc|Switzerland|y=1973}}\n| [[Patrick Juvet]]\n| \"[[Je vais me marier, Marie]]\"\n| French\n| 12\n| 79\n|-\n| 09\n| {{Esc|Yugoslavia|y=1973}}\n| [[Zdravko \u010coli\u0107]]\n| \"[[Gori vatra]]\" \n| [[Serbo-Croatian]]\n| 15\n| 65\n|-\n| 10\n| {{Esc|Italy|y=1973}}\n| [[Massimo Ranieri]]\n| \"[[Chi sar\u00e0 con te]]\"\n| [[Italian language|Italian]]\n| 13\n| 74\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold;background:gold;\"\n| 11\n| {{Esc|Luxembourg|y=1973}}\n| [[Anne-Marie David]]\n| \"[[Tu te reconna\u00eetras]]\"\n| French\n| 1\n| 129\n|-\n| 12\n| {{Esc|Sweden|y=1973}}\n| [[Malta (band)|The Novas]] & [[The Dolls (band)|The Dolls]]\n| \"[[You're Summer]]\"\n| English\n| 5\n| 94\n|-\n| 13\n| {{Esc|Netherlands|y=1973}}\n| [[Ben Cramer]]\n| \"[[De oude muzikant]]\"\n| Dutch\n| 14\n| 69\n|-\n| 14\n| {{Esc|Ireland|y=1973}}\n| [[Maxi (singer)|Maxi]]\n| \"[[Do I Dream]]\"\n| English\n| 10\n| 80\n|-\n| 15\n| {{Esc|United Kingdom|y=1973}}\n| [[Cliff Richard]]\n| \"[[Power to All Our Friends]]\"\n| English\n