{"title_page": "Gabriel Matzneff", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| name               = Gabriel Matzneff\n| image              = Gabriel_Matzneff_1983_photographie_de_Florence_Kirastinnicos.jpg\n| caption            = Matzneff at Rue des Ursulines, Paris.\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1936|08|12}}\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Paris]]\n| birth_place        = [[Neuilly-sur-Seine]], France\n| nationality        = [[France|French]]\n| occupation         = Author\n| spouse             = {{marriage| Tatiana Scherbatcheff|January 8, 1970|March 3, 1973|end=div}}\n| criminal_charges   = \n}}\n\n'''Gabriel Matzneff''' (born August 12, 1936), is a French writer. He was the winner of the Mottard and Amic awards from the [[Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]] in 1987 and 2009 respectively, the [[Prix Renaudot]] in 2013 and the Prix Cazes in 2015. \n\nIn spite of having described his pedophile and sexual tourism activities in several of his books as well as on his official website. He remained sheltered from any criminal prosecution throughout his literary career and benefited from a wide and enthusiastic support within the French literary world and beyond - all that despite the fact that his books didn't sell well and that he was ignored by the general reading public.<ref>His best-seller, ''Ivre du Vin Perdu'' (1981) sold 20,000 copies. Most of his books sold between 1,500 and 2,000 copies and ''S\u00e9raphin, c'est la fin'', which earned him the prestigious Prix Renaudot in 2013, sold less than 4,000 copies. Christian Lehmann, \"Ivre du temps perdu\", ''M\u00e9diapart'', 30 December 2019. https://blogs.mediapart.fr/lehmann-christian/blog/301219/ivre-du-temps-perdu.</ref>\n\nOn February 11, 2020, French prosecutors announced that a criminal investigation had been launched. Matzneff was summoned to appear before a Paris court the following day.<ref name=nytimesonishi>{{citation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/11/world/europe/gabriel-matzneff-pedophilia-france.html|title=A Pedophile Writer Is on Trial. So Are the French Elites|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|date=February 11, 2020|first=Norimitsu|last=Onishi|access-date=February 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211182254/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/11/world/europe/gabriel-matzneff-pedophilia-france.html|archive-date=February 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n===Family, youth and education===\nMatzneff came from a family of Russian [[\u00e9migr\u00e9]]s who settled in France after 1917. According to information available on his official website, \u201chis parents divorced when he was six months old; throughout his childhood he never saw them in the same room, and would often be separated from his sister Alexandra and his brothers Andr\u00e9 and Nicolas. It was a childhood tossed to and fro, overshadowed by family breakdowns and war. It was a childhood which still causes him very painful memories.\"<ref>{{Cite web|lang=fr|title=La jeunesse de Gabriel Matzneff|trans-title=The youth of Gabriel Matzneff|url=http://www.matzneff.com/biographie.php|work=matzneff.com|date=2009|accessdate=30 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229181900/http://www.matzneff.com/biographie.php|archive-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHis family raised him in a refined cultural environment, rubbing shoulders with such famous French figures as [[L\u00e9on Chestov]] and [[Nikolai Berdyaev|Nicolas Berdiaev]]. It is here he discovered literature and religion. Matzneff spent a year attending the Gerson private Catholic school (1943\u20131944), two in [[Lyc\u00e9e Saint-Louis-de-Gonzague]] (1944\u20131946), then moved to a school in Tannenberg from between 1946 and 1952, and from 1952 attended [[Lyc\u00e9e Carnot]]. In 1954 he commenced his studies on classical letters and philosophy at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]]. After completing his military service in Algeria between 1959 and 1960, Matzneff returned to Paris in 1961. He enrolled as a Russian speaker at the [[Institut national des langues et civilisations orientales]] and began a career as a journalist.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|lang=fr|title=Biographie de Gabriel Matzneff|trans-title=Biography of Gabriel Matzneff|url=http://evene.lefigaro.fr/celebre/biographie/gabriel-matzneff-4453.php|work=Figaroscope|publisher=Le Figaro.fr|accessdate=December 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229002034/http://evene.lefigaro.fr/celebre/biographie/gabriel-matzneff-4453.php|archive-date=December 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>.\n\nHe met [[Henry de Montherlant]] in June 1957 and remained his friend, in spite of quarrels, until his suicide on September 21, 1972. On the nights of March 21st and 22, 1973, Matzneff dispersed the ashes of Montherlant with the 'executor of the latter, Jean-Claude Barat, on the Roman Forum and in the Tiber'.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/archives/article/1973/04/20/les-cendres-de-montherlant_2543478_1819218.html|title=Les cendres de Montherlant|publisher=[[Le Monde]]|date=April 20, 1973|trans-title=The ashes of Montherlant}}</ref>\n\nHe began to keep his diary on August 1, 1953 but did not publish it until 1976. In the first volume, he drew himself the face of a \"r\u00e9fractaire\" &ndash; an individual opposed to modern customs. He wrote at the time that \"I was [[Athos (mythology)|Athos]], the great misanthrope lord, secret, different...\".<ref>{{Citation|lang=fr|first=Fran\u00e7ois|last=Bott|title=Gabriel Matzneff, le \u201clibertin sentimental\u201d|trans-title=Gabriel Matzneff, the \u201csentimental libertine\u201d|publisher=Le Monde|date=19 March 1976|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/archives/article/1976/03/19/gabriel-matzneff-le-libertin-sentimental_2962768_1819218.html|access-date=21 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230153647/https://www.lemonde.fr/archives/article/1976/03/19/gabriel-matzneff-le-libertin-sentimental_2962768_1819218.html|archive-date=30 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Literary career===\nin October 1962, the publication director of [[Combat (newspaper)|Combat]], who had noticed his work, asked him to write a column for his daily. During the following decades, Matzneff was to be a regular or occasional columnist for several newspapers and magazines of all political stripes, including ''[[Le Quotidien de Paris]]'', ''[[Le Figaro]]'' and'' [[Le Monde]]'''. From 2013 to December 2019, he kept an irregular column on the web edition of ''[[Le Point]]''.<ref name=LeMdec19>{{citation|first=Dominique|surname=Perrin|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/m-le-mag/article/2019/12/23/les-temps-ont-change-il-est-devenu-indefendable-dans-un-contexte-post-metoo-le-malaise-gabriel-matzneff_6023870_4500055.html|title=Les temps ont chang\u00e9, il est devenu ind\u00e9fendable dans un contexte post-#metoo,|lang=fr|trans-title=Times have changed, it has become indefensible in a post-#metoo world to defend Gabriel Matzneff|publisher=Le Monde|date=December 23, 2019|access-date=January 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115191219/https://www.lemonde.fr/m-le-mag/article/2019/12/23/les-temps-ont-change-il-est-devenu-indefendable-dans-un-contexte-post-metoo-le-malaise-gabriel-matzneff_6023870_4500055.html|archive-date=January 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1964 he took part  in the founding congress of the Coordinating Committee of Orthodox youth, where he met the high school student Tatiana Scherbatcheff, \"a teenage girl with shaggy hair, a slightly triangular face, vast and magnificent black eyes, princess set and fowl\".<ref>{{citation|title=L'Archange aux pieds fourchus: 1963-1964|lang=fr|trans-title=The Archangel with Forked Feet: 1963-1964|publisher=La Table ronde|date=1974|p=197}}</ref> He married her on January 8, 1970 in London before divorcing on March 3, 1973. This divorce caused him a crisis of faith which moved him away from the Church; he then left the Committee and ceased co-production of the television program ''Orthodoxy'' which he had helped to create in May 1965.\n\nHis first book, ''Le D\u00e9fi'', a collection of essays, was published in 1965. The following year he published his first novel, ''L'Archimandrite'', which he began writing during his military service. During the 1970s, he made a number of trips to the Middle East as well as to Poland and the Soviet Union. During the 1980s, he made several trips to the Philippines where, as he described in one of his books, he engaged in sex with pre-adolescent boys that he had picked up at Harrison Plaza, Manilla's main shopping center.<ref>Gabriel Matzneff, ''Mes amours d\u00e9compos\u00e9s : journal 1983-1984'', Gallimard, 1990, p. 222, 226\u2013227, 232.</ref>\n\nThe critic Pol Vandromme wrote in 1974 that he was \"the most notable writer of his generation\".<ref>{{citation|title=Le Rappel de Charleroi|lang=fr|trans-title=The Recall of Charleroi|date=April 27, 2010|publisher=\u00c9ditions du Sandre|p=271}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Matzneff joined [[\u00c9ditions Gallimard|Gallimard]] with the help of [[Philippe Sollers]], who published it in his collection \" L'Infini \". Gallimard paid monthly royalties to Matzneff until 2004.<ref name=\":4\">{{citation|lang=fr|title=Gabriel Matzneff, questions sur un prix Renaudot|trans-title=Gabriel Matzneff, questions about a Renaudot Prize|publisher=Le Monde|date=January 6, 2020|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2020/01/06/gabriel-matzneff-questions-sur-un-prix-renaudot_6024917_3224.html|accessdate=2020-01-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107011413/https://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2020/01/06/gabriel-matzneff-questions-sur-un-prix-renaudot_6024917_3224.html|archive-date=January 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGallimard, the leading publishing group and Matzneff's historical publisher for 30 years, abruptly stopped marketing the author's books in early January 2020 and recalled his books from bookstores, less than two months after having published ''L\u2019Amante de l\u2019Arsenal'', the last installment of his diary.<ref>\"Affaire Matzneff: Gallimard retire de la vente le journal de l\u2019\u00e9crivain, qu\u2019elle publiait depuis trente ans\", ''AFP-Le Monde''. https://www.lemonde.fr/culture/article/2020/01/07/affaire-matzneff-gallimard-retire-de-la-vente-le-journal-de-l-ecrivain-qu-elle-publiait-depuis-trente-ans_6025067_3246.html </ref> On 12 February 2020, the police searched the headquarters of \u00c9ditions Gallimard looking for, among other things, unpublished manuscripts detailing Matzneff's pedophile activities.<ref>\"Affaire Matzneff: perquisition chez Gallimard, l\u2019enqu\u00eate s\u2019oriente vers son \u00e9diteur et compagnon de voyage\", L'Obs. https://www.nouvelobs.com/justice/20200212.OBS24751/affaire-matzneff-perquisition-chez-gallimard-l-enquete-s-oriente-vers-son-editeur-et-compagnon-de-voyage.html</ref>\n\nMatzneff was the winner of the Mottard and Amic awards from the [[Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]] in 1987 and 2009 respectively,{{cn|date=January 2020}} the [[Prix Renaudot]] for best essay in 2013<ref name=prix-renaudot/> and the Prix Cazes in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Alice de La|last1=Pradelle|accessdate=2020-01-21|title=Gabriel Matzneff re\u00e7oit le Prix Cazes|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/livres/2015/04/07/03005-20150407ARTFIG00284-gabriel-matzneff-recoit-le-prix-cazes.php|date=7 April 2015|website=Le Figaro.fr|trans-title=Gabriel Matzneff receives the Prix Cazes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115013205/https://www.lefigaro.fr/livres/2015/04/07/03005-20150407ARTFIG00284-gabriel-matzneff-recoit-le-prix-cazes.php|archive-date=15 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Pedophilia===\n\nDespite describing acts of [[pedophilia]] in his books, Matzneff remained sheltered from any criminal prosecution for a long time and benefited from a large support within the literary world.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51133850|title=When sexual abuse was called seduction: France confronts its past|first=Hugh|last=Schofield|author-link=Hugh Schofield|website=[[BBC News]]|date=January 19, 2020|access-date=January 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200120113140/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51133850|archive-date=January 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> At the end of 2019 one of his former victims, {{ill|Vanessa Springora|fr}} &mdash; the director of [[\u00c9ditions Julliard]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/27/french-publishing-boss-claims-she-was-groomed-at-age-14-by-acclaimed-author|title=French publishing boss claims she was groomed at age 14 by acclaimed author|first=Angelique|last=Chrisafis|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=December 28, 2019|access-date=January 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108184437/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/27/french-publishing-boss-claims-she-was-groomed-at-age-14-by-acclaimed-author|archive-date=January 8, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\u2014published the book ''Le Consentement'' describing the effect that Matzneff had on her at the age of 14. Her book unleashed an intense controversy over the tolerance of the literary milieu towards an assumed pedophile. This controversy first led [[\u00c9ditions Gallimard]] to withdraw their marketing services for some of his works, in particular ''Carnets noirs'' and ''Les Moins de seize ans'', with other publishers to follow.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/jan/10/matzneff-scandal-france-consent-literary-establishment|title=The Matzneff scandal shows France\u2019s attitude to consent is finally starting to change|first=Natasha|last=Lehrer|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=January 10, 2020|author-link=Natasha Lehrer|access-date=January 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115233817/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/jan/10/matzneff-scandal-france-consent-literary-establishment|archive-date=January 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMatzneff's diary ''Un Galop d\u2019Enfer'', published in 1985, read that whilst in the [[Philippines]] he would regularly have sex with underage boys. He wrote that \u201cSometimes, I\u2019ll have as many as four boys \u2014 from 8 to 14 years old \u2014 in my bed at the same time, and I\u2019ll engage in the most exquisite lovemaking with them\u201d.<ref name=nytimesonishi/>\n\n==Work==\n===Diaries===\nThe original title of the series, until 2009, was \"Journal\" , both in editions of the Round Table, from 1976 to 1991, and in Gallimard editions, from 1990 to 2007. According to the general catalog of the National Library from France, from 2009, with the publication by \u00c9ditions L\u00e9o Scheer, the overall title was changed to: ''Carnets noirs'' (\"Black Notebooks\").<ref name=\"BNF_journal\">[http://catalogue.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb343069518/PUBLIC Notice de collection ou de s\u00e9rie {{n\u00b0}}FRBNF34306951], dans le catalogue g\u00e9n\u00e9ral de la [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]].</ref>\n\n;Black Notebooks\n* {{citation|title=Cette camisole de flammes: 1953-1962|lang=fr|trans-title=This flaming camisole|publisher=[[\u00c9ditions de la Table ronde]]|publication-place=Paris|date=1976|p=262|id={{BNF|34557030f}}}}\n* {{citation|title=L'Archange aux pieds fourchus : 1963-1964|lang=fr|trans-title=The Archangel with Forked Feet: 1963-1964|publisher=\u00c9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1982| p=233|isbn=2-7103-0133-4|id={{BNF|34737851j}}}}\n* {{citation|title=V\u00e9nus et Junon : 1965-1969|lang=fr|trans-title=Venus and Juno: 1965-1969|publisher=\u00c9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1979|p=307|isbn=2-7103-0012-5|id={{BNF|34636949v}}}}\n* {{citation|title=\u00c9lie et Pha\u00e9ton : 1970-1973|lang=fr|trans-title=Elijah and Phaeton: 1970-1973|publisher=\u00c9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1991|p=386|isbn=2-7103-0470-8|id={{BNF|35414867d}}}}\n* {{citation|title=La Passion Francesca : 1974-1976|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|series=L'infini|publication-place=Paris|date=1998|p=339|isbn=978-2-07-075221-8|id={{BNF|36703098p}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Un galop d'enfer : 1977-1978|lang=fr|trans-title=A gallop from hell: 1977-1978|publisher=\u00c9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1985|p=294|isbn=2-7103-0250-0|id={{BNF|34871681g}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Les Soleils r\u00e9volus : 1979-1982|lang=fr|trans-title=The Suns Completed: 1979-1982|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|series=L'infini|publication-place=Paris|date=2001|p=544|isbn=978-2-07-076027-5|id={{BNF|372216856}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Mes amours d\u00e9compos\u00e9s : 1983-1984|lang=fr|trans-title=My broken down loves: 1983-1984|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|series=L'infini|publication-place=Paris|date=1990|p=381|isbn=978-2-07-071802-3|id={{BNF|35067165v}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Calamity Gab : janvier 1985 \u2013 avril 1986|lang=fr|trans-title=Calamity Gab: January 1985 - April 1986|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|work=L'infini|publication-place=Paris|date=2004|p=361|isbn=978-2070732654|id={{BNF|391539559}}}}\n* {{citation|title=La Prunelle de mes yeux : 1986-1987|lang=fr|trans-title=Apple of my eye: 1986-1987|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|series=L'infini|publication-place=Paris|date=1993|p=337|isbn=978-2-07-073174-9|id={{BNF|356015132}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Les Demoiselles du Taranne : journal 1988|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|series=L'infini|publication-place=Paris|date=2007|p=396|isbn=978-2-07-078399-1|id={{BNF|41004733g}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Carnets noirs 2007-2008|lang=fr|trans-title=Black Notebooks 2007-2008|publisher=[[\u00c9ditions L\u00e9o Scheer]]|publication-place=Paris|date=2009|p=512|isbn=978-2756101811|id={{BNF|41442267f}}}}\n\n;Journal\n* {{citation|title=Mais la musique soudain s'est tue : Journal 2009-2013|lang=fr|trans-title=But the music suddenly fell silent: Journal 2009-2013|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|work=Blanche|publication-place=Paris|date=2015|p=528|isbn=978-2-07-014542-3}}\n* {{citation|title=La Jeune Moabite : Journal 2013-2016|lang=fr|trans-title=Young Moabite: Journal 2013-2016|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|series=Blanche|publication-place=Paris|date=2017|p=702|isbn=978-2-07-273267-6}}\n* {{citation|title=L\u2019Amante de l\u2019Arsenal : Journal 2016-2018|lang=fr|trans-title=Lover of the Arsenal: Journal 2016-2018|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|series==Blanche|publication-place=Paris|date=2019|p=432|isbn=978-2-07-285442-2}}\n\n===Novels===\nGabriel Matzneff is the author of several novels with the same hero, Nil Kolytcheff. These are: ''Isa\u00efe r\u00e9jouis-toi'', ''Ivre du vin perdu'', ''Harrison Plaza'', ''Mamma, li Turchi!'', ''Voici venir le fianc\u00e9'', ''La Lettre au capitaine Brunner''.\n\n* {{citation|title=L'Archimandrite|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1966|pages=222|isbn=2-7103-00427|id={{BNF|40090166j}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Nous n'irons plus au Luxembourg|lang=fr|trans-title=We will no longer go to Luxembourg|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1972|edition=1st|pages=245|id={{BNF|35213179w}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Isa\u00efe r\u00e9jouis-toi|lang=fr|trans-title=Isaiah rejoice|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1974|p=251}} {{BNF|352146127}}\n* {{citation|title=Ivre du vin perdu|lang=fr|trans-title=Drunk on lost wine|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1981|p=323|isbn=2-7103-0065-6}} {{BNF|346611419}}\n* {{citation|title=Harrison Plaza|lang=fr|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1988|p=235|isbn=2-7103-0352-3}} {{BNF|349382059}}\n* {{citation|title=Les L\u00e8vres menteuses|lang=fr|trans-title=Lying lips|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1992|p=7|isbn=2-7103-0527-5}} {{BNF|35525394j}}\n* {{citation|title=Les Aventures de Nil Kolytcheff|trans-title=The Adventures of Nile Kolytcheff|publisher=\u00e9ditions Jean-Claude Latt\u00e8s|lang=fr|work=Les romanesques|publication-place=Paris|date=1994|pages=805|isbn=2-7096-1491-X|id={{BNF|357393226}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Mamma, li Turchi!|lang=it|trans-title=Mother, the Turks!|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=2000|p=271|isbn=2-7103-0984-X|id={{BNF|371198948}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Voici venir le fianc\u00e9|lang=fr|trans-title=Here comes the fiance|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=2006|p=313|isbn=2710327090|id={{BNF|40130100j}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Les \u00c9miles de Gab la Rafale, roman \u00e9lectronique|lang=fr|publication-place=Paris|publisher={{ill|\u00c9ditions L\u00e9o Scheer|fr}}|date=2010|isbn=978-2756102641}}\n* {{citation|title=La Lettre au capitaine Brunner|trans-title=A letter to Captain Brunner|lang=fr|publisher=la Table Ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=2015|p=208|isbn=978-2-7103-7586-9}} - winner of the Cazes-Brasserie Lipp prize, 2015<ref>{{Cite web|first=Agathe|last=Auproux|title=Gabriel Matzneff laur\u00e9at du prix Cazes-Brasserie Lipp|trans-title=Gabriel Matzneff winner of the Cazes-Brasserie Lipp prize|lang=fr|url=http://www.livreshebdo.fr/article/gabriel-matzneff-laureat-du-prix-cazes-brasserie-lipp|work=Livres Hebdo|date=8 April 2015|accessdate=2015-04-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413121653/http://www.livreshebdo.fr/article/gabriel-matzneff-laureat-du-prix-cazes-brasserie-lipp|archive-date=13 April 2015|url-status=live}}.</ref>\n\n===Essays===\n* {{citation|title=Le D\u00e9fi|lang=fr|trans-title=The Challenge|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1965}} - {{citation|title=Le D\u00e9fi - Nouvelle \u00e9dition, revue et augment\u00e9e|lang=fr|trans-title=The Challenge - New edition, revised and expanded|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1977|id={{BNF|35001130h}}}}\n* {{citation|title=La Caracole|lang=fr|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1969}}\n* {{citation|title=Les Moins de seize ans|lang=fr|trans-title=The under-sixteen|publisher=\u00e9ditions Julliard|work=Id\u00e9e fixe|publication-place=Paris|date=1974|pages=125|id={{BNF|34559062j}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Les Passions schismatiques|lang=fr|trans-title=Schismatic Passions|publisher=\u00e9ditions Stock|work=Le Monde ouvert|publication-place=Paris|date=1977|pages=160|isbn=2-234-00771-2|id={{BNF|345867642}}}}\n* {{citation|title=La Di\u00e9t\u00e9tique de lord Byron|lang=fr|trans-title=The Dietetics of Lord Byron|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1984|pages=215|isbn=2-7103-0185-7|id={{BNF|34752435d}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Le Sabre de Didi : pamphlet|lang=fr|trans-title=Didi's Saber: pamphlet|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1986|pages=266|isbn=2-7103-0298-5|id={{BNF|348777816}}}}. &mdash; This is a revised and expanded edition of ''La Caracole'', a collection of texts from various sources, published between 1963 and 1986\n* {{citation|title=Le Taureau de Phalaris: dictionnaire philosophique|lang=fr|trans-title=The Bull of Phalaris: philosophical dictionary|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1987|pages=300|isbn=2-7103-0313-2|id={{BNF|34908696x}}}} &mdash; reissued in the 1994 collection \"La Petite Vermillon\"\n* {{citation|title=Ma\u00eetres et complices|lang=fr|trans-title=Masters and accomplices|publisher=\u00e9ditions Jean-Claude Latt\u00e8s|publication-place=Paris|date=1994|pages=313|isbn=2-7096-1485-5|id={{BNF|36680568w}}}} &mdash; reissued in the collection \"La Petite Vermillon\"\n* {{citation|title=Le D\u00eener des mousquetaires|lang=fr|trans-title=The Musketeers' Dinner|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1995|pages=408|isbn=2-7103-0686-7|id={{BNF|357894722}}}}. &mdash; a collection of articles from various sources, published between 1961 and 1993\n* {{citation|title=De la rupture|lang=fr|trans-title=Break up|publisher=\u00e9ditions Payot & Rivages|work=Manuels Payot|publication-place=Paris|date=1997|pages=167|isbn=2-228-89070-7|id={{BNF|35860367s}}}}\n* {{citation|title=C'est la gloire, Pierre-Fran\u00e7ois !|lang=fr|trans-title=It's glory, Pierre-Fran\u00e7ois!|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=2002|pages=284|isbn=2-7103-2479-2|id={{BNF|388062554}}}} &mdash; a collection of texts from various sources, published between 1962 and 2001\n* {{citation|title=Yogourt et yoga|lang=fr|trans-title=Yogurt and yoga|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|work=Vermillon|publication-place=Paris|date=2004|pages=267|isbn=978-2-7103-2671-7|id={{BNF|39140535n}}}} &mdash; a collection of texts, from various sources, published between 1962 and 2003\n* {{citation|title=Vous avez dit m\u00e9t\u00e8que ?|lang=fr|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=2008|pages=415|isbn=978-2-7103-3087-5|id={{BNF|41362523w}}}} & mdash; a collection of 107 articles published between 1958 and 2007\n* {{citation|title=La S\u00e9quence de l'\u00e9nergum\u00e8ne|lang=fr|trans-title=The Sequence of a madman|publisher=\u00e9ditions L\u00e9o Sheer|date=2012|pages=340|isbn=2-7561-0360-8}} - chronicles appearances on television shows in the 1960s\n* {{citation|title=S\u00e9raphin c'est la fin !|lang=fr|trans-title=The end of the Seraphin!|publication-place=Paris|publisher=La Table Ronde|date=2013|pages=266|isbn=978-2-7103-7006-2}} &mdash; winner of the  [[Prix Renaudot|Renaudot Prize for essays]], 2013<ref name=prix-renaudot>{{cite news|url=http://www.lepoint.fr/livres/gabriel-matzneff-remporte-le-renaudot-essai-pour-seraphin-c-est-la-fin-04-11-2013-1751783_37.php|publisher=Le Point|title=Gabriel Matzneff remporte le Renaudot essai pour \"S\u00e9raphin, c'est la fin !\"|lang=fr|trans-title=Gabriel Matzneff wins the Renaudot essay for '' S\u00e9raphin, c'est la fin! ''|date=November 4, 2013|access-date=January 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216093333/https://www.lepoint.fr/livres/gabriel-matzneff-remporte-le-renaudot-essai-pour-seraphin-c-est-la-fin-04-11-2013-1751783_37.php|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* {{citation|title=Un diable dans le b\u00e9nitier|lang=fr|trans-title=A devil in the [[stoup]]|publisher=[[\u00c9ditions Stock]]|publication-place=Paris|date=2017|pages=380|isbn=978-2-234-08254-0}}\n\n===Stories===\n* {{citation|title=Le Carnet arabe|lang=fr|trans-title=The Arab Notebook|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1971|pages=231|id={{BNF|35173361f}}}} &mdash; reissued in the collection \"La Petite Vermillon\"\n* {{citation|title=Comme le feu m\u00eal\u00e9 d'aromates : r\u00e9cit|lang=fr|trans-title=Like fire mixed with aromatics: story|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1989|pages=176|isbn=2-7103-1168-2|id={{BNF|35001130h}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Boulevard Saint-Germain|lang=fr|publisher=\u00e9ditions du Rocher|work=La fantaisie du voyageur|publication-place=Monaco and Paris|date=1998|pages=194|isbn=2-268-03059-8|id={{BNF|37069451r}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Monsieur le comte monte en ballon|lang=fr|trans-title=The Count goes up in a balloon|publication-place=Paris|publisher=\u00c9ditions L\u00e9o Scheer|date=2012|pages=72|isbn=978-2-7561-0387-7}}\n\n===Poetry===\n* The 37th edition of the journal ''Recherches'', edited by F\u00e9lix Guattari, contains a poem by Gabriel Matzneff in his dossier ''Fous d'enfance : qui a peur des p\u00e9dophiles ?'' (which in English is \"Crazy about childhood: who is afraid of pedophiles?\") Other contributors: [[Luc Rosenzweig]], Gilbert Villerot, Jean-Luc Hennig, [[Ren\u00e9 Sch\u00e9rer]], [[Bernard Faucon]], [[Guy Hocquenghem]]...), \u00c9ditions Recherches, 1979.\n* {{citation|title=Douze po\u00e8mes pour Francesca|lang=fr|trans-title=Twelve poems for Francesca|publisher=\u00e9ditions A. Eibel|work=Lettres 5|publication-place=[[Lausanne]]|date=1977|pages=41|isbn=2-8274-0010-3|id={{BNF|346022062}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Super Flumina Babylonis : po\u00e8mes|lang=fr|trans-title=By the rivers of Bablyon &mdash; poems|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=2000|pages=97|isbn=2-7103-0959-9|id={{BNF|37111035m}}}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Matzneff, Gabriel}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:French writers]]\n[[Category:French people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:Modern pederasty]]\n[[Category:Pedophile activism]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| name               = Gabriel Matzneff\n| image              = Gabriel_Matzneff_1983_photographie_de_Florence_Kirastinnicos.jpg\n| caption            = Matzneff at Rue des Ursulines, Paris.\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1936|08|12}}\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Paris]]\n| birth_place        = [[Neuilly-sur-Seine]], France\n| nationality        = [[France|French]]\n| occupation         = Author\n| spouse             = {{marriage| Tatiana Scherbatcheff|January 8, 1970|March 3, 1973|end=div}}\n| criminal_charges   = \n}}\n\n'''Gabriel Matzneff''' (born August 12, 1936), is a French writer. He was the winner of the Mottard and Amic awards from the [[Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]] in 1987 and 2009 respectively, the [[Prix Renaudot]] in 2013 and the Prix Cazes in 2015. \n\nIn spite of having described his pedophile and sexual tourism activities in several of his books as well as on his official website. He remained sheltered from any criminal prosecution throughout his literary career and benefited from a wide and enthusiastic support within the French literary world and beyond - all that despite the fact that his books didn't sell well and that he was ignored by the general reading public.<ref>His best-seller, ''Ivre du Vin Perdu'' (1981) sold 20,000 copies. Most of his books sold between 1,500 and 2,000 copies and ''S\u00e9raphin, c'est la fin'', which earned him the prestigious Prix Renaudot in 2013, sold less than 4,000 copies. Christian Lehmann, \"Ivre du temps perdu\", ''M\u00e9diapart'', 30 December 2019. https://blogs.mediapart.fr/lehmann-christian/blog/301219/ivre-du-temps-perdu.</ref>\n\nOn February 11, 2020, French prosecutors announced that a criminal investigation had been launched. Matzneff was summoned to appear before a Paris court the following day.<ref name=nytimesonishi>{{citation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/11/world/europe/gabriel-matzneff-pedophilia-france.html|title=A Pedophile Writer Is on Trial. So Are the French Elites|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|date=February 11, 2020|first=Norimitsu|last=Onishi|access-date=February 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211182254/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/11/world/europe/gabriel-matzneff-pedophilia-france.html|archive-date=February 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n===Family, youth and education===\nMatzneff came from a family of Russian [[\u00e9migr\u00e9]]s who settled in France after 1917. According to information available on his official website, \u201chis parents divorced when he was six months old; throughout his childhood he never saw them in the same room, and would often be separated from his sister Alexandra and his brothers Andr\u00e9 and Nicolas. It was a childhood tossed to and fro, overshadowed by family breakdowns and war. It was a childhood which still causes him very painful memories.\"<ref>{{Cite web|lang=fr|title=La jeunesse de Gabriel Matzneff|trans-title=The youth of Gabriel Matzneff|url=http://www.matzneff.com/biographie.php|work=matzneff.com|date=2009|accessdate=30 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229181900/http://www.matzneff.com/biographie.php|archive-date=29 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHis family raised him in a refined cultural environment, rubbing shoulders with such famous French figures as [[L\u00e9on Chestov]] and [[Nikolai Berdyaev|Nicolas Berdiaev]]. It is here he discovered literature and religion. Matzneff spent a year attending the Gerson private Catholic school (1943\u20131944), two in [[Lyc\u00e9e Saint-Louis-de-Gonzague]] (1944\u20131946), then moved to a school in Tannenberg from between 1946 and 1952, and from 1952 attended [[Lyc\u00e9e Carnot]]. In 1954 he commenced his studies on classical letters and philosophy at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]]. After completed his military service in Algeria from between 1959 and 1960, Matzneff returned to Paris in 1961, enrolled in Russian at the [[Institut national des langues et civilisations orientales]] and began a career as a journalist.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|lang=fr|title=Biographie de Gabriel Matzneff|trans-title=Biography of Gabriel Matzneff|url=http://evene.lefigaro.fr/celebre/biographie/gabriel-matzneff-4453.php|work=Figaroscope|publisher=Le Figaro.fr|accessdate=December 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229002034/http://evene.lefigaro.fr/celebre/biographie/gabriel-matzneff-4453.php|archive-date=December 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>.\n\nHe met [[Henry de Montherlant]] in June 1957 and remained his friend, in spite of quarrels, until his suicide on September 21, 1972. On the nights of March 21st and 22, 1973, Matzneff dispersed the ashes of Montherlant with the 'executor of the latter, Jean-Claude Barat, on the Roman Forum and in the Tiber'.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/archives/article/1973/04/20/les-cendres-de-montherlant_2543478_1819218.html|title=Les cendres de Montherlant|publisher=[[Le Monde]]|date=April 20, 1973|trans-title=The ashes of Montherlant}}</ref>\n\nHe began to keep his diary on August 1, 1953 but did not publish it until 1976. In the first volume, he drew himself the face of a \"r\u00e9fractaire\" &ndash; an individual opposed to modern customs. He wrote at the time that \"I was [[Athos (mythology)|Athos]], the great misanthrope lord, secret, different...\".<ref>{{Citation|lang=fr|first=Fran\u00e7ois|last=Bott|title=Gabriel Matzneff, le \u201clibertin sentimental\u201d|trans-title=Gabriel Matzneff, the \u201csentimental libertine\u201d|publisher=Le Monde|date=19 March 1976|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/archives/article/1976/03/19/gabriel-matzneff-le-libertin-sentimental_2962768_1819218.html|access-date=21 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230153647/https://www.lemonde.fr/archives/article/1976/03/19/gabriel-matzneff-le-libertin-sentimental_2962768_1819218.html|archive-date=30 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Literary career===\nin October 1962, the publication director of [[Combat (newspaper)|Combat]], who had noticed his work, asked him to write a column for his daily. During the following decades, Matzneff was to be a regular or occasional columnist for several newspapers and magazines of all political stripes, including ''[[Le Quotidien de Paris]]'', ''[[Le Figaro]]'' and'' [[Le Monde]]'''. From 2013 to December 2019, he kept an irregular column on the web edition of ''[[Le Point]]''.<ref name=LeMdec19>{{citation|first=Dominique|surname=Perrin|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/m-le-mag/article/2019/12/23/les-temps-ont-change-il-est-devenu-indefendable-dans-un-contexte-post-metoo-le-malaise-gabriel-matzneff_6023870_4500055.html|title=Les temps ont chang\u00e9, il est devenu ind\u00e9fendable dans un contexte post-#metoo,|lang=fr|trans-title=Times have changed, it has become indefensible in a post-#metoo world to defend Gabriel Matzneff|publisher=Le Monde|date=December 23, 2019|access-date=January 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115191219/https://www.lemonde.fr/m-le-mag/article/2019/12/23/les-temps-ont-change-il-est-devenu-indefendable-dans-un-contexte-post-metoo-le-malaise-gabriel-matzneff_6023870_4500055.html|archive-date=January 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1964 he took part  in the founding congress of the Coordinating Committee of Orthodox youth, where he met the high school student Tatiana Scherbatcheff, \"a teenage girl with shaggy hair, a slightly triangular face, vast and magnificent black eyes, princess set and fowl\".<ref>{{citation|title=L'Archange aux pieds fourchus: 1963-1964|lang=fr|trans-title=The Archangel with Forked Feet: 1963-1964|publisher=La Table ronde|date=1974|p=197}}</ref> He married her on January 8, 1970 in London before divorcing on March 3, 1973. This divorce caused him a crisis of faith which moved him away from the Church; he then left the Committee and ceased co-production of the television program ''Orthodoxy'' which he had helped to create in May 1965.\n\nHis first book, ''Le D\u00e9fi'', a collection of essays, was published in 1965. The following year he published his first novel, ''L'Archimandrite'', which he began writing during his military service. During the 1970s, he made a number of trips to the Middle East as well as to Poland and the Soviet Union. During the 1980s, he made several trips to the Philippines where, as he described in one of his books, he engaged in sex with pre-adolescent boys that he had picked up at Harrison Plaza, Manilla's main shopping center.<ref>Gabriel Matzneff, ''Mes amours d\u00e9compos\u00e9s : journal 1983-1984'', Gallimard, 1990, p. 222, 226\u2013227, 232.</ref>\n\nThe critic Pol Vandromme wrote in 1974 that he was \"the most notable writer of his generation\".<ref>{{citation|title=Le Rappel de Charleroi|lang=fr|trans-title=The Recall of Charleroi|date=April 27, 2010|publisher=\u00c9ditions du Sandre|p=271}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Matzneff joined [[\u00c9ditions Gallimard|Gallimard]] with the help of [[Philippe Sollers]], who published it in his collection \" L'Infini \". Gallimard paid monthly royalties to Matzneff until 2004.<ref name=\":4\">{{citation|lang=fr|title=Gabriel Matzneff, questions sur un prix Renaudot|trans-title=Gabriel Matzneff, questions about a Renaudot Prize|publisher=Le Monde|date=January 6, 2020|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2020/01/06/gabriel-matzneff-questions-sur-un-prix-renaudot_6024917_3224.html|accessdate=2020-01-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107011413/https://www.lemonde.fr/societe/article/2020/01/06/gabriel-matzneff-questions-sur-un-prix-renaudot_6024917_3224.html|archive-date=January 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGallimard, the leading publishing group and Matzneff's historical publisher for 30 years, abruptly stopped marketing the author's books in early January 2020 and recalled his books from bookstores, less than two months after having published ''L\u2019Amante de l\u2019Arsenal'', the last installment of his diary.<ref>\"Affaire Matzneff: Gallimard retire de la vente le journal de l\u2019\u00e9crivain, qu\u2019elle publiait depuis trente ans\", ''AFP-Le Monde''. https://www.lemonde.fr/culture/article/2020/01/07/affaire-matzneff-gallimard-retire-de-la-vente-le-journal-de-l-ecrivain-qu-elle-publiait-depuis-trente-ans_6025067_3246.html </ref> On 12 February 2020, the police searched the headquarters of \u00c9ditions Gallimard looking for, among other things, unpublished manuscripts detailing Matzneff's pedophile activities.<ref>\"Affaire Matzneff: perquisition chez Gallimard, l\u2019enqu\u00eate s\u2019oriente vers son \u00e9diteur et compagnon de voyage\", L'Obs. https://www.nouvelobs.com/justice/20200212.OBS24751/affaire-matzneff-perquisition-chez-gallimard-l-enquete-s-oriente-vers-son-editeur-et-compagnon-de-voyage.html</ref>\n\nMatzneff was the winner of the Mottard and Amic awards from the [[Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]] in 1987 and 2009 respectively,{{cn|date=January 2020}} the [[Prix Renaudot]] for best essay in 2013<ref name=prix-renaudot/> and the Prix Cazes in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Alice de La|last1=Pradelle|accessdate=2020-01-21|title=Gabriel Matzneff re\u00e7oit le Prix Cazes|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/livres/2015/04/07/03005-20150407ARTFIG00284-gabriel-matzneff-recoit-le-prix-cazes.php|date=7 April 2015|website=Le Figaro.fr|trans-title=Gabriel Matzneff receives the Prix Cazes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115013205/https://www.lefigaro.fr/livres/2015/04/07/03005-20150407ARTFIG00284-gabriel-matzneff-recoit-le-prix-cazes.php|archive-date=15 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Pedophilia===\n\nDespite describing acts of [[pedophilia]] in his books, Matzneff remained sheltered from any criminal prosecution for a long time and benefited from a large support within the literary world.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51133850|title=When sexual abuse was called seduction: France confronts its past|first=Hugh|last=Schofield|author-link=Hugh Schofield|website=[[BBC News]]|date=January 19, 2020|access-date=January 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200120113140/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51133850|archive-date=January 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> At the end of 2019 one of his former victims, {{ill|Vanessa Springora|fr}} &mdash; the director of [[\u00c9ditions Julliard]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/27/french-publishing-boss-claims-she-was-groomed-at-age-14-by-acclaimed-author|title=French publishing boss claims she was groomed at age 14 by acclaimed author|first=Angelique|last=Chrisafis|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=December 28, 2019|access-date=January 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108184437/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/27/french-publishing-boss-claims-she-was-groomed-at-age-14-by-acclaimed-author|archive-date=January 8, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\u2014published the book ''Le Consentement'' describing the effect that Matzneff had on her at the age of 14. Her book unleashed an intense controversy over the tolerance of the literary milieu towards an assumed pedophile. This controversy first led [[\u00c9ditions Gallimard]] to withdraw their marketing services for some of his works, in particular ''Carnets noirs'' and ''Les Moins de seize ans'', with other publishers to follow.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/jan/10/matzneff-scandal-france-consent-literary-establishment|title=The Matzneff scandal shows France\u2019s attitude to consent is finally starting to change|first=Natasha|last=Lehrer|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=January 10, 2020|author-link=Natasha Lehrer|access-date=January 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115233817/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/jan/10/matzneff-scandal-france-consent-literary-establishment|archive-date=January 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMatzneff's diary ''Un Galop d\u2019Enfer'', published in 1985, read that whilst in the [[Philippines]] he would regularly have sex with underage boys. He wrote that \u201cSometimes, I\u2019ll have as many as four boys \u2014 from 8 to 14 years old \u2014 in my bed at the same time, and I\u2019ll engage in the most exquisite lovemaking with them\u201d.<ref name=nytimesonishi/>\n\n==Work==\n===Diaries===\nThe original title of the series, until 2009, was \"Journal\" , both in editions of the Round Table, from 1976 to 1991, and in Gallimard editions, from 1990 to 2007. According to the general catalog of the National Library from France, from 2009, with the publication by \u00c9ditions L\u00e9o Scheer, the overall title was changed to: ''Carnets noirs'' (\"Black Notebooks\").<ref name=\"BNF_journal\">[http://catalogue.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb343069518/PUBLIC Notice de collection ou de s\u00e9rie {{n\u00b0}}FRBNF34306951], dans le catalogue g\u00e9n\u00e9ral de la [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]].</ref>\n\n;Black Notebooks\n* {{citation|title=Cette camisole de flammes: 1953-1962|lang=fr|trans-title=This flaming camisole|publisher=[[\u00c9ditions de la Table ronde]]|publication-place=Paris|date=1976|p=262|id={{BNF|34557030f}}}}\n* {{citation|title=L'Archange aux pieds fourchus : 1963-1964|lang=fr|trans-title=The Archangel with Forked Feet: 1963-1964|publisher=\u00c9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1982| p=233|isbn=2-7103-0133-4|id={{BNF|34737851j}}}}\n* {{citation|title=V\u00e9nus et Junon : 1965-1969|lang=fr|trans-title=Venus and Juno: 1965-1969|publisher=\u00c9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1979|p=307|isbn=2-7103-0012-5|id={{BNF|34636949v}}}}\n* {{citation|title=\u00c9lie et Pha\u00e9ton : 1970-1973|lang=fr|trans-title=Elijah and Phaeton: 1970-1973|publisher=\u00c9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1991|p=386|isbn=2-7103-0470-8|id={{BNF|35414867d}}}}\n* {{citation|title=La Passion Francesca : 1974-1976|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|series=L'infini|publication-place=Paris|date=1998|p=339|isbn=978-2-07-075221-8|id={{BNF|36703098p}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Un galop d'enfer : 1977-1978|lang=fr|trans-title=A gallop from hell: 1977-1978|publisher=\u00c9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1985|p=294|isbn=2-7103-0250-0|id={{BNF|34871681g}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Les Soleils r\u00e9volus : 1979-1982|lang=fr|trans-title=The Suns Completed: 1979-1982|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|series=L'infini|publication-place=Paris|date=2001|p=544|isbn=978-2-07-076027-5|id={{BNF|372216856}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Mes amours d\u00e9compos\u00e9s : 1983-1984|lang=fr|trans-title=My broken down loves: 1983-1984|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|series=L'infini|publication-place=Paris|date=1990|p=381|isbn=978-2-07-071802-3|id={{BNF|35067165v}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Calamity Gab : janvier 1985 \u2013 avril 1986|lang=fr|trans-title=Calamity Gab: January 1985 - April 1986|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|work=L'infini|publication-place=Paris|date=2004|p=361|isbn=978-2070732654|id={{BNF|391539559}}}}\n* {{citation|title=La Prunelle de mes yeux : 1986-1987|lang=fr|trans-title=Apple of my eye: 1986-1987|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|series=L'infini|publication-place=Paris|date=1993|p=337|isbn=978-2-07-073174-9|id={{BNF|356015132}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Les Demoiselles du Taranne : journal 1988|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|series=L'infini|publication-place=Paris|date=2007|p=396|isbn=978-2-07-078399-1|id={{BNF|41004733g}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Carnets noirs 2007-2008|lang=fr|trans-title=Black Notebooks 2007-2008|publisher=[[\u00c9ditions L\u00e9o Scheer]]|publication-place=Paris|date=2009|p=512|isbn=978-2756101811|id={{BNF|41442267f}}}}\n\n;Journal\n* {{citation|title=Mais la musique soudain s'est tue : Journal 2009-2013|lang=fr|trans-title=But the music suddenly fell silent: Journal 2009-2013|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|work=Blanche|publication-place=Paris|date=2015|p=528|isbn=978-2-07-014542-3}}\n* {{citation|title=La Jeune Moabite : Journal 2013-2016|lang=fr|trans-title=Young Moabite: Journal 2013-2016|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|series=Blanche|publication-place=Paris|date=2017|p=702|isbn=978-2-07-273267-6}}\n* {{citation|title=L\u2019Amante de l\u2019Arsenal : Journal 2016-2018|lang=fr|trans-title=Lover of the Arsenal: Journal 2016-2018|publisher=\u00c9ditions Gallimard|series==Blanche|publication-place=Paris|date=2019|p=432|isbn=978-2-07-285442-2}}\n\n===Novels===\nGabriel Matzneff is the author of several novels with the same hero, Nil Kolytcheff. These are: ''Isa\u00efe r\u00e9jouis-toi'', ''Ivre du vin perdu'', ''Harrison Plaza'', ''Mamma, li Turchi!'', ''Voici venir le fianc\u00e9'', ''La Lettre au capitaine Brunner''.\n\n* {{citation|title=L'Archimandrite|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1966|pages=222|isbn=2-7103-00427|id={{BNF|40090166j}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Nous n'irons plus au Luxembourg|lang=fr|trans-title=We will no longer go to Luxembourg|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1972|edition=1st|pages=245|id={{BNF|35213179w}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Isa\u00efe r\u00e9jouis-toi|lang=fr|trans-title=Isaiah rejoice|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1974|p=251}} {{BNF|352146127}}\n* {{citation|title=Ivre du vin perdu|lang=fr|trans-title=Drunk on lost wine|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1981|p=323|isbn=2-7103-0065-6}} {{BNF|346611419}}\n* {{citation|title=Harrison Plaza|lang=fr|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1988|p=235|isbn=2-7103-0352-3}} {{BNF|349382059}}\n* {{citation|title=Les L\u00e8vres menteuses|lang=fr|trans-title=Lying lips|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1992|p=7|isbn=2-7103-0527-5}} {{BNF|35525394j}}\n* {{citation|title=Les Aventures de Nil Kolytcheff|trans-title=The Adventures of Nile Kolytcheff|publisher=\u00e9ditions Jean-Claude Latt\u00e8s|lang=fr|work=Les romanesques|publication-place=Paris|date=1994|pages=805|isbn=2-7096-1491-X|id={{BNF|357393226}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Mamma, li Turchi!|lang=it|trans-title=Mother, the Turks!|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=2000|p=271|isbn=2-7103-0984-X|id={{BNF|371198948}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Voici venir le fianc\u00e9|lang=fr|trans-title=Here comes the fiance|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=2006|p=313|isbn=2710327090|id={{BNF|40130100j}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Les \u00c9miles de Gab la Rafale, roman \u00e9lectronique|lang=fr|publication-place=Paris|publisher={{ill|\u00c9ditions L\u00e9o Scheer|fr}}|date=2010|isbn=978-2756102641}}\n* {{citation|title=La Lettre au capitaine Brunner|trans-title=A letter to Captain Brunner|lang=fr|publisher=la Table Ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=2015|p=208|isbn=978-2-7103-7586-9}} - winner of the Cazes-Brasserie Lipp prize, 2015<ref>{{Cite web|first=Agathe|last=Auproux|title=Gabriel Matzneff laur\u00e9at du prix Cazes-Brasserie Lipp|trans-title=Gabriel Matzneff winner of the Cazes-Brasserie Lipp prize|lang=fr|url=http://www.livreshebdo.fr/article/gabriel-matzneff-laureat-du-prix-cazes-brasserie-lipp|work=Livres Hebdo|date=8 April 2015|accessdate=2015-04-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413121653/http://www.livreshebdo.fr/article/gabriel-matzneff-laureat-du-prix-cazes-brasserie-lipp|archive-date=13 April 2015|url-status=live}}.</ref>\n\n===Essays===\n* {{citation|title=Le D\u00e9fi|lang=fr|trans-title=The Challenge|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1965}} - {{citation|title=Le D\u00e9fi - Nouvelle \u00e9dition, revue et augment\u00e9e|lang=fr|trans-title=The Challenge - New edition, revised and expanded|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1977|id={{BNF|35001130h}}}}\n* {{citation|title=La Caracole|lang=fr|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1969}}\n* {{citation|title=Les Moins de seize ans|lang=fr|trans-title=The under-sixteen|publisher=\u00e9ditions Julliard|work=Id\u00e9e fixe|publication-place=Paris|date=1974|pages=125|id={{BNF|34559062j}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Les Passions schismatiques|lang=fr|trans-title=Schismatic Passions|publisher=\u00e9ditions Stock|work=Le Monde ouvert|publication-place=Paris|date=1977|pages=160|isbn=2-234-00771-2|id={{BNF|345867642}}}}\n* {{citation|title=La Di\u00e9t\u00e9tique de lord Byron|lang=fr|trans-title=The Dietetics of Lord Byron|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1984|pages=215|isbn=2-7103-0185-7|id={{BNF|34752435d}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Le Sabre de Didi : pamphlet|lang=fr|trans-title=Didi's Saber: pamphlet|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1986|pages=266|isbn=2-7103-0298-5|id={{BNF|348777816}}}}. &mdash; This is a revised and expanded edition of ''La Caracole'', a collection of texts from various sources, published between 1963 and 1986\n* {{citation|title=Le Taureau de Phalaris: dictionnaire philosophique|lang=fr|trans-title=The Bull of Phalaris: philosophical dictionary|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1987|pages=300|isbn=2-7103-0313-2|id={{BNF|34908696x}}}} &mdash; reissued in the 1994 collection \"La Petite Vermillon\"\n* {{citation|title=Ma\u00eetres et complices|lang=fr|trans-title=Masters and accomplices|publisher=\u00e9ditions Jean-Claude Latt\u00e8s|publication-place=Paris|date=1994|pages=313|isbn=2-7096-1485-5|id={{BNF|36680568w}}}} &mdash; reissued in the collection \"La Petite Vermillon\"\n* {{citation|title=Le D\u00eener des mousquetaires|lang=fr|trans-title=The Musketeers' Dinner|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1995|pages=408|isbn=2-7103-0686-7|id={{BNF|357894722}}}}. &mdash; a collection of articles from various sources, published between 1961 and 1993\n* {{citation|title=De la rupture|lang=fr|trans-title=Break up|publisher=\u00e9ditions Payot & Rivages|work=Manuels Payot|publication-place=Paris|date=1997|pages=167|isbn=2-228-89070-7|id={{BNF|35860367s}}}}\n* {{citation|title=C'est la gloire, Pierre-Fran\u00e7ois !|lang=fr|trans-title=It's glory, Pierre-Fran\u00e7ois!|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=2002|pages=284|isbn=2-7103-2479-2|id={{BNF|388062554}}}} &mdash; a collection of texts from various sources, published between 1962 and 2001\n* {{citation|title=Yogourt et yoga|lang=fr|trans-title=Yogurt and yoga|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|work=Vermillon|publication-place=Paris|date=2004|pages=267|isbn=978-2-7103-2671-7|id={{BNF|39140535n}}}} &mdash; a collection of texts, from various sources, published between 1962 and 2003\n* {{citation|title=Vous avez dit m\u00e9t\u00e8que ?|lang=fr|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=2008|pages=415|isbn=978-2-7103-3087-5|id={{BNF|41362523w}}}} & mdash; a collection of 107 articles published between 1958 and 2007\n* {{citation|title=La S\u00e9quence de l'\u00e9nergum\u00e8ne|lang=fr|trans-title=The Sequence of a madman|publisher=\u00e9ditions L\u00e9o Sheer|date=2012|pages=340|isbn=2-7561-0360-8}} - chronicles appearances on television shows in the 1960s\n* {{citation|title=S\u00e9raphin c'est la fin !|lang=fr|trans-title=The end of the Seraphin!|publication-place=Paris|publisher=La Table Ronde|date=2013|pages=266|isbn=978-2-7103-7006-2}} &mdash; winner of the  [[Prix Renaudot|Renaudot Prize for essays]], 2013<ref name=prix-renaudot>{{cite news|url=http://www.lepoint.fr/livres/gabriel-matzneff-remporte-le-renaudot-essai-pour-seraphin-c-est-la-fin-04-11-2013-1751783_37.php|publisher=Le Point|title=Gabriel Matzneff remporte le Renaudot essai pour \"S\u00e9raphin, c'est la fin !\"|lang=fr|trans-title=Gabriel Matzneff wins the Renaudot essay for '' S\u00e9raphin, c'est la fin! ''|date=November 4, 2013|access-date=January 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216093333/https://www.lepoint.fr/livres/gabriel-matzneff-remporte-le-renaudot-essai-pour-seraphin-c-est-la-fin-04-11-2013-1751783_37.php|archive-date=February 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* {{citation|title=Un diable dans le b\u00e9nitier|lang=fr|trans-title=A devil in the [[stoup]]|publisher=[[\u00c9ditions Stock]]|publication-place=Paris|date=2017|pages=380|isbn=978-2-234-08254-0}}\n\n===Stories===\n* {{citation|title=Le Carnet arabe|lang=fr|trans-title=The Arab Notebook|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1971|pages=231|id={{BNF|35173361f}}}} &mdash; reissued in the collection \"La Petite Vermillon\"\n* {{citation|title=Comme le feu m\u00eal\u00e9 d'aromates : r\u00e9cit|lang=fr|trans-title=Like fire mixed with aromatics: story|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=1989|pages=176|isbn=2-7103-1168-2|id={{BNF|35001130h}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Boulevard Saint-Germain|lang=fr|publisher=\u00e9ditions du Rocher|work=La fantaisie du voyageur|publication-place=Monaco and Paris|date=1998|pages=194|isbn=2-268-03059-8|id={{BNF|37069451r}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Monsieur le comte monte en ballon|lang=fr|trans-title=The Count goes up in a balloon|publication-place=Paris|publisher=\u00c9ditions L\u00e9o Scheer|date=2012|pages=72|isbn=978-2-7561-0387-7}}\n\n===Poetry===\n* The 37th edition of the journal ''Recherches'', edited by F\u00e9lix Guattari, contains a poem by Gabriel Matzneff in his dossier ''Fous d'enfance : qui a peur des p\u00e9dophiles ?'' (which in English is \"Crazy about childhood: who is afraid of pedophiles?\") Other contributors: [[Luc Rosenzweig]], Gilbert Villerot, Jean-Luc Hennig, [[Ren\u00e9 Sch\u00e9rer]], [[Bernard Faucon]], [[Guy Hocquenghem]]...), \u00c9ditions Recherches, 1979.\n* {{citation|title=Douze po\u00e8mes pour Francesca|lang=fr|trans-title=Twelve poems for Francesca|publisher=\u00e9ditions A. Eibel|work=Lettres 5|publication-place=[[Lausanne]]|date=1977|pages=41|isbn=2-8274-0010-3|id={{BNF|346022062}}}}\n* {{citation|title=Super Flumina Babylonis : po\u00e8mes|lang=fr|trans-title=By the rivers of Bablyon &mdash; poems|publisher=\u00e9ditions de la Table ronde|publication-place=Paris|date=2000|pages=97|isbn=2-7103-0959-9|id={{BNF|37111035m}}}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Matzneff, Gabriel}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:French writers]]\n[[Category:French people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:Modern pederasty]]\n[[Category:Pedophile activism]]\n", "name_user": "Verademillo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFamily, youth and education", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gabriel_Matzneff"}
{"title_page": "Immigration to Singapore", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n'''Immigration to Singapore''' is historically the main impetus for population growth in the country since the founding of modern Singapore in the early 19th century. Immigration and immigrant workers in [[Singapore]] have been closely associated with [[Economy of Singapore|Singapore's economic]] [[Economic development|development]]. For a long period after its founding, the majority of Singapore's population were immigrants. It was not until around the 1930s that the number of native births in Singapore would overtake net immigration. After [[Singapore in Malaysia#Expulsion|its expulsion from Malaysia in 1965]], immigration laws were modified in 1966 to reinforce Singapore's identity as a [[sovereign state]]. However, the initial strict controls on immigrant workers were relaxed as demand for [[Labour (economics)|labour]] grew with increased [[industrialisation]].  Immigration would again become the largest contributor to population increase in Singapore in the late 20th century and early 21st century.\n\nThe [[Immigration and Checkpoints Authority]] publishes a number of criteria for eligibility for permanent residence.<ref>[https://www.ica.gov.sg/apply/PR/apply_PR_who ICA - Becoming a permanent resident]</ref> In colonial times, British merchants and others moved to Singapore and helped develop the region. The large flow of migrants into Singapore in more recent times however has raised concerns and curbs on immigration have been introduced.<ref name=\"ST 2015\"/>\n\n==History==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; text-align:center; margin:1em;\"\n|-\n|+ '''Population growth and immigration in selected periods'''<ref name=\"saw2\"/>\n|-\n!style=\"width:6em;\"| Period\n!style=\"width:7em;\"| Population increase\n!style=\"width:7em;\"| Natural Increase\n!style=\"width:7em;\"| Net Immigration\n|-\n|align=left|1881\u20131891\n| 43,857\n| \u221230,932{{ref|11|A}}\n| 74,798\n|-\n|align=left|1901\u20131911\n| 75,729\n| \u221259,978{{ref|11|A}}\n| 135,707\n|-\n|align=left|1921\u20131931\n| 139,387\n| 18,176\n| 212,211\n|-\n|align=left|1947\u20131957\n| 507,800\n| 395,600\n| 112,200\n|-\n|align=left|1970\u20131980\n| 339,400\n| 315,400\n| 24,000\n|-\n|align=left|1990\u20132000\n| 970,601\n| 330,030\n| 640,571\n|-\n|colspan=4|\n*<small>{{note|11|A}} Negative figures are due to low birth rate and high death rate</small>\n|}\n\n===Early immigration===\nEarly population figures show that, for a long period, the growth of population in Singapore was fuelled by immigration that started soon after [[Stamford Raffles]] landed in Singapore in 1819.  The founding of colonial Singapore as a free port led to a rapid influx of people, initially mostly Malays, quickly followed by Chinese. It was estimated that when Raffles arrived in Singapore on January 1819, Singapore had about 120 Malays, 30 Chinese and some local tribes such as the [[Orang Laut]]. Another estimate put the total population of Singapore at 1,000, mostly of various local tribes.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=1utb8ZYyUeQC&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Singapore in the Malay World: Building and Breaching Regional Bridges|authors= Lily Zubaidah Rahim, Lily Zubaidah Rahim |page=24 |publisher= Taylor & Francis |isbn= 9781134013975 }}</ref>  By 1821, the population was estimated to have increased to 4,724 Malays and 1,150 Chinese.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dD2qVu8EpdUC&pg=PA7#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=The Population of Singapore |edition=3rd |author= Saw Swee-Hock | publisher=ISEAS Publishing|date=30 June 2012|isbn= 978-9814380980 |page=7&ndash;8}}</ref> [[Javanese people|Javanese]], [[Bugis]] and [[Balinese people|Balinese]] also began to arrive. In the first census of 1824, out of the 10,683 total, 6,505 were Malays and Bugis constituting over 60% of the population. The total population of Singapore then increased to 16,000 by 1829, 26,000 five years later, and 60,000 by the beginning of 1850.\n\nChinese migrants started to enter Singapore from the Straits area and southern China to trade just months after it became a British settlement.  Later migrant workers from China would also increase considerably to work on the pepper and [[Uncaria gambir|gambier]] plantations, with 11,000 recorded in one year.<ref name=\"sanderson\"/> Indian migrants also arrived, mostly from [[Bengal]] and the [[Coromandel Coast]]. Singapore became one of the entry and dispersal points for a large number of Chinese and Indian migrants who came to work in the plantations and mines of the Straits Settlements, some of whom then settled in Singapore after their contracts ended.  By 1860, the total population had reached around 90,000, of these 50,000 were Chinese, and 2,445 Europeans and Eurasians.  The first thorough census in Singapore was undertaken in 1871, and it showed that Chinese were the largest ethnic group at 57.6%.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=wVyqbmHS2zQC&pg=PA18#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Rickshaw Coolie: A People's History of Singapore, 1880-1940 |author= James Francis Warren|page=18 |publisher=NUS Press |date=30 June 2003|isbn=978-9971692667 }}</ref>  In 1901, the total population of Singapore was 228,555,<ref name=\"sanderson\">{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924023134368#page/n227/mode/2up |editors=Wright, Arnold and Cartwright, H.A. |author=Mrs Reginald Sanderson|date= 1907|title=Twentieth century impressions of British Malaya: its history, people, commerce, industries, and resources |pages=220\u2013221 }}</ref> with 15.8% Malays, 71.8% Chinese, 7.8% Indians, and 3.5% Europeans and Eurasians. The Chinese population of Singapore has stayed at over 70% of the total ever since.\n\nThe early population figures show that Chinese immigrants of the period were overwhelmingly male. The 1826 figures give a total population of 13,750, with 5,747 Chinese males and only 341 Chinese females, compared to 2,501 Malay males and 2,289 Malay females.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924023134368#page/n43/mode/2up |editors=Wright, Arnold and Cartwright, H.A. |date= 1907|title=Twentieth century impressions of British Malaya: its history, people, commerce, industries, and resources |page=37 }}</ref> The sex ratio of Indian migrants was similarly distorted.  The imbalance of the sexes of the immigrant communities continued for a long time with the continual flow into Singapore of male migrant workers who were either single or had left their wives and children behind in China or India, for example the 1901 census figures show that there were 130,367 Chinese males and 33,674 Chinese females.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924030396067#page/n189/mode/2up/search/singapore |title=Census of the British empire. 1901|page=123 |date=1906 |work=Great Britain Census Office}}</ref>  Most of the early Chinese immigrants did not intend to settle permanently to raise their families there; they worked to send money back home, and many would return to China after they had earned enough money. For over a hundred years, the great proportion of the Chinese in Singapore were immigrants \u2013 by the late 1890s only around 10% of the Chinese population were native-born in Singapore.  Later an increasing number would also choose to settle permanently in Singapore, especially in the 1920s when more chose to remain in Singapore rather than leave.<ref name=\"warren\"/> Change in social attitude in the modern era also meant that Chinese women were freer to emigrate from China, and the sex ratio began to normalise in the 20th century, which led to a much greater number of people being born in Singapore.<ref name=\"jstor1\"/> Immigration continued to be the main reason for the Chinese population increase in Singapore until the 1931&ndash;1947 period when the natural increase in population surpassed the net immigration figure.<ref name=\"warren\">{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=wVyqbmHS2zQC&pg=PA19#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Rickshaw Coolie: A People's History of Singapore, 1880-1940 |author= James Francis Warren|page=19 |publisher=NUS Press |date=30 June 2003|isbn=978-9971692667 }}</ref><ref name=\"saw\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dD2qVu8EpdUC&pg=PA12#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=The Population of Singapore |edition=3rd |author= Saw Swee-Hock | publisher=ISEAS Publishing|date=30 June 2012|isbn= 978-9814380980 |pages=11\u201312}}</ref>\n\nImmigration from China and India to Singapore stopped during the years of [[Japanese occupation of Singapore|Japanese occupation]].<ref name=\"saw\"/> After the [[Second World War]], the immigration pattern shifted from the influx of migrants from other countries to movement of people between peninsular Malaya and Singapore, with a significant number of net migrants moving from Malaya to Singapore. However, after the declaration of independence of [[Federation of Malaya|Malaya]] in 1957, the migration of people from Malaya began to fall.<ref name=\"jstor1\">{{cite journal |jstor=20067730 |title=Population Trends in Singapore, 1819-1967 |author=Saw Swee-Hock|journal=Journal of Southeast Asian History|volume= 10|issue= 1|date= March 1969|pages= 36\u201349 }}</ref>\n\n===Post-independence immigration===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; text-align:center; width:120px; margin:1em;\"\n|+ Population size and growth by residential status in selected years<ref>[http://www.singstat.gov.sg/pubn/popn/population2012b.pdf Population Trends 2012] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113152420/http://www.singstat.gov.sg/pubn/popn/population2012b.pdf |date=13 November 2012 }} ''Department of Statistics, Singapore''.</ref>\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year || colspan=\"3\" | Number (thousands) || colspan=\"3\" | Growth\n|-\n! Total population || Permanent Residents || Non-residents || Total population || Permanent Residents || Non-residents\n|-\n| 1990 || 3,047.10 || 112.1 || 311.3 || 1.70% || 2.30% || 9.00%\n|-\n| 2000 || 4,027.90 || 287.5 || 754.5 || 1.80% || 9.90% || 9.30%\n|-\n| 2006 || 4,401.40 || 418 || 875.5 || 1.70% || 8.10% || 9.70%\n|-\n| 2008 || 4,839.40 || 478.2 || 1,196.70 || 1.70% || 6.50% || 19.00% \n|-\n| 2010 || 5,076.70 || 541 || 1,305.00 || 1.00% || 1.50% || 4.10%\n|-\n| 2012 || 5,312.40 || 533.1 || 1,494.20 || 0.80% || 0.20% || 7.20%\n|}\nWhen Singapore became an independent nation in 1965, it signalled the end of free movement of people between Malaysia and Singapore. This and increasing job opportunities in Malaysia meant that the previous high level of movement of people between the two countries fell significantly. Net migration in Singapore dropped to 24,000 in the decade of 1970-80 due to tighter control of immigration from Malaysia and other countries. However, a lower rate of natural growth in population and the need for low-skill labour resulted in a deliberate shift in policy by the Singapore government to allow more foreigners to live and work in the country, and net migration increased in the 1980-1990 period to nearly 200,000. By the decade of 1990-2000, the net migrant number of over 600,000 had surpassed the natural growth of the population, and accounted for nearly two-third of the population increase.  The same high level of immigration is also seen in the next decade with 664,083 net migration recorded.<ref name=\"saw2\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dD2qVu8EpdUC&pg=PA14#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=The Population of Singapore |edition=3rd |author= Saw Swee-Hock | publisher=ISEAS Publishing|date=30 June 2012|isbn= 978-9814380980 |pages=11&ndash;18}}</ref>  Curbs on immigration however began to be implemented in the 2010s to ease increasing social issues arising from the high level of immigration.<ref name=\"ST 2015\">{{cite news |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/no-easy-choices-on-foreign-worker-immigrant-policies-pm-lee |title=No easy choices on foreign worker, immigrant policies: PM Lee |date= 3 August 2015 |work=The Straits Times |author=Rachel Chang}}</ref>\n\nThe high level of foreign migrant workers in late 20th and early 21st centuries meant that Singapore has one of the highest percentages of foreigners in the world. By the middle of the 2010s, nearly 40% of the population were estimated to be of foreign origin; although many have become permanent residents, most of them were non-citizens made up of foreign students and workers including dependants.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.expatfocus.com/c/aid=2514/articles/general/these-five-countries-have-the-highest-percentage-of-expats-find-out-why/ |title=These Five Countries Have The Highest Percentage Of Expats: Find Out Why |work=ExpatFocus |date= December 10, 2015 }}</ref>  Between 1970 and 1980, the size of the non-resident population in Singapore doubled. The numbers began to increase greatly from 1980 to 2010. Foreigners constituted 28.1% of Singapore's total [[labour force]] in 2000, to 34.7% in 2010,<ref name=\"yeoh 2012\">{{cite web |url=http://www.migrationpolicy.org/article/rapid-growth-singapores-immigrant-population-brings-policy-challenges |title=Rapid Growth in Singapore's Immigrant Population Brings Policy Challenges |date=April 3, 2012|authors= Brenda Yeoh and Weiqiang Lin |work=Migration Policy Institute }}</ref> which is the highest proportion of [[foreign worker]]s in Asia.  Singapore's non-resident workforce increased 170% from 248,000 in 1990 to 670,000 in 2006 (Yeoh 2007). By 2010, the non-resident workforce had reached nearly 1.09 million, of these 870,000 were low-[[Skill (labor)|skilled]] foreign workers in Singapore; another 240,000 were skilled foreign worker, better-educated S-pass or employment pass holders. Malaysia is the main source of immigrants in Singapore (386,000 in 2010), followed by China, Hong Kong, and Macau, then South Asia, Indonesia, and other Asian countries.<ref name=\"yeoh 2012\"/>  As of June 2014, the total population of Singapore stands at 5.47 million:  3.34 million citizens and 0.53 million permanent residents (total resident number 3.87 million), with 1.60 million non-residents with work passes and foreign students.<ref>{{cite web|title=Total population of Singapore as on June 2014|url=http://www.nptd.gov.sg/portals/0/homepage/highlights/population-in-brief-2014.pdf|accessdate=22 February 2015| work=National Population and Talent Division NPTD |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141211034148/http://www.nptd.gov.sg/portals/0/homepage/highlights/population-in-brief-2014.pdf |archivedate=11 December 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Policy==\nIn Singapore, the term ''immigrant workers'' is separated into ''foreign workers'' and ''foreign talents''. ''Foreign workers'' refers to semi-[[Skill (labor)|skilled]] or unskilled workers who mainly work in the manufacturing, construction, and [[domestic service]]s sectors. The majority of them come from places such as People's Republic of China,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clb.org.hk/en/node/100977 |title=Hired on Sufferance: China\u2019s migrant workers in Singapore |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727232521/http://www.clb.org.hk/en/node/100977 |archivedate=27 July 2011 |work=Chinese Labour Bulletin |date=10 February 2011}}</ref> Indonesia, India, Bangladesh, Pakistan, Myanmar, Sri Lanka, the Philippines, and Thailand, as part of bilateral agreements between Singapore and these countries. ''Foreign talent'' refers to foreigners with professional qualifications or acceptable degrees working at the higher end of Singapore's economy. They mostly come from India, Australia, the Philippines, People's Republic of China, Taiwan, Hong Kong, Japan, Republic of Korea, Malaysia, Europe, New Zealand, United Kingdom and the United States.\n\nIn September 1998 the [[Government of Singapore|Singaporean government]] first constructed a system under which different types of employment passes (EP) are issued to immigrant workers according to their qualifications and monthly salaries. The \"P, Q, R\" employment pass system was put into practice in September 1998; a new \"S\" type employment pass was later introduced in July 2004. The government has also set different policies on recruiting foreign talents and foreign workers.\n\nIn 2014, the Ministry of Manpower did away with their pass type category, however, the criteria remains the same.  From 1 January 2017, new EP applicants will have to earn a fixed monthly salary of $3,600 or more, depending on their qualifications and experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mom.gov.sg/passes-and-permits/employment-pass/eligibility |title=Eligibility for Employment Pass|work=Ministry of Manpower}}</ref>\n\nThe different policies towards 'Foreign workers' and 'Foreign talent' in Singapore have led some people to feel that their contributions toward Singapore's development are valued differently. However, the Singapore government has always stressed the importance of immigrant workers to [[Economy of Singapore|Singapore's economy]] and development. [[Senior Minister]] [[Goh Chok Tong]], then [[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]], said in his 1997 [[National Day]] rally speech that the government's lack of restrictions on the recruitment of foreigners did not extend only to top-rung prestigious positions, but also to middle-level management, skilled worker and technician positions.{{sfn|Low|2002}}\n\n===Foreign talent===\nVarious policies and incentives are used to attract foreign talent to Singapore. CONTACT SINGAPORE was launched in 1997 by the International Talent Division of the [[Ministry of Manpower (Singapore)|Ministry of Manpower]], beginning with six offices worldwide, to facilitate the inflow of international talent to Singapore.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nathan|first1=Dominic|title=New global drive starts, to attract foreign talent.|work=Straits Times|date=31 July 1997}}</ref> The Singapore Talent Recruitment (STAR) Committee was formed in November 1998 with the aim of attracting foreign talents to Singapore. Other similar programmes include Manpower 21,<ref>{{cite news|title=Singapore seeks foreign workers|work=International Business Asia|publisher=Factiva|date=13 September 1999}}</ref> launched in 1999, and the International Manpower Program of the [[Economic Development Board]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ristelhueber|first1=Robert|title=HQ Singapore|work=Electronic Business|issue=3 (Vol 24)|publisher=Gale Group|date=1 March 1998}}</ref> The government has developed the Scheme for Housing of Foreign Talents with the aim of providing affordable yet comfortable accommodations for foreign talents, to attract them to work and stay in Singapore.{{sfn|Low|2002}}\n\n===Foreign workers===\nOn the other hand, stringent policies and regulations have been set on employing foreign workers. In 1981, the government even announced its intention to phase out all unskilled foreign workers by the end of 1991, except domestic maids and those employed in construction and [[shipyard]]s. The policy stance was met with strong protests from employers facing [[labour shortage]]s.{{sfn|Athukorala|Manning|1999}}\n\nIn April 1987, the Singapore government announced its [[immigration policy]], which intended to control the foreign worker inflow. The two key elements in the policy were a monthly levy payable by the employer for each foreign worker employed, and a \"dependency ceiling\" that limits the proportion of foreign workers in the total workforce of any one employer. The government later introduced a two-tier levy system in October 1991 under which employers were required to pay a higher levy on workers whose employment would change the \"dependent ceiling\" value of the company.{{sfn|Athukorala|Manning|1999}}  The levy and the \"dependency ceiling\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Changes To Foreign Workers Levy 2015|url=http://aesperoncoretrade.com/bca-coretrade-levy/|publisher=Aesperon - Changes to Foreign Workers Levy and Quota in 2015|accessdate=1 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150811180940/http://aesperoncoretrade.com/bca-coretrade-levy/|archivedate=11 August 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> have remained the two instruments with which the government has regulated worker inflow in line with changes in domestic [[Labour economics|labour-market]] conditions.{{sfn|Athukorala|Manning|1999}}\n\n*[http://www.aseanhrmech.org/downloads/singapore-Immigration_Act_Of_Singapore.pdf Immigration Act]\n\nNon-residents working in Singapore will require a work visa. There are various types of Singapore work visas starting from work permits for the lower-skilled labourers, to P1 and P2 category Employment Passes to attract niche professionals with good credentials in both education and work experience.\n\nFrom 1 September 2012 only foreign workers with earnings of at least SGD4,000 (USD3,150) per month can sponsor their spouses and children for their stay in Singapore and some of them are also not allowed to bring their parents and in-laws on long-term visit passes. The new regulation also impacts those who switch companies on/after the date, but foreign workers whose families are already in Singapore won't be affected. The increase from SGD2,800 to SGD4,000 was to ease public disquiet over the influx of workers from overseas.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-07-09/singapore-tightens-rules-for-foreign-workers-families.html |title=Singapore Tightens Rules for Foreign Workers' Families |date=10 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, there were over 1,268,300 foreign workers employed in Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.universal.sg/immigration-and-domestic-workers-of-singapore |title=Immigration and Domestic Workers of Singapore |access-date=16 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180209021807/http://www.universal.sg/immigration-and-domestic-workers-of-singapore |archive-date=9 February 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===2013 Population White Paper===\n{{main|Population White Paper}}\nIn early 2013, the [[Parliament of Singapore|Singapore parliament]] debated over the policies recommended by the Population White Paper entitled ''A Sustainable Population for a Dynamic Singapore''. Citing that Singapore's 900,000 Baby Boomers would comprise a quarter of the citizen population by 2030 and that its workforce would shrink \"from 2020 onward\", the White Paper projected that by 2030, Singapore's \"total population could range between 6.5 and 6.9 million\", with resident population between 4.2 and 4.4 million and citizen population between 3.6 and 3.8 million. The White Paper called for an increase in the number of foreign workers so as to provide balance between the number of skilled and less-skilled workers, as well as provide healthcare and domestic services. It also claimed that foreign workers help businesses thrive when the economy is good.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130218092002/http://202.157.171.46/whitepaper/downloads/population-white-paper.pdf ''A Sustainable Population for a Dynamic Singapore''.]</ref> The motion was passed<ref>[http://www.straitstimes.com/microsites/parliament/story/amended-motion-white-paper-adopted-69-million-not-target-20130209 Amended motion on white paper adopted; 6.9 million is not a target.] ''The Straits Times''. 9 February 2013.</ref> albeit after amendments made to leave out \"population policy\" and add focus on infrastructure and transport development.\n\nThe White Paper was criticised by opposition parties.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wp.sg:80/wp-population-policy-paper/ |title=The Workers\u2019 Party\u2019s Population Policy Paper: \"A Dynamic Population for a Sustainable Singapore\" ''The Workers' Party'' |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130228143717/http://wp.sg/wp-population-policy-paper/ |archivedate=28 February 2013 |author=Low Thia Khiang |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Member of Parliament [[Low Thia Khiang]] of the [[Workers' Party of Singapore]] had criticised current measures of increasing the fertility rate, claiming that the high cost of living and lack of family and social support discouraged young couples from having babies. As for current immigration policies, he had noted that immigrants were a source of friction for Singaporeans and that an increased population would put more stress on the already strained urban infrastructure.<ref>[http://wp.sg/2013/02/a-sustainable-singapore-with-a-dynamic-singaporean-majority-mp-low-thia-khiang/ A Sustainable Singapore with a Dynamic Singaporean majority \u2013 MP Low Thia Khiang] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130315182137/http://wp.sg/2013/02/a-sustainable-singapore-with-a-dynamic-singaporean-majority-mp-low-thia-khiang |date=15 March 2013 }} ''The Workers' Party''.</ref> PAP MP Inderjit Singh had also spoken out on the issue, citing cohesion and social issues that would have been made worse with the proposed immigrant influx rate.On 16 February 2013, nearly 3,000 people rallied to protest the White Paper and raise concerns that the increased population would lead to the deterioration of public service and the increase of the cost of living in the future.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2013/02/17/rare-singapore-protest-against-population-plan.html |title=Rare Singapore protest against population plan |date=17 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130218035052/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2013/02/17/rare-singapore-protest-against-population-plan.html |archivedate=18 February 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Impact and criticism==\nThe large influx of migrants from the 1980s onward has raised concerns about the government's policy on immigration. Whilst the inflow of immigrants and foreign workers have helped to alleviate a labour crunch and help the economy, it has also resulted in strong sentiment by the locals against both foreigners and the government, and was a major issue in both the 2011 [[2011 Singaporean general election|general]] and [[2011 Singaporean presidential election|presidential]] elections.<ref name=\"telegrah\">{{cite news|last=Hyslop|first=Leah|title=Singapore opposition stirs up anti-foreigner sentiment|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/expat/expatnews/8494772/Singapore-opposition-stirs-up-anti-foreigner-sentiment.html|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=The Telegraph (UK)|date=5 May 2011}}</ref> Singaporeans have attributed to the government's open-door immigration policy the country's overcrowding and falling reliability of its public transportation system, increasing property prices for housing, suppressed wage level, increased competition for jobs and education, increasing income inequality and other social problems.<ref name=\"chinapost\">{{cite news|title=Singapore tightens rules for hiring foreigners|url=http://www.chinapost.com.tw/business/asia/singapore/2011/08/17/313605/Singapore-tightens.htm|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=The China Post|date=17 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"tafep\">{{cite news|title=Job bias against Singaporeans the top complaint|url=http://business.asiaone.com/Business/News/Office/Story/A1Story20120419-340668.html|accessdate=20 April 2012|last=Boh|first=Samantha|newspaper=my paper|date=19 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121202052258/http://business.asiaone.com/Business/News/Office/Story/A1Story20120419-340668.html|archive-date=2 December 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"asiaoneafp\">{{cite news|title=Singapore to further curb foreign worker inflow|url=http://www.asiaone.com/Business/News/My%2BMoney/Story/A1Story20120217-328618.html|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=AFP|date=17 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221012848/http://www.asiaone.com/Business/News/My+Money/Story/A1Story20120217-328618.html|archive-date=21 February 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"thestarscn1\">{{cite news|last=Seah|first=Chiang Nee|title=Talent buy becomes sore point|url=http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2012/3/24/focus/10969821&sec=focus|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019211757/http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2012%2F3%2F24%2Ffocus%2F10969821&sec=focus|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 October 2012|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=The Star (Malaysia)|date=24 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"cnbc-ac\">{{cite news|first=Leslie|last=Shaffer|title=British banker stirs up storm by mocking Singapore's 'poor'|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/101357276|accessdate=28 January 2014|newspaper=CNBC|date=23 January 2014}}</ref> These issues came under close scrutiny by foreign media in the aftermath of the [[2013 Little India riot]].<ref name=\"littleindiariot\">{{cite news|title=Singapore to Charge Rioters After Little India Violence|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-12-09/lee-clamps-down-on-rioters-after-violence-in-singapore.html|authors=Sharon Chen and Weiyi Lim|accessdate=28 January 2014|newspaper=Bloomberg|date=10 December 2013}}</ref> Local [[Non-governmental organization|NGOs]] have also raised issues of migrant welfare, especially those relating to work injury and living conditions.<ref name=migrant-welfare-cna>{{cite news|last1=Toh|first1=Ee Ming|title=Making Singapore a better place for workers who come from afar|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/making-singapore-a-better/2341718.html|accessdate=4 February 2016|work=Channel NewsAsia|date=12 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Malay|first1=Michael|title=Singapore needs to address its treatment of migrant workers|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development-professionals-network/2014/apr/21/singapore-address-treatment-migrant-workers|accessdate=4 February 2016|work=Guardian|date=21 April 2014}}</ref> Social pressures have been acknowledged by Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong with various measures put in place in the last few years, such as the Fair Employment (Consideration) Framework and Tripartite Alliance for Fair Employment Practices and increasing support for migrant workers.<ref name=migrant-welfare-cna /><ref>{{Cite web|title = 'I owe Singaporeans a responsibility' to get foreign worker balance right: PM Lee|url = http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/i-owe-singaporeans-a/2023914.html|website = Channel NewsAsia|access-date = 2016-01-26}}</ref>\n\nPrime Minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]] and various government agencies have spoken out against a rising anti-foreigner sentiment after Singaporeans expressed outrage at disparaging statements made by foreigners residing in Singapore.<ref name=asiaonesx>{{cite news|title=PM Lee worried about growing divide in Singapore|url=http://news.asiaone.com/print/News/Latest%2BNews/Singapore/Story/A1Story20120405-337897.html|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=AsiaOne|date=5 April 2012}}</ref> For example, in March 2012, Sun Xu, a scholar from China studying in the [[National University of Singapore]], made a remark in his blog that \"there are more dogs than humans in Singapore\".<ref name=asiaonesx /><ref name=stmarch26>{{cite news|last=Jennani|first=Durai|title=Final semester scholarship benefits revoked for China NUS student|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/Singapore/Story/STIStory_781837.html|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=26 March 2012}}</ref> This was weeks after a revelation in parliament that SGD36 million worth of scholarships were awarded to 2,000 foreign students every year, something that is unheard of in other countries.<ref name=thestarscn1 /> The government was accused of disadvantaging local students in places for education and affordability,<ref name=thestarscn1 /> and in response it has made a policy change in primary education to give some priority to Singaporeans.<ref name=thestarp1>{{cite news|title=P1 priority for citizens|url=http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2012/3/27/asia/10994414&sec=asia|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130221023949/http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2012/3/27/asia/10994414&sec=asia|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 February 2013|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=The Star (Malaysia)|date=27 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nFurther incidents have also fanned local sentiments against expatriates and foreign workers in Singapore, for example, the publicity over negative comments about the locals by banker Anton Casey and Filipino nurse Ed Mundsel Bello Ello.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mortlock|first1=Simon|title=How Anton Casey is making life tough for arrogant expat bankers in Singapore|url=https://sg.finance.yahoo.com/news/anton-casey-making-life-tough-000147872.html|accessdate=4 February 2016|publisher=Yahoo! News/Singapore Business Review|date=24 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305002345/https://sg.finance.yahoo.com/news/anton-casey-making-life-tough-000147872.html|archive-date=5 March 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ortiga|first1=Yasmin Y|title=Multiculturalism on Its Head: Unexpected Boundaries and New Migration in Singapore|journal=Journal of International Migration and Integration|date=7 September 2014|volume=16|issue=4|pages=953\u2013954|ref=10.1007/s12134-014-0378-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Diola|first1=Camille|title=Filipino nurse sacked for anti-Singapore comments|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2015/01/12/1412123/filipino-nurse-sacked-anti-singapore-comments|accessdate=7 April 2015|work=Philippine Star|date=12 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=Reuters-ac>{{cite news|last=Leonal|first=Brian|title=Porsche-owning UK expat infuriates Singapore with \"poor people\" gaffes|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/01/23/us-singapore-banker-idUSBREA0M0OJ20140123|accessdate=28 January 2014|newspaper=Reuters|date=23 January 2014}}</ref> In the case of [[Anton Casey]], he had posted comments on Facebook which had abused, variously, a taxi driver and Singaporean commuters in general.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/anton-casey-fired-and-flees-singapore-in-economy-class-over-poor-people-comments-9088199.html|title=Anton Casey fired and flees Singapore in economy class over \"poor|date=2014-01-27|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> Whilst anti-foreigner sentiments are still prevalent online, fifteen foreigners who were interviewed by [[CNA (news channel)|CNA]] did not feel such anti-foreigner sentiments reflected what they encountered in the real world.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Are Singaporeans anti-foreigner? Not in the real world|url = http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/are-singaporeans-anti/1777708.html|website = Channel NewsAsia|access-date = 2016-01-26}}</ref> Local Singaporeans have also written in to the press to encourage fellow Singaporeans to have a mindset of being more accepting towards other cultures, reminding them that Singapore is also from immigrant stock.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Greater cultural integration needed|url = http://www.straitstimes.com/forum/letters-on-the-web/greater-cultural-integration-needed|website = The Straits Times|access-date = 2016-01-26|last = hermesauto}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Let's be a cultural melting pot, not bowl of salad|url = http://www.straitstimes.com/forum/letters-in-print/lets-be-a-cultural-melting-pot-not-bowl-of-salad|website = The Straits Times|access-date = 2016-01-26|last = hermes}}</ref> Media reporting that foreign workers help out in distressed situations have also helped improve locals' perception of foreign workers.<ref name=migrant-welfare-cna />\n\nThere are also concerns that immigrants were using Singapore as a springboard for immigration to other developed countries.<ref name=stnewcitizenrn>{{cite news|last=Tan|first=Amanda|title=300 new citizens give up their status each year|url=http://www.spp.nus.edu.sg/ips/docs/media/yr2012/ST_300%20new%20citizens%20give%20up%20their%20status%20each%20year_020312.pdf|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=2 March 2012}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Every year, 300 naturalised citizens renounce their Singapore citizenship.<ref name=stnewcitizenrn /> Many foreigners remain hesitant to take up [[Permanent residency in Singapore|Permanent Residency]] (PR) or [[Singapore citizenship]] because of the two years of [[Conscription in Singapore|mandatory military service]] for male citizens and second-generation PRs.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Singaporean nationality law]]\n* [[Immigration and Checkpoints Authority]]\n* [[National Registration Identity Card]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book|last1=Athukorala|first1=Prema-Chandra|first2=Chris |last2=Manning|chapter=Hong Kong and Singapore: City-States Shaped by Migrants|title=Structural Change and International Migration in East Asia: Adjusting to Labour Scarcity|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2000|isbn=0-19-554173-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last =Low|first=Linda|title=The Political Economy of Migrant Worker Policy in Singapore|journal=Asia Pacific Business Review|volume=8|issue=4|date=June 2002|pages=95\u2013118|doi=10.1080/713999166 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Library resources about |onlinebooks=no |others=yes}}\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Singapore}}\n{{Asia topic|Immigration to}}\n\n[[Category:Singaporean society]]\n[[Category:Immigration to Singapore| ]]\n[[Category:Foreign workers]]\n[[Category:Economy of Singapore]]\n[[Category:Demographics of Singapore]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n'''Immigration to Singapore''' is historically the main impetus for population growth in the country since the founding of modern Singapore in the early 19th century. Immigration and immigrant workers in [[Singapore]] have been closely associated with [[Economy of Singapore|Singapore's economic]] [[Economic development|development]]. For a long period after its founding, the majority of Singapore's population were immigrants. It was not until around the 1930s that the number of native births in Singapore would overtake net immigration. After [[Singapore in Malaysia#Expulsion|its expulsion from Malaysia in 1965]], immigration laws were modified in 1966 to reinforce Singapore's identity as a [[sovereign state]]. However, the initial strict controls on immigrant workers were relaxed as demand for [[Labour (economics)|labour]] grew with increased [[industrialisation]].  Immigration would again become the largest contributor to population increase in Singapore in the late 20th century and early 21st century.\n\nThe [[Immigration and Checkpoints Authority]] publishes a number of criteria for eligibility for permanent residence.<ref>[https://www.ica.gov.sg/apply/PR/apply_PR_who ICA - Becoming a permanent resident]</ref> In colonial times, British merchants and others moved to Singapore and helped develop the region. The large flow of migrants into Singapore in more recent times however has raised concerns and curbs on immigration have been introduced.<ref name=\"ST 2015\"/>\n\n==History==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; text-align:center; margin:1em;\"\n|-\n|+ '''Population growth and immigration in selected periods'''<ref name=\"saw2\"/>\n|-\n!style=\"width:6em;\"| Period\n!style=\"width:7em;\"| Population increase\n!style=\"width:7em;\"| Natural Increase\n!style=\"width:7em;\"| Net Immigration\n|-\n|align=left|1881\u20131891\n| 43,857\n| \u221230,932{{ref|11|A}}\n| 74,798\n|-\n|align=left|1901\u20131911\n| 75,729\n| \u221259,978{{ref|11|A}}\n| 135,707\n|-\n|align=left|1921\u20131931\n| 139,387\n| 18,176\n| 212,211\n|-\n|align=left|1947\u20131957\n| 507,800\n| 395,600\n| 112,200\n|-\n|align=left|1970\u20131980\n| 339,400\n| 315,400\n| 24,000\n|-\n|align=left|1990\u20132000\n| 970,601\n| 330,030\n| 640,571\n|-\n|colspan=4|\n*<small>{{note|11|A}} Negative figures are due to low birth rate and high death rate</small>\n|}\n\n===Early immigration===\nEarly population figures show that, for a long period, the growth of population in Singapore was fuelled by immigration that started soon after [[Stamford Raffles]] landed in Singapore in 1819.  The founding of colonial Singapore as a free port led to a rapid influx of people, initially mostly Malays, quickly followed by Chinese. It was estimated that when Raffles arrived in Singapore on January 1819, Singapore had about 120 Malays, 30 Chinese and some local tribes such as the [[Orang Laut]]. Another estimate put the total population of Singapore at 1,000, mostly of various local tribes.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=1utb8ZYyUeQC&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Singapore in the Malay World: Building and Breaching Regional Bridges|authors= Lily Zubaidah Rahim, Lily Zubaidah Rahim |page=24 |publisher= Taylor & Francis |isbn= 9781134013975 }}</ref>  By 1821, the population was estimated to have increased to 4,724 Malays and 1,150 Chinese.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dD2qVu8EpdUC&pg=PA7#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=The Population of Singapore |edition=3rd |author= Saw Swee-Hock | publisher=ISEAS Publishing|date=30 June 2012|isbn= 978-9814380980 |page=7&ndash;8}}</ref> [[Javanese people|Javanese]], [[Bugis]] and [[Balinese people|Balinese]] also began to arrive. In the first census of 1824, out of the 10,683 total, 6,505 were Malays and Bugis constituting over 60% of the population. The total population of Singapore then increased to 16,000 by 1829, 26,000 five years later, and 60,000 by the beginning of 1850.\n\nChinese migrants started to enter Singapore from the Straits area and southern China to trade just months after it became a British settlement.  Later migrant workers from China would also increase considerably to work on the pepper and [[Uncaria gambir|gambier]] plantations, with 11,000 recorded in one year.<ref name=\"sanderson\"/> Indian migrants also arrived, mostly from [[Bengal]] and the [[Coromandel Coast]]. Singapore became one of the entry and dispersal points for a large number of Chinese and Indian migrants who came to work in the plantations and mines of the Straits Settlements, some of whom then settled in Singapore after their contracts ended.  By 1860, the total population had reached around 90,000, of these 50,000 were Chinese, and 2,445 Europeans and Eurasians.  The first thorough census in Singapore was undertaken in 1871, and it showed that Chinese were the largest ethnic group at 57.6%.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=wVyqbmHS2zQC&pg=PA18#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Rickshaw Coolie: A People's History of Singapore, 1880-1940 |author= James Francis Warren|page=18 |publisher=NUS Press |date=30 June 2003|isbn=978-9971692667 }}</ref>  In 1901, the total population of Singapore was 228,555,<ref name=\"sanderson\">{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924023134368#page/n227/mode/2up |editors=Wright, Arnold and Cartwright, H.A. |author=Mrs Reginald Sanderson|date= 1907|title=Twentieth century impressions of British Malaya: its history, people, commerce, industries, and resources |pages=220\u2013221 }}</ref> with 15.8% Malays, 71.8% Chinese, 7.8% Indians, and 3.5% Europeans and Eurasians. The Chinese population of Singapore has stayed at over 70% of the total ever since.\n\nThe early population figures show that Chinese immigrants of the period were overwhelmingly male. The 1826 figures give a total population of 13,750, with 5,747 Chinese males and only 341 Chinese females, compared to 2,501 Malay males and 2,289 Malay females.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924023134368#page/n43/mode/2up |editors=Wright, Arnold and Cartwright, H.A. |date= 1907|title=Twentieth century impressions of British Malaya: its history, people, commerce, industries, and resources |page=37 }}</ref> The sex ratio of Indian migrants was similarly distorted.  The imbalance of the sexes of the immigrant communities continued for a long time with the continual flow into Singapore of male migrant workers who were either single or had left their wives and children behind in China or India, for example the 1901 census figures show that there were 130,367 Chinese males and 33,674 Chinese females.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924030396067#page/n189/mode/2up/search/singapore |title=Census of the British empire. 1901|page=123 |date=1906 |work=Great Britain Census Office}}</ref>  Most of the early Chinese immigrants did not intend to settle permanently to raise their families there; they worked to send money back home, and many would return to China after they had earned enough money. For over a hundred years, the great proportion of the Chinese in Singapore were immigrants \u2013 by the late 1890s only around 10% of the Chinese population were native-born in Singapore.  Later an increasing number would also choose to settle permanently in Singapore, especially in the 1920s when more chose to remain in Singapore rather than leave.<ref name=\"warren\"/> Change in social attitude in the modern era also meant that Chinese women were freer to emigrate from China, and the sex ratio began to normalise in the 20th century, which led to a much greater number of people being born in Singapore.<ref name=\"jstor1\"/> Immigration continued to be the main reason for the Chinese population increase in Singapore until the 1931&ndash;1947 period when the natural increase in population surpassed the net immigration figure.<ref name=\"warren\">{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=wVyqbmHS2zQC&pg=PA19#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Rickshaw Coolie: A People's History of Singapore, 1880-1940 |author= James Francis Warren|page=19 |publisher=NUS Press |date=30 June 2003|isbn=978-9971692667 }}</ref><ref name=\"saw\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dD2qVu8EpdUC&pg=PA12#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=The Population of Singapore |edition=3rd |author= Saw Swee-Hock | publisher=ISEAS Publishing|date=30 June 2012|isbn= 978-9814380980 |pages=11\u201312}}</ref>\n\nImmigration from China and India to Singapore stopped during the years of [[Japanese occupation of Singapore|Japanese occupation]].<ref name=\"saw\"/> After the [[Second World War]], the immigration pattern shifted from the influx of migrants from other countries to movement of people between peninsular Malaya and Singapore, with a significant number of net migrants moving from Malaya to Singapore. However, after the declaration of independence of [[Federation of Malaya|Malaya]] in 1957, the migration of people from Malaya began to fall.<ref name=\"jstor1\">{{cite journal |jstor=20067730 |title=Population Trends in Singapore, 1819-1967 |author=Saw Swee-Hock|journal=Journal of Southeast Asian History|volume= 10|issue= 1|date= March 1969|pages= 36\u201349 }}</ref>\n\n===Post-independence immigration===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; text-align:center; width:120px; margin:1em;\"\n|+ Population size and growth by residential status in selected years<ref>[http://www.singstat.gov.sg/pubn/popn/population2012b.pdf Population Trends 2012] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113152420/http://www.singstat.gov.sg/pubn/popn/population2012b.pdf |date=13 November 2012 }} ''Department of Statistics, Singapore''.</ref>\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year || colspan=\"3\" | Number (thousands) || colspan=\"3\" | Growth\n|-\n! Total population || Permanent Residents || Non-residents || Total population || Permanent Residents || Non-residents\n|-\n| 1990 || 3,047.10 || 112.1 || 311.3 || 1.70% || 2.30% || 9.00%\n|-\n| 2000 || 4,027.90 || 287.5 || 754.5 || 1.80% || 9.90% || 9.30%\n|-\n| 2006 || 4,401.40 || 418 || 875.5 || 1.70% || 8.10% || 9.70%\n|-\n| 2008 || 4,839.40 || 478.2 || 1,196.70 || 1.70% || 6.50% || 19.00% \n|-\n| 2010 || 5,076.70 || 541 || 1,305.00 || 1.00% || 1.50% || 4.10%\n|-\n| 2012 || 5,312.40 || 533.1 || 1,494.20 || 0.80% || 0.20% || 7.20%\n|}\nWhen Singapore became an independent nation in 1965, it signalled the end of free movement of people between Malaysia and Singapore. This and increasing job opportunities in Malaysia meant that the previous high level of movement of people between the two countries fell significantly. Net migration in Singapore dropped to 24,000 in the decade of 1970-80 due to tighter control of immigration from Malaysia and other countries. However, a lower rate of natural growth in population and the need for low-skill labour resulted in a deliberate shift in policy by the Singapore government to allow more foreigners to live and work in the country, and net migration increased in the 1980-1990 period to nearly 200,000. By the decade of 1990-2000, the net migrant number of over 600,000 had surpassed the natural growth of the population, and accounted for nearly two-third of the population increase.  The same high level of immigration is also seen in the next decade with 664,083 net migration recorded.<ref name=\"saw2\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dD2qVu8EpdUC&pg=PA14#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=The Population of Singapore |edition=3rd |author= Saw Swee-Hock | publisher=ISEAS Publishing|date=30 June 2012|isbn= 978-9814380980 |pages=11&ndash;18}}</ref>  Curbs on immigration however began to be implemented in the 2010s to ease increasing social issues arising from the high level of immigration.<ref name=\"ST 2015\">{{cite news |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/no-easy-choices-on-foreign-worker-immigrant-policies-pm-lee |title=No easy choices on foreign worker, immigrant policies: PM Lee |date= 3 August 2015 |work=The Straits Times |author=Rachel Chang}}</ref>\n\nThe high level of foreign migrant workers in late 20th and early 21st centuries meant that Singapore has one of the highest percentages of foreigners in the world. By the middle of the 2010s, nearly 40% of the population were estimated to be of foreign origin; although many have become permanent residents, most of them were non-citizens made up of foreign students and workers including dependants.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.expatfocus.com/c/aid=2514/articles/general/these-five-countries-have-the-highest-percentage-of-expats-find-out-why/ |title=These Five Countries Have The Highest Percentage Of Expats: Find Out Why |work=ExpatFocus |date= December 10, 2015 }}</ref>  Between 1970 and 1980, the size of the non-resident population in Singapore doubled. The numbers began to increase greatly from 1980 to 2010. Foreigners constituted 28.1% of Singapore's total [[labour force]] in 2000, to 34.7% in 2010,<ref name=\"yeoh 2012\">{{cite web |url=http://www.migrationpolicy.org/article/rapid-growth-singapores-immigrant-population-brings-policy-challenges |title=Rapid Growth in Singapore's Immigrant Population Brings Policy Challenges |date=April 3, 2012|authors= Brenda Yeoh and Weiqiang Lin |work=Migration Policy Institute }}</ref> which is the highest proportion of [[foreign worker]]s in Asia.  Singapore's non-resident workforce increased 170% from 248,000 in 1990 to 670,000 in 2006 (Yeoh 2007). By 2010, the non-resident workforce had reached nearly 1.09 million, of these 870,000 were low-[[Skill (labor)|skilled]] foreign workers in Singapore; another 240,000 were skilled foreign worker, better-educated S-pass or employment pass holders. Malaysia is the main source of immigrants in Singapore (386,000 in 2010), followed by China, Hong Kong, and Macau, then South Asia, Indonesia, and other Asian countries.<ref name=\"yeoh 2012\"/>  As of June 2014, the total population of Singapore stands at 5.47 million:  3.34 million citizens and 0.53 million permanent residents (total resident number 3.87 million), with 1.60 million non-residents with work passes and foreign students.<ref>{{cite web|title=Total population of Singapore as on June 2014|url=http://www.nptd.gov.sg/portals/0/homepage/highlights/population-in-brief-2014.pdf|accessdate=22 February 2015| work=National Population and Talent Division NPTD |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141211034148/http://www.nptd.gov.sg/portals/0/homepage/highlights/population-in-brief-2014.pdf |archivedate=11 December 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Policy==\nIn Singapore, the term ''immigrant workers'' is separated into ''foreign workers'' and ''foreign talents''. ''Foreign workers'' refers to semi-[[Skill (labor)|skilled]] or unskilled workers who mainly work in the manufacturing, construction, and [[domestic service]]s sectors. The majority of them come from places such as People's Republic of China,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clb.org.hk/en/node/100977 |title=Hired on Sufferance: China\u2019s migrant workers in Singapore |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727232521/http://www.clb.org.hk/en/node/100977 |archivedate=27 July 2011 |work=Chinese Labour Bulletin |date=10 February 2011}}</ref> Indonesia, India, Bangladesh, Pakistan, Myanmar, Sri Lanka, the Philippines, and Thailand, as part of bilateral agreements between Singapore and these countries. ''Foreign talent'' refers to foreigners with professional qualifications or acceptable degrees working at the higher end of Singapore's economy. They mostly come from India, Australia, the Philippines, People's Republic of China, Taiwan, Hong Kong, Japan, Republic of Korea, Malaysia, Europe, New Zealand, United Kingdom and the United States.\n\nIn September 1998 the [[Government of Singapore|Singaporean government]] first constructed a system under which different types of employment passes (EP) are issued to immigrant workers according to their qualifications and monthly salaries. The \"P, Q, R\" employment pass system was put into practice in September 1998; a new \"S\" type employment pass was later introduced in July 2004. The government has also set different policies on recruiting foreign talents and foreign workers.\n\nIn 2014, the Ministry of Manpower did away with their pass type category, however, the criteria remains the same.  From 1 January 2017, new EP applicants will have to earn a fixed monthly salary of $3,600 or more, depending on their qualifications and experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mom.gov.sg/passes-and-permits/employment-pass/eligibility |title=Eligibility for Employment Pass|work=Ministry of Manpower}}</ref>\n\nThe different policies towards 'Foreign workers' and 'Foreign talent' in Singapore have led some people to feel that their contributions toward Singapore's development are valued differently. However, the Singapore government has always stressed the importance of immigrant workers to [[Economy of Singapore|Singapore's economy]] and development. [[Senior Minister]] [[Goh Chok Tong]], then [[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]], said in his 1997 [[National Day]] rally speech that the government's lack of restrictions on the recruitment of foreigners did not extend only to top-rung prestigious positions, but also to middle-level management, skilled worker and technician positions.{{sfn|Low|2002}}\n\n===Foreign talent===\nVarious policies and incentives are used to attract foreign talent to Singapore. CONTACT SINGAPORE was launched in 1997 by the International Talent Division of the [[Ministry of Manpower (Singapore)|Ministry of Manpower]], beginning with six offices worldwide, to facilitate the inflow of international talent to Singapore.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nathan|first1=Dominic|title=New global drive starts, to attract foreign talent.|work=Straits Times|date=31 July 1997}}</ref> The Singapore Talent Recruitment (STAR) Committee was formed in November 1998 with the aim of attracting foreign talents to Singapore. Other similar programmes include Manpower 21,<ref>{{cite news|title=Singapore seeks foreign workers|work=International Business Asia|publisher=Factiva|date=13 September 1999}}</ref> launched in 1999, and the International Manpower Program of the [[Economic Development Board]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ristelhueber|first1=Robert|title=HQ Singapore|work=Electronic Business|issue=3 (Vol 24)|publisher=Gale Group|date=1 March 1998}}</ref> The government has developed the Scheme for Housing of Foreign Talents with the aim of providing affordable yet comfortable accommodations for foreign talents, to attract them to work and stay in Singapore.{{sfn|Low|2002}}\n\n===Foreign workers===\nOn the other hand, stringent policies and regulations have been set on employing foreign workers. In 1981, the government even announced its intention to phase out all unskilled foreign workers by the end of 1991, except domestic maids and those employed in construction and [[shipyard]]s. The policy stance was met with strong protests from employers facing [[labour shortage]]s.{{sfn|Athukorala|Manning|1999}}\n\nIn April 1987, the Singapore government announced its [[immigration policy]], which intended to control the foreign worker inflow. The two key elements in the policy were a monthly levy payable by the employer for each foreign worker employed, and a \"dependency ceiling\" that limits the proportion of foreign workers in the total workforce of any one employer. The government later introduced a two-tier levy system in October 1991 under which employers were required to pay a higher levy on workers whose employment would change the \"dependent ceiling\" value of the company.{{sfn|Athukorala|Manning|1999}}  The levy and the \"dependency ceiling\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Changes To Foreign Workers Levy 2015|url=http://aesperoncoretrade.com/bca-coretrade-levy/|publisher=Aesperon - Changes to Foreign Workers Levy and Quota in 2015|accessdate=1 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150811180940/http://aesperoncoretrade.com/bca-coretrade-levy/|archivedate=11 August 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> have remained the two instruments with which the government has regulated worker inflow in line with changes in domestic [[Labour economics|labour-market]] conditions.{{sfn|Athukorala|Manning|1999}}\n\n*[http://www.aseanhrmech.org/downloads/singapore-Immigration_Act_Of_Singapore.pdf Immigration Act]\n\nNon-residents working in Singapore will require a work visa. There are various types of Singapore work visas starting from work permits for the lower-skilled labourers, to P1 and P2 category Employment Passes to attract niche professionals with good credentials in both education and work experience.\n\nFrom 1 September 2012 only foreign workers with earnings of at least SGD4,000 (USD3,150) per month can sponsor their spouses and children for their stay in Singapore and some of them are also not allowed to bring their parents and in-laws on long-term visit passes. The new regulation also impacts those who switch companies on/after the date, but foreign workers whose families are already in Singapore won't be affected. The increase from SGD2,800 to SGD4,000 was to ease public disquiet over the influx of workers from overseas.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-07-09/singapore-tightens-rules-for-foreign-workers-families.html |title=Singapore Tightens Rules for Foreign Workers' Families |date=10 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, there were over 1,268,300 foreign workers employed in Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.universal.sg/immigration-and-domestic-workers-of-singapore |title=Immigration and Domestic Workers of Singapore |access-date=16 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180209021807/http://www.universal.sg/immigration-and-domestic-workers-of-singapore |archive-date=9 February 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===2013 Population White Paper===\n{{main|Population White Paper}}\nIn early 2013, the [[Parliament of Singapore|Singapore parliament]] debated over the policies recommended by the Population White Paper entitled ''A Sustainable Population for a Dynamic Singapore''. Citing that Singapore's 900,000 Baby Boomers would comprise a quarter of the citizen population by 2030 and that its workforce would shrink \"from 2020 onward\", the White Paper projected that by 2030, Singapore's \"total population could range between 6.5 and 6.9 million\", with resident population between 4.2 and 4.4 million and citizen population between 3.6 and 3.8 million. The White Paper called for an increase in the number of foreign workers so as to provide balance between the number of skilled and less-skilled workers, as well as provide healthcare and domestic services. It also claimed that foreign workers help businesses thrive when the economy is good.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130218092002/http://202.157.171.46/whitepaper/downloads/population-white-paper.pdf ''A Sustainable Population for a Dynamic Singapore''.]</ref> The motion was passed<ref>[http://www.straitstimes.com/microsites/parliament/story/amended-motion-white-paper-adopted-69-million-not-target-20130209 Amended motion on white paper adopted; 6.9 million is not a target.] ''The Straits Times''. 9 February 2013.</ref> albeit after amendments made to leave out \"population policy\" and add focus on infrastructure and transport development.\n\nThe White Paper was criticised by opposition parties.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wp.sg:80/wp-population-policy-paper/ |title=The Workers\u2019 Party\u2019s Population Policy Paper: \"A Dynamic Population for a Sustainable Singapore\" ''The Workers' Party'' |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130228143717/http://wp.sg/wp-population-policy-paper/ |archivedate=28 February 2013 |author=Low Thia Khiang |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Member of Parliament [[Low Thia Khiang]] of the [[Workers' Party of Singapore]] had criticised current measures of increasing the fertility rate, claiming that the high cost of living and lack of family and social support discouraged young couples from having babies. As for current immigration policies, he had noted that immigrants were a source of friction for Singaporeans and that an increased population would put more stress on the already strained urban infrastructure.<ref>[http://wp.sg/2013/02/a-sustainable-singapore-with-a-dynamic-singaporean-majority-mp-low-thia-khiang/ A Sustainable Singapore with a Dynamic Singaporean majority \u2013 MP Low Thia Khiang] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130315182137/http://wp.sg/2013/02/a-sustainable-singapore-with-a-dynamic-singaporean-majority-mp-low-thia-khiang |date=15 March 2013 }} ''The Workers' Party''.</ref> PAP MP Inderjit Singh had also spoken out on the issue, citing cohesion and social issues that would have been made worse with the proposed immigrant influx rate.On 16 February 2013, nearly 3,000 people rallied to protest the White Paper and raise concerns that the increased population would lead to the deterioration of public service and the increase of the cost of living in the future.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2013/02/17/rare-singapore-protest-against-population-plan.html |title=Rare Singapore protest against population plan |date=17 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130218035052/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2013/02/17/rare-singapore-protest-against-population-plan.html |archivedate=18 February 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Impact and criticism==\nThe large influx of migrants from the 1980s onward has raised concerns about the government's policy on immigration. Whilst the inflow of immigrants and foreign workers have helped to alleviate a labour crunch and help the economy, it has also resulted in strong sentiment by the locals against both foreigners and the government, and was a major issue in both the 2011 [[2011 Singaporean general election|general]] and [[2011 Singaporean presidential election|presidential]] elections.<ref name=\"telegrah\">{{cite news|last=Hyslop|first=Leah|title=Singapore opposition stirs up anti-foreigner sentiment|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/expat/expatnews/8494772/Singapore-opposition-stirs-up-anti-foreigner-sentiment.html|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=The Telegraph (UK)|date=5 May 2011}}</ref> Singaporeans have attributed to the government's open-door immigration policy the country's overcrowding and falling reliability of its public transportation system, increasing property prices for housing, suppressed wage level, increased competition for jobs and education, increasing income inequality and other social problems.<ref name=\"chinapost\">{{cite news|title=Singapore tightens rules for hiring foreigners|url=http://www.chinapost.com.tw/business/asia/singapore/2011/08/17/313605/Singapore-tightens.htm|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=The China Post|date=17 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"tafep\">{{cite news|title=Job bias against Singaporeans the top complaint|url=http://business.asiaone.com/Business/News/Office/Story/A1Story20120419-340668.html|accessdate=20 April 2012|last=Boh|first=Samantha|newspaper=my paper|date=19 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121202052258/http://business.asiaone.com/Business/News/Office/Story/A1Story20120419-340668.html|archive-date=2 December 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"asiaoneafp\">{{cite news|title=Singapore to further curb foreign worker inflow|url=http://www.asiaone.com/Business/News/My%2BMoney/Story/A1Story20120217-328618.html|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=AFP|date=17 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221012848/http://www.asiaone.com/Business/News/My+Money/Story/A1Story20120217-328618.html|archive-date=21 February 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"thestarscn1\">{{cite news|last=Seah|first=Chiang Nee|title=Talent buy becomes sore point|url=http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2012/3/24/focus/10969821&sec=focus|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019211757/http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2012%2F3%2F24%2Ffocus%2F10969821&sec=focus|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 October 2012|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=The Star (Malaysia)|date=24 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"cnbc-ac\">{{cite news|first=Leslie|last=Shaffer|title=British banker stirs up storm by mocking Singapore's 'poor'|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/101357276|accessdate=28 January 2014|newspaper=CNBC|date=23 January 2014}}</ref> These issues came under close scrutiny by foreign media in the aftermath of the [[2013 Little India riot]].<ref name=\"littleindiariot\">{{cite news|title=Singapore to Charge Rioters After Little India Violence|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-12-09/lee-clamps-down-on-rioters-after-violence-in-singapore.html|authors=Sharon Chen and Weiyi Lim|accessdate=28 January 2014|newspaper=Bloomberg|date=10 December 2013}}</ref> Local [[Non-governmental organization|NGOs]] have also raised issues of migrant welfare, especially those relating to work injury and living conditions.<ref name=migrant-welfare-cna>{{cite news|last1=Toh|first1=Ee Ming|title=Making Singapore a better place for workers who come from afar|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/making-singapore-a-better/2341718.html|accessdate=4 February 2016|work=Channel NewsAsia|date=12 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Malay|first1=Michael|title=Singapore needs to address its treatment of migrant workers|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development-professionals-network/2014/apr/21/singapore-address-treatment-migrant-workers|accessdate=4 February 2016|work=Guardian|date=21 April 2014}}</ref> Social pressures have been acknowledged by Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong with various measures put in place in the last few years, such as the Fair Employment (Consideration) Framework and Tripartite Alliance for Fair Employment Practices and increasing support for migrant workers.<ref name=migrant-welfare-cna /><ref>{{Cite web|title = 'I owe Singaporeans a responsibility' to get foreign worker balance right: PM Lee|url = http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/i-owe-singaporeans-a/2023914.html|website = Channel NewsAsia|access-date = 2016-01-26}}</ref>\n\nPrime Minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]] and various government agencies have spoken out against a rising anti-foreigner sentiment after Singaporeans expressed outrage at disparaging statements made by foreigners residing in Singapore.<ref name=asiaonesx>{{cite news|title=PM Lee worried about growing divide in Singapore|url=http://news.asiaone.com/print/News/Latest%2BNews/Singapore/Story/A1Story20120405-337897.html|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=AsiaOne|date=5 April 2012}}</ref> For example, in March 2012, Sun Xu, a scholar from China studying in the [[National University of Singapore]], made a remark in his blog that \"there are more dogs than humans in Singapore\".<ref name=asiaonesx /><ref name=stmarch26>{{cite news|last=Jennani|first=Durai|title=Final semester scholarship benefits revoked for China NUS student|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/Singapore/Story/STIStory_781837.html|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=26 March 2012}}</ref> This was weeks after a revelation in parliament that SGD36 million worth of scholarships were awarded to 2,000 foreign students every year, something that is unheard of in other countries.<ref name=thestarscn1 /> The government was accused of disadvantaging local students in places for education and affordability,<ref name=thestarscn1 /> and in response it has made a policy change in primary education to give some priority to Singaporeans.<ref name=thestarp1>{{cite news|title=P1 priority for citizens|url=http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2012/3/27/asia/10994414&sec=asia|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130221023949/http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2012/3/27/asia/10994414&sec=asia|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 February 2013|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=The Star (Malaysia)|date=27 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nFurther incidents have also fanned local sentiments against expatriates and foreign workers in Singapore, for example, the publicity over negative comments about the locals by banker Anton Casey and Filipino nurse Ed Mundsel Bello Ello.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mortlock|first1=Simon|title=How Anton Casey is making life tough for arrogant expat bankers in Singapore|url=https://sg.finance.yahoo.com/news/anton-casey-making-life-tough-000147872.html|accessdate=4 February 2016|publisher=Yahoo! News/Singapore Business Review|date=24 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305002345/https://sg.finance.yahoo.com/news/anton-casey-making-life-tough-000147872.html|archive-date=5 March 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ortiga|first1=Yasmin Y|title=Multiculturalism on Its Head: Unexpected Boundaries and New Migration in Singapore|journal=Journal of International Migration and Integration|date=7 September 2014|volume=16|issue=4|pages=953\u2013954|ref=10.1007/s12134-014-0378-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Diola|first1=Camille|title=Filipino nurse sacked for anti-Singapore comments|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2015/01/12/1412123/filipino-nurse-sacked-anti-singapore-comments|accessdate=7 April 2015|work=Philippine Star|date=12 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=Reuters-ac>{{cite news|last=Leonal|first=Brian|title=Porsche-owning UK expat infuriates Singapore with \"poor people\" gaffes|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/01/23/us-singapore-banker-idUSBREA0M0OJ20140123|accessdate=28 January 2014|newspaper=Reuters|date=23 January 2014}}</ref> In the case of [[Anton Casey]], he had posted comments on Facebook which had abused, variously, a taxi driver and Singaporean commuters in general.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/anton-casey-fired-and-flees-singapore-in-economy-class-over-poor-people-comments-9088199.html|title=Anton Casey fired and flees Singapore in economy class over \"poor|date=2014-01-27|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> Whilst anti-foreigner sentiments are still prevalent online, fifteen foreigners who were interviewed by [[CNA (news channel)|CNA]] did not feel such anti-foreigner sentiments reflected what they encountered in the real world.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Are Singaporeans anti-foreigner? Not in the real world|url = http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/are-singaporeans-anti/1777708.html|website = Channel NewsAsia|access-date = 2016-01-26}}</ref> Local Singaporeans have also written in to the press to encourage fellow Singaporeans to have a mindset of being more accepting towards other cultures, reminding them that Singapore is also from immigrant stock.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Greater cultural integration needed|url = http://www.straitstimes.com/forum/letters-on-the-web/greater-cultural-integration-needed|website = The Straits Times|access-date = 2016-01-26|last = hermesauto}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Let's be a cultural melting pot, not bowl of salad|url = http://www.straitstimes.com/forum/letters-in-print/lets-be-a-cultural-melting-pot-not-bowl-of-salad|website = The Straits Times|access-date = 2016-01-26|last = hermes}}</ref> Media reporting that foreign workers help out in distress situations have also helped improve locals' perception of foreign workers.<ref name=migrant-welfare-cna />\n\nThere are also concerns that immigrants were using Singapore as a springboard for immigration to other developed countries.<ref name=stnewcitizenrn>{{cite news|last=Tan|first=Amanda|title=300 new citizens give up their status each year|url=http://www.spp.nus.edu.sg/ips/docs/media/yr2012/ST_300%20new%20citizens%20give%20up%20their%20status%20each%20year_020312.pdf|accessdate=10 April 2012|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=2 March 2012}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Every year, 300 naturalised citizens renounce their Singapore citizenship.<ref name=stnewcitizenrn /> Many foreigners remain hesitant to take up [[Permanent residency in Singapore|Permanent Residency]] (PR) or [[Singapore citizenship]] because of the two years of [[Conscription in Singapore|mandatory military service]] for male citizens and second-generation PRs.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Singaporean nationality law]]\n* [[Immigration and Checkpoints Authority]]\n* [[National Registration Identity Card]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book|last1=Athukorala|first1=Prema-Chandra|first2=Chris |last2=Manning|chapter=Hong Kong and Singapore: City-States Shaped by Migrants|title=Structural Change and International Migration in East Asia: Adjusting to Labour Scarcity|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2000|isbn=0-19-554173-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last =Low|first=Linda|title=The Political Economy of Migrant Worker Policy in Singapore|journal=Asia Pacific Business Review|volume=8|issue=4|date=June 2002|pages=95\u2013118|doi=10.1080/713999166 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Library resources about |onlinebooks=no |others=yes}}\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Singapore}}\n{{Asia topic|Immigration to}}\n\n[[Category:Singaporean society]]\n[[Category:Immigration to Singapore| ]]\n[[Category:Foreign workers]]\n[[Category:Economy of Singapore]]\n[[Category:Demographics of Singapore]]\n", "name_user": "DidIWikiThat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eImpact and criticism", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Immigration_to_Singapore"}
{"title_page": "2018 British Columbia electoral reform referendum", "text_new": "{{Short description|referendum on British Columbia's voting system}}\n{{Infobox multichoice referendum \n| name        = British Columbia electoral reform referendum \n| map         = British_Columbia_Electoral_Reform_Referendum_2018_-_Question_1_Results_by_Riding.svg\n| mapcaption = Question 1 results by electoral district (green: FPTP; red: PR)\n| mapdivision  = electoral district\n| title       = Which system should British Columbia use for provincial elections?\n| location    = [[British Columbia]], Canada\n| date        = {{Start date|2018|10|22}} \u2013 {{End date|2018|12|7}}\n| choice1 = The current First Past the Post voting system\n| percentage1 = 61.3\n| choice2 = A proportional representation voting system\n| percentage2 = 38.7\n| status = complete\n}}\n\nA referendum on [[electoral reform]] took place by [[postal ballot|mail-in ballot]] between October 22 and December 7, 2018, in the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Canadian province]] of [[British Columbia]]. This was British Columbia's third referendum on electoral reform since 2005.\n\nVoters were asked two questions: first, what electoral system should be used to determine election results\u2014the existing [[first-past-the-post]] (FPTP) system or a [[proportional representation]] (PR) system; and second, what type of proportional voting system should be used if PR is chosen. In the second question, voters were asked to rank three proportional representation voting systems: [[dual-member proportional representation]], [[mixed-member proportional representation]], and [[rural\u2013urban proportional representation]].\n\nThe referendum fulfilled an election commitment by the [[British Columbia New Democratic Party]] (NDP) during the 2017 election. Their platform promised a referendum and that the government would actively campaign for electoral reform.\n\nResults were released by [[Elections BC]] on December 20, 2018. British Columbians voted in favour of maintaining the first-past-the-post voting system rather than switching to a proportional representation voting system.\n\n==Background==\nBC has a long history of changing its electoral system. For BC's first election in 1871, the majority of ridings were elected using an \"at large\" system. This is the way city councillors are elected in BC to this day: a voter gets as many votes as there were people to be elected in the riding.<ref name=1871-1986>{{cite web |last=[[Elections BC|Elections British Columbia]] |title=Electoral History of British Columbia 1871\u20131986 |date=1988 |url=http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/1871-1986_ElectoralHistoryofBC.pdf |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613200446/http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/1871-1986_ElectoralHistoryofBC.pdf# |archive-date=13 June 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOver its history, BC modified its electoral system at least 15 times without a referendum.<ref name=1871-1986 /> It previously used an [[Instant-runoff voting|alternative voting system]] in the [[1952 British Columbia general election|1952 provincial election]] before abolishing it and reestablishing the previous mix of \"at large\" and first-past-the-post.<ref name=\"pdennis\">{{Cite book |title=The politics of voting : reforming Canada's electoral system |last=Pilon |first=Dennis |date=2007 |publisher=Emond Montgomery Publications |isbn=9781552392362 |location=Toronto |oclc=150223313}}</ref>{{rp|81\u201382}}<ref>{{cite web |last=[[Elections BC|Elections British Columbia]] |title=Electoral History of British Columbia 1871\u20131986 |date=1988 |url=http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/1871-1986_ElectoralHistoryofBC.pdf |access-date=21 June 2018 |pages=231\u2013232 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613200446/http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/1871-1986_ElectoralHistoryofBC.pdf# |archive-date=13 June 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> The first BC election done entirely under first-past-the-post came in 1991, after the last \"at-large\" voting districts had been abolished.<ref name=\"pdennis\"/>{{rp|76}}<ref>{{cite web |last=[[Elections BC]] |title=Electoral History of B.C. |date=2018 |url=http://elections.bc.ca/resources/learning-about-elections/electoral-history-of-bc/ |access-date=25 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626030841/http://elections.bc.ca/resources/learning-about-elections/electoral-history-of-bc/# |archive-date=26 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The multi-member at-large ridings were abolished after the 1986 election due to a Supreme Court of Canada ruling that found them unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite web |last=[[Elections BC]] |title=Electoral History of B.C. |date=2018 |url=http://elections.bc.ca/resources/learning-about-elections/electoral-history-of-bc/}}</ref>\n\n\n===Previous referendums===\nBefore the [[2001 British Columbia general election|2001 provincial election]], the [[British Columbia Liberal Party|BC Liberal Party]] committed to appoint a [[Citizens' Assembly on Electoral Reform (British Columbia)|Citizens' Assembly]] to investigate electoral reform, hold consultations, and prepare a report recommending whether a different [[electoral system]] should be adopted.<ref name=CAReport>{{cite web |title=Making Every Vote Count: The Case for Electoral Reform in British Columbia |url=http://www.citizensassembly.bc.ca:80/resources/final_report.pdf |date=December 2004 |access-date=15 June 2018 |author=[[Citizens' Assembly on Electoral Reform (British Columbia)|British Columbia Citizens' Assembly on Electoral Reform]] |publisher=Government of British Columbia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050513192722/http://www.citizensassembly.bc.ca/resources/final_report.pdf# |archive-date=13 May 2005}}</ref> The commitment was driven in part by the anomalous provincial election result in [[1996 British Columbia general election|1996]], in which the BC New Democratic Party won reelection as a majority government with 39.5% of the vote and 39 seats, despite gaining a 3% smaller share of the popular vote than the Liberals at 41.8%, which translated into 33 Liberal seats.<ref name=\"pdennis\"/>{{rp|90\u201391}} In December 2004, the Assembly released its report recommending that the province adopt [[BC-STV]], a BC-specific variant of the [[single transferable vote]] (STV) system.<ref name=CAReport /> On May 17, 2005, a [[2005 British Columbia electoral reform referendum|referendum]] was held in conjunction with the [[2005 British Columbia general election|2005 general election]], in which voters were asked whether the province should adopt the recommendation of the Assembly to replace the first-past-the-post electoral system with BC-STV, or maintain the current system. While 57.7% of the electorate voted in favour of BC-STV, including a majority of voters in 77 of 79 ridings, its support failed to reach the 60% threshold set by the government and it was not adopted.<ref>{{cite web |last=Elections BC |title=Statement of Votes \u2013 Referendum on Electoral Reform |date=May 17, 2005 |page=9 |url=http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/SOV-2005-ReferendumOnElectoralReform.pdf |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220152639/http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/SOV-2005-ReferendumOnElectoralReform.pdf# |archive-date=20 February 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2005 referendum, British Columbia held [[2009 British Columbia electoral reform referendum|a second referendum]] on electoral reform in conjunction with the [[2009 British Columbia general election|provincial election]] on May 12, 2009. It was the most recent referendum on electoral reform that has been held in British Columbia. As in 2005, voters in 2009 were asked to provide their opinions on the BC-STV electoral system proposed by the [[Citizens' Assembly on Electoral Reform (British Columbia)|British Columbia Citizen's Assembly on Electoral Reform]] to ensure more proportional representation in the [[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia|provincial Legislative Assembly]]. British Columbians were asked which electoral system should be used to elect legislators: the existing first-past-the-post electoral system or the proposed BC-STV system.\n\nThe adoption of BC-STV in the 2009 referendum was defeated, with 60.9% voting against the reform and 39.09% of voters supporting the change.<ref>{{cite web |last=Elections BC |title=Statement of Votes \u2013 Referendum on Electoral Reform |date=May 12, 2009 |page=20 |url=http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/2009Ref/2009-Ref-SOV.pdf |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423200639/http://elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/2009Ref/2009-Ref-SOV.pdf# |archive-date=23 April 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Intervening federal developments===\nDuring the [[2015 Canadian federal election|2015 federal election]], [[Justin Trudeau]] and the [[Liberal Party of Canada]] campaigned on the promise that it would be the last federal election under the first-past-the-post electoral system. The party's platform stated that a Liberal government would form an all-party Parliamentary committee, and introduce legislation within 18 months enacting electoral reform.<ref>{{cite web |title=Electoral reform |url=https://www.liberal.ca/realchange/electoral-reform/ |website=Real Change |publisher=Liberal Party of Canada |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621194408/https://www.liberal.ca/realchange/electoral-reform/# |archive-date=21 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"2part-question\">{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/news-pmn/canada-news-pmn/b-c-electoral-reform-referendum-includes-two-part-ballot-question|title=B.C. electoral reform referendum includes two-part ballot question|last=Meissner|first=Dirk|date=May 30, 2018|work=[[The National Post]]|access-date=4 June 2018}}</ref> On December 1, 2016, the [[Canadian House of Commons Special Committee on Electoral Reform|House of Commons of Canada Special Committee on Electoral Reform]] released its report recommending Canada hold a referendum to adopt a proportional representation voting system for federal elections.<ref name=\"fed-report\">{{cite report |author=Special Committee on Electoral Reform |date=December 1, 2016 |title=Strengthening Democracy in Canada: Principles, Process and Public Engagement for Electoral Reform |url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?DocId=8655791&Language=E&Mode=1&Parl=42&Ses=1 |publisher=Parliament of Canada |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408092349/http://www.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?Language=e&Mode=1&Parl=42&Ses=1&DocId=8655791# |archive-date=8 April 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Several months later, the government announced that it was no longer pursuing electoral reform.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stone |first=Laura |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/trudeau-abandons-electoral-reform/article33855925/ |title=Trudeau abandons electoral reform, breaking key campaign promise |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |access-date=6 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205160959/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/trudeau-abandons-electoral-reform/article33855925/# |archive-date=5 February 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Joanna |title=Trudeau abandons promise for electoral reform |url=http://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/trudeau-abandons-promise-for-electoral-reform/ |access-date=21 June 2018 |work=Maclean's |agency=The Canadian Press |date=February 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209174029/http://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/trudeau-abandons-promise-for-electoral-reform/# |archive-date=9 February 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Origin of third referendum===\nDuring the [[2017 British Columbia general election|2017 provincial election]], both the NDP and the [[Green Party of British Columbia|Green Party]] campaigned for PR and included the policy in their election platforms.<ref name=\"NDPplatform\">{{cite web |title=Platform 2017 |url=https://action.bcndp.ca/page/-/bcndp/docs/BC-NDP-Platform-2017.pdf |website=bcndp.ca |publisher=BC NDP |access-date=30 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510162021/https://action.bcndp.ca/page/-/bcndp/docs/BC-NDP-Platform-2017.pdf# |archive-date=10 May 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bc-election-aftermath-electoral-reform-1.4122921 |title=B.C. parties leave door open to electoral reform without a referendum |last=Omand |first=Geordon |work=[[CBC News]] |date=May 18, 2017 |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180604094829/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bc-election-aftermath-electoral-reform-1.4122921# |archive-date=4 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=BC Green Party |title=Change You Can Count On: Platform 2017 |date=2017 |url=https://www.bcgreens.ca/platform |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140957/https://www.bcgreens.ca/platform# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> On May 29, 2017, approximately three weeks after the election resulted in a [[British Columbia Liberal Party|BC Liberal]] [[minority government]], the NDP and Green caucuses signed a [[Confidence and supply|supply and confidence]] agreement.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bc-ndp-green-agreement-1.4136539 |title=B.C. Green Party agrees to support NDP in the legislature |last=McElroy |first=Justin |work=[[CBC News]] |date=May 29, 2017 |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180605094150/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bc-ndp-green-agreement-1.4136539# |archive-date=5 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The agreement included a section on PR, in which the parties agreed to put the issue to a referendum and that both parties would actively campaign for PR in the referendum.<ref>{{cite web |last=BC NDP Caucus |title=2017 Confidence and Supply Agreement between the BC Green Caucus and the BC New Democrat Caucus |date=May 30, 2017 |url=http://bcndpcaucus.ca/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2017/05/BC-Green-BC-NDP-Agreement_vf-May-29th-2017.pdf |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712183901/http://bcndpcaucus.ca/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2017/05/BC-Green-BC-NDP-Agreement_vf-May-29th-2017.pdf# |archive-date=12 July 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/whats-ahead-for-bc-politics-after-the-ndp-green-partyagreement/article35160029/ |title=The road ahead for B.C. politics |last=Hipolito |first=Chad |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=May 31, 2018 |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813154305/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/whats-ahead-for-bc-politics-after-the-ndp-green-partyagreement/article35160029/# |archive-date=13 August 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> On June 22, 2017, the Liberal government tabled its [[throne speech]], adopting the opposition parties' policy to hold a third referendum on electoral reform.<ref>{{cite web |last=Meissner |first=Dirk |title=B.C. Throne Speech: Clark's Liberals Promise Electoral Reform Referendum, Sales Tax Cut |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2017/06/22/b-c-throne-speech-clarks-liberals-promise-electoral-reform-re_a_22583513/ |access-date=11 June 2018 |date=June 23, 2017 |work=[[Huffington Post Canada]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141218/https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2017/06/22/b-c-throne-speech-clarks-liberals-promise-electoral-reform-re_a_22583513/# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Speech from the Throne |url=https://www.leg.bc.ca/parliamentary-business/legislation-debates-proceedings/41st-parliament/1st-session/throne-speech |access-date=11 June 2018 |date=June 22, 2017 |publisher=[[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141507/https://www.leg.bc.ca/parliamentary-business/legislation-debates-proceedings/41st-parliament/1st-session/throne-speech# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> On June 29, 2017, the BC Liberal government was defeated in a [[confidence and supply|confidence vote]]. [[Lieutenant Governor of British Columbia|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Judith Guichon]] then invited the NDP to form a minority government with Green support.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McElroy |first1=Justin |title=NDP Leader John Horgan to be next premier of British Columbia |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/horgan-government-guichon-2017-1.4185204 |access-date=30 June 2017 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630112221/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/horgan-government-guichon-2017-1.4185204# |archive-date=30 June 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> On November 30, 2017, the ''Electoral Reform Referendum 2018 Act'' was passed into law.<ref>{{Cite canlaw |short title=Electoral Reform Referendum 2018 Act |abbr=SBC |year=2017 |chapter=22 |link=http://www.bclaws.ca/civix/document/id/complete/statreg/17022_01}}</ref> It required the referendum to be held and authorized [[Executive Council of British Columbia|Cabinet]] to make various regulations.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hunter |first1=Justine |title=B.C. NDP, Greens flex partnership with swath of new policy achievements |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/bc-ndp-greens-flex-partnership-with-swath-of-new-policy-achievements/article37158183/ |date=November 30, 2017 |access-date=23 June 2018 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418220125/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/bc-ndp-greens-flex-partnership-with-swath-of-new-policy-achievements/article37158183/# |archive-date=18 April 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Consultation and implementation==\nBetween November 2017 and February 2018, [[Attorney General]] [[David Eby]] conducted a public consultation entitled \"How We Vote\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Meissner |first=Dirk |title=B.C. New Democrats invite public electoral reform vote; Liberals cry foul |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/politics/b-c-new-democrats-invite-public-electoral-reform-vote-liberals-cry-foul |date=November 23, 2017 |access-date=7 June 2018 |work=[[Vancouver Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612142419/http://vancouversun.com/news/politics/b-c-new-democrats-invite-public-electoral-reform-vote-liberals-cry-foul# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> On May 30, 2018, he released the report on the consultation and recommendations concerning how the referendum process should be conducted.<ref name=\"2018report\">{{cite web |last=Eby |first=David |date=May 30, 2018 |title=How We Vote 2018 Electoral Reform Referendum: Report and Recommendations of the Attorney General |url=https://engage.gov.bc.ca/app/uploads/sites/271/2018/05/How-We-Vote-2018-Electoral-Reform-Referendum-Report-and-Recommendations-of-the-Attorney-General.pdf |publisher=Government of British Columbia |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831060310/https://engage.gov.bc.ca/app/uploads/sites/271/2018/05/How-We-Vote-2018-Electoral-Reform-Referendum-Report-and-Recommendations-of-the-Attorney-General.pdf# |archive-date=31 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Tyee?s\">{{cite web |url=https://thetyee.ca/News/2018/05/30/Eby-Proposed-Electoral-Reform-Referendum-Questions/ |title=Eby Unveils Proposed Electoral Reform Referendum Questions |last=MacLeod |first=Andrew |work=[[The Tyee]] |date=May 30, 2018 |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612142804/https://thetyee.ca/News/2018/05/30/Eby-Proposed-Electoral-Reform-Referendum-Questions/# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Eagland |first=Nick |title=New Zealand gives B.C. a lesson on proportional representation |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/new-zealand-gives-b-c-a-lesson-on-proportional-representation |date=June 4, 2018 |access-date=6 June 2018 |work=[[Vancouver Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180609041248/http://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/new-zealand-gives-b-c-a-lesson-on-proportional-representation# |archive-date=9 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Cabinet accepted the recommendations shortly thereafter, in early June.<ref name=\"PremierStatement\">{{cite web |author=Office of the Premier |title=Premier's statement on recommendations for proportional representation referendum |date=June 7, 2018 |url=https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2018PREM0083-001137 |access-date=7 June 2018 |publisher=Government of British Columbia |type=Press release |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141900/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2018PREM0083-001137# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Fletcher |first=Tom |title=B.C. cabinet approves multiple-choice voting referendum |url=https://www.theprogress.com/news/b-c-cabinet-approves-multiple-choice-voting-referendum/ |access-date=7 June 2018 |date=June 7, 2018 |publisher=[[Black Press]] |work=The Chilliwack Progress |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612122653/https://www.theprogress.com/news/b-c-cabinet-approves-multiple-choice-voting-referendum/# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Later in June, Vote PR BC launched their campaign for proportional representation, canvassing in cities across the province.<ref>{{cite web |last=Grauer |first=Perrin |title=Campaign to change B.C. voting system hits the streets, with Ontario election in mind |url=https://www.thestar.com/vancouver/2018/06/10/campaign-to-change-bc-voting-system-hits-the-streets-with-ontario-election-in-mind.html |date=June 10, 2018 |access-date=11 June 2018 |work=[[StarMetro (newspaper)|StarMetro Vancouver]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140600/https://www.thestar.com/vancouver/2018/06/10/campaign-to-change-bc-voting-system-hits-the-streets-with-ontario-election-in-mind.html# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Ryan |first=Denise |title=Canvassers take case for B.C. electoral reform to commuters |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/canvassers-take-case-for-b-c-electoral-reform-to-commuters |date=June 10, 2018 |access-date=11 June 2018 |work=[[Vancouver Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140431/http://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/canvassers-take-case-for-b-c-electoral-reform-to-commuters# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Elections BC]] reviewed the referendum questions in June. On June 18, Chief Electoral Officer Anton Boegman wrote to the [[Speaker of the Legislative Assembly of British Columbia|Speaker of the Legislative Assembly]] advising that in his view both questions were simple and clear enough for voters to understand. He also made recommendations for small changes to the questions.<ref>{{cite web |last=Boegman |first=Anton |title=Letter to the Speaker of the Legislative Assembly |url=http://elections.bc.ca/docs/referendum/REF-2018-LTR-CEO-speaker-response.pdf |date=June 18, 2018 |access-date=19 June 2018 |work=[[Elections BC]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619214100/http://elections.bc.ca/docs/referendum/REF-2018-LTR-CEO-speaker-response.pdf# |archive-date=19 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Press Progress |title=Elections BC Just Blew a Giant Hole in the Big Money Campaign Attacking Electoral Reform |url=https://pressprogress.ca/elections-bc-just-blew-a-giant-hole-in-the-big-money-campaign-attacking-electoral-reform/ |date=June 19, 2018 |access-date=19 June 2018 |work=Press Progress |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620001245/https://pressprogress.ca/elections-bc-just-blew-a-giant-hole-in-the-big-money-campaign-attacking-electoral-reform/# |archive-date=20 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>  On June 22, 2018, the government released the regulations governing the referendum.<ref name=\"regulation\">{{cite web |url=https://engage.gov.bc.ca/app/uploads/sites/271/2018/06/ReferendumRegulation2018.pdf |title=Electoral Reform Referendum 2018 Regulation, Reg. 313/2018 |date=June 22, 2018 |access-date=23 June 2018 |work=govTogetherBC |publisher=Government of British Columbia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623210203/https://engage.gov.bc.ca/app/uploads/sites/271/2018/06/ReferendumRegulation2018.pdf |archive-date=23 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The regulations adopted the changes to the question proposed by the Chief Electoral Officer, and set down other rules governing the campaign.<ref>{{cite web |last=[[The Canadian Press]]|title=Electoral reform vote in B.C. includes $500,000 each for pro and con groups |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-electoral-reform-vote-in-bc-includes-500000-each-for-pro-and-con/|date=June 22, 2018 |access-date=23 June 2018|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Little|first=Simon|title=B.C. lays out rules for fall referendum on changing the way politicians are elected|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4292443/proportional-representation-referendum-rules/|date=June 22, 2018|access-date=23 June 2018|work=[[Global News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623023255/https://globalnews.ca/news/4292443/proportional-representation-referendum-rules/#|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===ICBA lawsuit===\n\nOn June 28, 2018, the Independent Contractors and Business Association (ICBA)\u2014a lobby group for the construction industry\u2014 filed a lawsuit seeking an injunction to stop the referendum, or alternatively, to strike down the campaign financing rules governing the referendum.<ref>{{cite web |title=About ICBA |url=https://icba.ca/about-icba/ |access-date=29 June 2018 |publisher=Independent Contractors and Business Association |website=icba.ca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629211710/https://icba.ca/about-icba/# |archive-date=29 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=LawsuitFiled>{{cite web|last=Mulgrew|first=Ian|title=Injunction sought to halt B.C. proportional representation vote|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/injunction-sought-to-halt-b-c-proportional-representation-vote|date=June 29, 2018|access-date=29 June 2018|work=[[Vancouver Sun]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629024007/http://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/injunction-sought-to-halt-b-c-proportional-representation-vote#|archive-date=29 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The lawsuit contains various complaints about the process, the referendum, and the systems on the ballot.<ref name=LawsuitFiled /> In response, NDP MLA [[Bob D'Eith]] called the lawsuit an attempt to stop people from having a choice in their electoral system, and said ICBA does not want \"ordinary people to have a stronger voice in the elections and I think they're desperate to hang on to the status quo\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Kretzel|first=Lasia|title=ICBA, Union seek injunction on proportional representation referendum|url=https://www.news1130.com/2018/06/29/icba-union-seek-injunction-proportional-representation-referendum/|date=June 29, 2018|access-date=1 July 2018|work=[[News 1130]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701165030/https://www.news1130.com/2018/06/29/icba-union-seek-injunction-proportional-representation-referendum/#|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Attorney General of British Columbia|Ministry of the Attorney General]] is defending the legislation in court.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bains|first=Camille|title=B.C. referendum campaign launches as groups file petition to stop process|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-bc-referendum-campaign-launches-as-groups-file-petition-to-stop/|date=July 1, 2018|access-date=2 July 2018|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704225722/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-bc-referendum-campaign-launches-as-groups-file-petition-to-stop/#|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The official campaign began July 1, 2018.<ref name=\"regulation\" />\n\nOn July 17, 2018, ICBA's court application for an early trial date was dismissed by Justice Miriam Gropper of the [[British Columbia Supreme Court]], in order to allow the government time to respond. Following the hearing, ICBA's lawyer, Peter Gall, told reporters ICBA would be seeking an interim injunction.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mulgrew|first=Ian|title=B.C. electoral system referendum foes lose first round|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/politics/b-c-electoral-system-referendum-foes-lose-first-round|date=July 18, 2018|access-date=19 July 2018|work=[[Vancouver Sun]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718205834/https://vancouversun.com/news/politics/b-c-electoral-system-referendum-foes-lose-first-round#|archive-date=18 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn July 24, ICBA filed an application seeking an interim injunction to halt campaign financing rules and prevent ballots from being counted. The application was heard by Justice Gropper on August 7. In her decision handed down several weeks later, she dismissed the application calling ICBA's allegations about the referendum \"rhetoric\", \"conjecture\" and \"exaggeration\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Fraser |first=Keith |title=Judge refuses to stop B.C.'s referendum on proportional representation voting system |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/judge-refuses-to-stop-b-c-s-referendum-on-proportional-representation-voting-system |date=August 28, 2018 |access-date=28 August 2018 |work=[[Vancouver Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829013223/https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/judge-refuses-to-stop-b-c-s-referendum-on-proportional-representation-voting-system# |archive-date=29 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Ball |first=David |title=Judge quashes attempt to halt mailing of ballots for B.C.'s referendum on electoral reform |url=https://www.thestar.com/vancouver/2018/08/28/judge-quashes-attempt-to-halt-mailing-of-ballots-for-bcs-referendum-on-electoral-reform.html |date=August 28, 2018 |access-date=29 August 2018 |work=[[StarMetro (newspaper)|The Star Vancouver]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829073738/https://www.thestar.com/vancouver/2018/08/28/judge-quashes-attempt-to-halt-mailing-of-ballots-for-bcs-referendum-on-electoral-reform.html# |archive-date=29 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite CanLII |litigants=ICBA v British Columbia |year=2018 |court=bcsc |num=1597 |courtname=auto}}</ref> In mid-September, the ICBA announced that they will be seeking leave to appeal Justice Gropper's ruling on the interim injunction.<ref>{{cite web |last=Yuzda |first=Liza |title=ICBA seeking appeal on proportional representation referendum injunction request |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4446641/icba-seeking-appeal-on-proportional-representation-referendum-injunction-request/ |date=September 13, 2018 |access-date=13 September 2018 |work=[[Global News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180913211133/https://globalnews.ca/news/4446641/icba-seeking-appeal-on-proportional-representation-referendum-injunction-request/# |archive-date=13 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> That same month, the [[British Columbia Government and Service Employees' Union]] was granted [[Intervention (law)|intervenor status]] by the court, siding against the ICBA.<ref>{{cite web |last=Macdonald |first=Gord |title=BCGEU joins legal fight over proportional representation referendum |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4495631/bcgeu-legal-fight-proportional-representation-referendum/ |date=September 28, 2018 |access-date=5 November 2018 |work=[[Global News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929113346/https://globalnews.ca/news/4495631/bcgeu-legal-fight-proportional-representation-referendum/# |archive-date=29 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe appeal of Justice Gropper's judgement concerning the interim injunction was heard on November 2. Justice Fitch of the [[British Columbia Court of Appeal]] dismissed the appeal, finding that there was no merit to the ICBA's argument.<ref>{{cite CanLII |litigants=ICBA v British Columbia |year=2018 |court=bcca |num=429 |courtname=auto}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=[[The Canadian Press]] |title=Top B.C. court rejects group's attempt to stop electoral reform referendum |url=https://theprovince.com/news/local-news/top-court-rejects-groups-attempt-to-stop-b-c-electoral-reform-referendum/wcm/be8876e2-5e41-4e4c-a6ce-cce680bbc313 |date=November 2, 2018 |access-date=2 November 2018 |work=[[The Province]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103003643/https://theprovince.com/news/local-news/top-court-rejects-groups-attempt-to-stop-b-c-electoral-reform-referendum/wcm/be8876e2-5e41-4e4c-a6ce-cce680bbc313# |archive-date=3 November 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Ballot structure and details==\nVoters were asked two questions in the referendum. The first revolved around what electoral system should be used to determine election results: the existing first-past-the-post system or a proportional representation system. The second question explored what type of proportional voting system should be used if PR is chosen. This involved voters ranking three proportional representation voting systems: [[dual-member proportional representation]], [[mixed-member proportional representation]], and [[rural\u2013urban proportional representation]].<ref name=\"2part-question\" /><ref name=announcement>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/electoral-reform-referendum-question-eby-1.4683919 |title=B.C. to choose between 4 systems for electoral reform referendum |last=McElroy |first=Justin |work=[[CBC News]] |date=May 30, 2018 |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180604094840/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/electoral-reform-referendum-question-eby-1.4683919# |archive-date=4 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"systems\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/pr-electoral-reform-questions-1.4688604 |title=Know your voting systems: three types of electoral reform on B.C.'s ballot |last=McElroy |first=Justin |work=[[CBC News]] |date=June 2, 2018 |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603182847/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/pr-electoral-reform-questions-1.4688604# |archive-date=3 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*Question 1: Which system should British Columbia use for provincial elections? (Vote for only one.)\n**The current First Past the Post voting system\n**A proportional representation voting system\n*Question 2: If British Columbia adopts a proportional representation voting system, which of the following voting systems do you prefer? (Rank in order of preference. You may choose to support one, two or all three of the systems.)\n**Dual-member proportional (DMP)\n**Mixed-member proportional (MMP)\n**Rural\u2013urban proportional (RUP)\n\n==Proportional voting systems on the ballot==\nThe referendum asked voters to rank three proportional representation voting systems in order of preference: Voters ranked one, two, or all three systems.<ref name=\"2018report\" />\n* [[dual-member proportional representation]] (DMP)\n* [[mixed-member proportional representation]] (MMP)\n* [[rural\u2013urban proportional representation]] (RUP)\n\n===Dual-member proportional (DMP)===\nDual-member proportional is an electoral system designed to produce proportional election results across a region by electing two [[legislator|representatives]] in each of the region's [[electoral district|districts]].<ref name=\"dmpreport\">{{cite web |url=https://dmpforcanada.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/dmp-report-updated-april-4-2016.pdf |title=Dual-Member Mixed Proportional: A New Electoral System for Canada |author=Sean Graham |date=April 4, 2016 |access-date=18 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020142244/https://dmpforcanada.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/dmp-report-updated-april-4-2016.pdf# |archive-date=20 October 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.assembly.pe.ca/sittings/2015fall/reports/23_1_2015-27-11-report.pdf |title=Recommendations in Response to the White Paper on Democratic Renewal |author=PEI Special Committee on Democratic Renewal |date=November 27, 2015 |access-date=18 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822171727/http://www.assembly.pe.ca/sittings/2015fall/reports/23_1_2015-27-11-report.pdf# |archive-date=22 August 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> The first seat in every district is awarded to the candidate who receives the most votes, similar to first-past-the-post voting. The second seat is awarded to one of the remaining district candidates so that proportionality is achieved across the region, using a calculation that aims to award parties their seats in the districts where they had their strongest performances.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/dual-member-proportional-dmp/ |title=Dual Member Proportional (DMP) |website=elections.bc.ca |publisher=Elections BC |access-date=20 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821093854/https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/dual-member-proportional-dmp/# |archive-date=21 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDMP was invented in 2013 by a [[University of Alberta]] mathematics student named Sean Graham.<ref name=\"DmpErreMeeting\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ourcommons.ca/DocumentViewer/en/42-1/ERRE/meeting-33/evidence |title=Meeting No. 33 Evidence |author=[[Canadian House of Commons Special Committee on Electoral Reform]] |date=29 September 2016 |access-date=18 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618102546/https://www.ourcommons.ca/DocumentViewer/en/42-1/ERRE/meeting-33/evidence# |archive-date=18 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The system was intended as a possible replacement for first-past-the-post voting in [[Elections in Canada|Canadian national and provincial elections]]. Whereas campaigns to adopt MMP representation or the single transferable vote had recently been defeated in a number of [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Canadian provinces]] (such as the 2005 and 2009 British Columbia referendums, the [[2005 Prince Edward Island electoral reform referendum|2005 Prince Edward Island referendum]], and the [[2007 Ontario electoral reform referendum|2007 Ontario referendum]]), the intent behind DMP was to gain broader acceptance by retaining salient features of first-past-the-post voting. These features include a one-vote ballot, relatively small districts (compared with STV), and a single tier of local representatives (in contrast to MMP).<ref name=\"DmpMediaEndorse\">{{cite news |url=http://www.theguardian.pe.ca/opinion/editorials/editorial-we-endorse-dmp-option-in-plebiscite-111292/ |title=Editorial: We endorse DMP option in plebiscite |author=[[The Guardian]] |date=October 29, 2016 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=18 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618102408/http://www.theguardian.pe.ca/opinion/editorials/editorial-we-endorse-dmp-option-in-plebiscite-111292/# |archive-date=18 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Mixed-member proportional===\nMixed-member proportional is a [[mixed electoral system]] in which voters get two votes: one to decide the [[legislator|representative]] for their single-seat [[electoral district|constituency]], and one for a political party. Seats in the legislature are filled firstly by candidates in local ridings, and secondly, by party candidates based on the percentage of nationwide or region-wide votes that each party received.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/mixed-member-proportional-mmp/ |title=Mixed Member Proportional (MMP) |publisher=[[Elections BC]] |website=elections.bc.ca |access-date=20 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821093857/https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/mixed-member-proportional-mmp/# |archive-date=21 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, MMP was recommended by the [[Law Commission of Canada]] to be adopted for federal elections.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://publications.gc.ca/collections/Collection/J31-61-2004E.pdf |title=Voting Counts: Electoral Reform for Canada |author=[[Law Commission of Canada]] |date=2004 |publisher=[[Minister of Public Services and Procurement|Minister of Public Works and Government Services]] |access-date=19 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020142238/http://publications.gc.ca/collections/Collection/J31-61-2004E.pdf# |archive-date=20 October 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=ElectoralGame /> In 2007, Ontario held a [[2007 Ontario electoral reform referendum|provincial referendum]] to adopt the system, which failed to pass.<ref name=ElectoralGame>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/ontario-election-electoral-system-alternatives-1.4709074 |title=The electoral game: What would Ontario results look like under a different voting system? |last1=Ouellet |first1=Val\u00e9rie |last2=Dubinsky |first2=Zach |date=June 16, 2018 |access-date=19 June 2018 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618183146/http://www.cbc.ca/news/ontario-election-electoral-system-alternatives-1.4709074# |archive-date=18 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, [[Prince Edward Island]] (PEI) voted to adopt MMP in a [[2016 Prince Edward Island electoral reform referendum|non-binding referendum]].<ref name=\"cbc results\">{{cite news |last1=Bradley |first1=Susan |title=P.E.I. plebiscite results favour mixed member proportional representation |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/mixed-member-proportional-representation-in-plebiscite-1.3840172 |accessdate=8 November 2016 |work=CBC News |date=8 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129004505/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/mixed-member-proportional-representation-in-plebiscite-1.3840172# |archive-date=29 November 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> PEI held [[2019 Prince Edward Island electoral reform referendum|another referendum]] on the issue during the 2019 provincial election, and narrowly voted against MMP. <ref>{{cite news |title=P.E.I. voters split on electoral reform |url=https://www.theguardian.pe.ca/news/pei-election/pei-voters-split-on-electoral-reform-304782/ |last=Smith |first=Katie |accessdate=April 24, 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=April 23, 2019 |location=Charlottetown, PEI |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/pei-referendum-act-passes-legislature-1.4703182 |title=Much-amended P.E.I. referendum legislation passes |last=CBC News |date=June 12, 2018 |work=[[CBC News]] |access-date=13 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613171020/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/pei-referendum-act-passes-legislature-1.4703182# |archive-date=13 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA form of MMP is used for national elections in [[Electoral system of New Zealand#MMP in New Zealand|New Zealand]] and Germany, and in the United Kingdom for elections to the [[Devolution in the United Kingdom|devolved parliaments]] of [[Elections in Scotland#Scottish Parliament|Scotland]] and Wales (where the system is referred to as the [[Additional Member System]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/new-zealand-democracy-1.4720787|title=Why New Zealand's former prime minister believes proportional representation works better |last=Humphrey|first=Matt|date=June 25, 2018 |work=[[CBC News]] |access-date=25 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fairvote.ca/mixed-member-proportional/ |title=Mixed Member Proportional |author=[[Fair Vote Canada]] |date=2018 |work=Fair Vote Canada |access-date=25 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724151104/https://www.fairvote.ca/mixed-member-proportional/# |archive-date=24 July 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Rural\u2013urban proportional (RUP)===\n[[File:Preferential ballot.svg|thumb|Simplified example of an STV ranked ballot used in an urban or semi-urban area under rural\u2013urban proportional (RUP). RUP is the only system that lets voters rank individual candidates in order of preference.]]\nRural\u2013urban proportional is a hybrid-proportional system designed by [[Fair Vote Canada]] to meet the challenges of Canada's geography.<ref name=\"fairvote-ru\">{{cite web|last=[[Fair Vote Canada]]|url=https://www.fairvote.ca/rural-urban-proportional/|title=Rural\u2013Urban Proportional|work=Fair Vote Canada|date=2018|access-date=25 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724151135/https://www.fairvote.ca/rural-urban-proportional/#|archive-date=24 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"fed-report\" /> As put forward for the BC referendum, it would use mixed-member proportional representation (MMP) in rural areas and the single transferable vote (STV) in urban and semi-urban areas.<ref name=\"systems\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/rural-urban-proportional-rup/ |title=Rural-Urban Proportional (RUP) |publisher=[[Elections BC]] |website=elections.bc.ca |access-date=20 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821093858/https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/rural-urban-proportional-rup/# |archive-date=21 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4242810/british-columbians-will-vote-on-our-electoral-system-here-are-the-4-options/ |title=British Columbians will vote on our electoral system \u2014 Here are the 4 options |last=Zussman |first=Richard |work=[[Global News]] |date=May 30, 2018 |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615004254/https://globalnews.ca/news/4242810/british-columbians-will-vote-on-our-electoral-system-here-are-the-4-options/# |archive-date=15 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Sweden, Denmark and Iceland use voting models with similar hybrid approaches. In Canada from the 1920s to the 1950s, the provinces of Alberta and Manitoba used a hybrid rural\u2013urban system where STV was used in large cities and the [[instant-runoff voting|alternative vote]] was used in single-member rural districts.<ref name=\"pdennis\"/>{{rp|81\u201382}}<ref name=\"fairvote-ru\"/><ref>{{Cite book| publisher = University of Michigan Press| isbn = 978-0-472-11159-6| editor1-last = Bowler| editor1-first = Shaun| editor2-last = Grofman| editor2-first = Bernard| title = Elections in Australia, Ireland, and Malta under the Single Transferable Vote| date = 2000| doi = 10.3998/mpub.16507| jstor = 10.3998/mpub.16507}}</ref>\n\nThe hybrid approach taken by rural\u2013urban proportional reflects lessons learned from previous attempts to pass electoral reform.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-bcs-proportional-representation-voting-system-options-include-two |title=BC's proportional representation voting system options include two that are lesser known |last=Dhillon |first=Sunny |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=June 17, 2018 |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621183227/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-bcs-proportional-representation-voting-system-options-include-two/# |archive-date=21 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> A major advantage of rural\u2013urban proportional as designed is that it requires creating far fewer top-up seats to achieve proportionality than MMP. Under rural\u2013urban PR, no more than 10\u201315% of seats \u2013 versus 40% of seats under MMP \u2013 would need to be set aside as top-up seats to achieve proportionality, because the results from the urban and semi-urban areas would already be proportional owing to their voting having been conducted using STV.\n\nFor rural areas, rural\u2013urban proportional is advantageous because existing first-past-the-post rural ridings need to grow only 15% larger to facilitate extra regional top-up seats under it, compared to 67% larger if MMP was chosen or double in size if DMP was chosen.<ref name=\"fairvote-ru\" />\n\nRUP is the only PR system of the three that lets voters rank individual candidates in order by preference. The use of STV ranked ballots means that all candidates must compete with one another for a voter's coveted first place ranking, including candidates running for the same party. Voters can rank long-shot independent candidates or candidates from unpopular parties first without fear of wasting their vote, because votes for badly performing candidates will be transferred during counting\u2014based on each voter's preferences\u2014to candidates who have yet to be eliminated, until all seats are won.\n\nIn its scorecard of proportional voting systems, Fair Voting BC gave rural\u2013urban proportional its highest ranking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fairvotingbc.com/scorecard/|title=Scorecard|author=Fair Voting BC|access-date=3 July 2018|publisher=Fair Voting BC|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704092834/https://fairvotingbc.com/scorecard/#|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> During the [[Government of Canada|Canadian government's]] 2016 consultation on electoral reform at the federal level,<ref name=\"fed-report\" /> both the [[New Democratic Party|New Democratic Party of Canada]] and [[Green Party of Canada]] recommended Canada adopt either RUP or MMP.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/wherry-electoral-reform-committee-1.3866879|title=Minister 'disappointed' as electoral reform committee recommends referendum on proportional representation|last1=Wherry|first1=Aaron|last2=Tasker|first2=John Paul|work=[[CBC News]]|date=December 1, 2016|access-date=25 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412133850/http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/wherry-electoral-reform-committee-1.3866879#|archive-date=12 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Campaign==\nThe official campaign began July 1, 2018.<ref name=\"regulation\" /> Groups had until July 6 to apply to Elections BC to be named the official proponent or opponent groups and receive $500,000 in public funding.<ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Referendum Funding |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referenda/2018-referendum-funding/ |access-date=26 June 2018 |publisher=Elections BC |website=elections.bc.ca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627034318/https://elections.bc.ca/referenda/2018-referendum-funding/# |archive-date=27 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>  On July 12, Elections BC announced that Vote PR BC would be the official proponent group and No BC Proportional Representation Society would be the official opponent group.<ref>{{cite news |last=[[The Canadian Press]] |title=Yes and No groups selected before B.C.'s electoral reform referendum |url=https://bc.ctvnews.ca/yes-and-no-groups-selected-before-b-c-s-electoral-reform-referendum-1.4010867 |date=July 12, 2018 |access-date=14 July 2018 |work=[[CTV News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713191957/https://bc.ctvnews.ca/yes-and-no-groups-selected-before-b-c-s-electoral-reform-referendum-1.4010867# |archive-date=13 July 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Referendum Funding |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referenda/2018-referendum-funding/ |access-date=14 July 2018 |publisher=Elections BC |website=elections.bc.ca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627034318/https://elections.bc.ca/referenda/2018-referendum-funding/# |archive-date=27 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Other individuals, groups and political parties are permitted to register as referendum advertisers with Elections BC, but are not eligible for public funds.<ref name=\"regulation\" />\n\nThe NDP and Green Party campaigned for proportional representation. [[Sonia Furstenau]], a Green [[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia|MLA]], held town halls about electoral reform in cities across the province in July and August.<ref>{{cite news |last=Slack |first=Jeff |title=Green Party MLA holding forum on Electoral Reform in PG |url=https://www.myprincegeorgenow.com/80016/green-party-mla-holding-forum-on-electoral-reform-in-pg/ |date=July 19, 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |work=My Prince George Now |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908015902/https://www.myprincegeorgenow.com/80016/green-party-mla-holding-forum-on-electoral-reform-in-pg/# |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Staff |title=Green MLA Furstenau visits Nelson-Creston riding |url=http://thenelsondaily.com/news/green-mla-furstenau-visits-nelson-creston-riding#.W5LKksInaUk |date=August 21, 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |work=Nelson Daily |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908092736/http://thenelsondaily.com/news/green-mla-furstenau-visits-nelson-creston-riding#.W5LKksInaUk#.W5LKksInaUk |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Eckford |first=Sean |title=Simons and Green MLAs discuss PR, cooperation |url=https://www.coastreporter.net/news/local-news/simons-and-green-mlas-discuss-pr-cooperation-1.23412249 |date=August 24, 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |work=Coast Reporter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908092817/https://www.coastreporter.net/news/local-news/simons-and-green-mlas-discuss-pr-cooperation-1.23412249# |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Premier of British Columbia|BC Premier]] [[John Horgan]] launched the NDP's referendum campaign in early September, saying \"Proportional representation means exactly what it says. Whatever proportion, or share, of the vote a party wins, they get that many seats in government.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Palmer |first=Vaughn |title=Horgan selling positives of electoral change, but there are negatives |url=https://vancouversun.com/opinion/columnists/vaughn-palmer-horgan-selling-positives-of-electoral-change-but-there-are-negatives |date=September 7, 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |work=[[Vancouver Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907082937/https://vancouversun.com/opinion/columnists/vaughn-palmer-horgan-selling-positives-of-electoral-change-but-there-are-negatives# |archive-date=7 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Andrew Wilkinson]], BC Liberal leader, opposed the referendum and a change to a proportional representation system.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smyth |first=Mike |title=B.C. Liberals declare all-out war on proportional representation |url=https://theprovince.com/opinion/columnists/mike-smyth-liberals-declare-all-out-war-on-proportional-representation |date=June 3, 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |work=[[The Province]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908092836/https://theprovince.com/opinion/columnists/mike-smyth-liberals-declare-all-out-war-on-proportional-representation# |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nElections BC mailed a referendum information card to every household in the province between September 10 and 28, and a voter's guide between October 15 and 26.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fletcher |first=Tom |title=Voter registration push begins for B.C. referendum |url=https://www.castlegarnews.com/news/voter-registration-push-begins-for-b-c-referendum/ |date=September 10, 2018 |access-date=10 September 2018 |work=Castlegar News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911045135/https://www.castlegarnews.com/news/voter-registration-push-begins-for-b-c-referendum/# |archive-date=11 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=EBCmail /> Voters received their referendum voting package in the mail between October 22 and November 2.<ref name=EBCmail>{{cite web |title=Referendum Resources |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/referendum-resources/ |access-date=11 September 2018 |publisher=Elections BC |website=elections.bc.ca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908015803/https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/referendum-resources/# |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In early September, the members of the [[Canadian Union of Postal Workers]] voted in favour of job action. The strike resulted in Elections BC extending the voting deadline by a week.<ref name=\"extension\" />\n\nIn early November, Horgan announced that he had cast his ballot for proportional representation, and that his first choice was MMP.<ref>{{cite news |last=CBC News |title=John Horgan: I voted for mixed-member proportional in electoral reform referendum |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/john-horgan-i-voted-for-mixed-member-proportional-in-electoral-reform-referendum-1.4888430 |date=November 1, 2018 |access-date=5 November 2018 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104053556/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/john-horgan-i-voted-for-mixed-member-proportional-in-electoral-reform-referendum-1.4888430# |archive-date=4 November 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>  Vote PR BC, the official proponent group, flew Andrew Coyne to Vancouver to give a talk endorsing PR, where Coyne announced he supported Rural\u2013Urban Proportional.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/voteprbc/photos/a.228311341063875/337164366845238/|title=Tomorrow noted political commentator @ACoyne joins us for a lively discussion on Pro Rep. Are you planning on taking part? RSVP here to attend: #PR4BC #ProRep #BCPoli|date=October 24, 2018|website=Facebook|access-date=8 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nationalpost.com/opinion/andrew-coyne-which-electoral-system-for-b-c-any-option-is-better-than-the-status-quo |title=Andrew Coyne: Which electoral system for B.C.? Any option is better than the status quo |last=Coyne |first=Andrew |date=2018-10-30 |work=National Post |access-date=12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Debate ===\nIn late September, Andrew Wilkinson challenged John Horgan to a debate concerning the referendum, a challenge which Horgan accepted. The debate took place on November 8 at 7:00{{Nbsp}}pm. It was broadcast on [[CBC News]] and [[Global News]].<ref>{{cite news |last=CBC News |title=B.C. premier, opposition leader to face off in electoral reform debate |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/events/premier-opposition-leader-electoral-reform-debate-1.4883872 |date=October 30, 2018 |access-date=31 October 2018 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030223159/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/events/premier-opposition-leader-electoral-reform-debate-1.4883872# |archive-date=30 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Official campaign organizations===\nOfficial campaign organizations include the official proponent and opponent groups along with referendum advertising sponsors.<ref name=RefSponsors>{{cite web |title=2018 Referendum Advertising Sponsors |url=https://elections.bc.ca/docs/referendum/2018-Referendum-Advertising-Sponsors.pdf |accessdate=8 December 2018 |publisher=Elections BC |website=elections.bc.ca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181208221641/https://elections.bc.ca/docs/referendum/2018-Referendum-Advertising-Sponsors.pdf |archive-date=8 December 2018 |url-status=live  |date=December 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Official proponent and opponent groups====\n\n* Proponent: Vote PR BC\n* Opponent: No BC Proportional Representation Society\n\n====Referendum advertising sponsors====\n* Asian Environmental Association\n* [[British Columbia Conservative Party]]\n* [[British Columbia Government and Service Employees' Union]]\n* British Columbia Liberal Party\n* British Columbia New Democratic Party\n* Committee for Voting Equity in BC\n* [[Communist Party of British Columbia]]\n* [[Dogwood Initiative]]\n* Fair Vote Canada BC\n* Fraser Valley East Against Proportional Representation\n* Green Party Political Association of British Columbia\n* KnowB4UVote.com Society\n* [[LeadNow]]\n* No Pro Rep Fraser Valley East \n* Rural\u2013Urban Proportional for BC\n* Wake Up BC\n* Wildsight\n* Wise Vote BC\n* YES or NO, Rural Urban First\n\n==Voting period extension==\nOn November 23, 2018, due to a postal strike, Elections BC extended the voting period deadline by a week \u2013 from November 30, 2018, to December 7, 2018.<ref name=\"extension\">{{cite news |title=Voting period for electoral reform referendum extended due to postal strike |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/electoral-referendum-deadline-extended-1.4918055 |access-date=23 November 2018 |work=CBC News |date=November 23, 2018}}</ref> The deadline to register to vote remained midnight on November 23, 2018. Voters who were sent a voting package but did not receive it, or who need a replacement voting package, could request a replacement package up to December 7. All ballots must have been received by Elections BC by 4:30{{Nbsp}}pm on December 7.<ref>https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/how-to-vote</ref> In response to a question from a constituent on [[Twitter]], Elections BC clarified that ballots received by Elections BC's Referendum Service Offices or Service BC Centres up to and including 4:30{{Nbsp}}pm on December 7, 2018, but which had not been physically transferred to Elections BC's counting centre, would be accepted and counted as valid ballots.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=ElectionsBC |number=1073637787738357761 |date=December 14, 2018 |access-date=December 19, 2018 |author=Elections BC |author-link=Elections BC |title=Hi Doug \u2013 Yes, completed voting packages received by Elections BC by mail or in person at a Referendum Service Office or Service BC Centre by 4:30 p.m. on December 7, 2018 were accepted for counting.}}</ref>\n\n==Post-referendum plans==\n\nThe government had plans for the required next steps had proportional representation passed. However, as it did not pass, the government will not implement any of these steps.  Had a proportional system been adopted, the independent [[British Columbia Electoral Boundaries Commission|BC Electoral Boundaries Commission]] would have determined the number and location of new electoral districts. A legislative committee would have been tasked with determining whether the number of members of the Legislative Assembly should increase, and if so by how many (to a maximum of an additional eight). Some other aspects of how the new system would have worked would have also needed to be determined by a legislative committee.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/what-are-we-voting-on/ |title=What happens after the referendum? |website=elections.bc.ca |publisher=[[Elections BC]] |access-date=24 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825073911/https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/what-are-we-voting-on/# |archive-date=25 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIf a form of proportional representation had been adopted, the government had also committed to holding a further confirming referendum after two general elections.<ref name=\"2018report\" /><ref name=\"PremierStatement\" /> Voters in that future referendum would have had the option of maintaining the form of proportional representation adopted or switching back to the first-past-the-post electoral system.<ref name=\"Tyee?s\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4259321/bc-electoral-reform-referendum-format/|title=B.C. cabinet confirms format of electoral reform referendum|last=Zussman|first=Richard|work=[[Global News]]|date=June 7, 2018|access-date=25 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612165225/https://globalnews.ca/news/4259321/bc-electoral-reform-referendum-format/#|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 2, 2018, the government introduced legislation to enact the requirement for this second referendum into law. If a change from the first-past-the-post system had been adopted in 2018, the bill would have required a second referendum on electoral reform to occur within 13 months of the second provincial general election held under the chosen proportional representation voting system (no later than November 30, 2026). As voters decided to keep the existing first-past-the-post system, this second referendum will not take place.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4509590/b-c-government-second-referendum-electoral-reform/ |title=B.C. Government to legislate a second referendum on electoral reform if new system passes |last=Zussman |first=Richard |work=[[Global News]] |date=October 2, 2018 |access-date=3 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002223022/https://globalnews.ca/news/4509590/b-c-government-second-referendum-electoral-reform/# |archive-date=2 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cheknews.ca/legislation-proposed-for-a-confirming-referendum-if-b-c-voters-choose-proportional-representation-494941/|title=Legislation proposed for a confirming referendum if B.C. voters choose proportional representation|last=CHEK News|work=[[CHEK-DT|CHEK News]]|date=October 2, 2018|access-date=3 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004103735/https://www.cheknews.ca/legislation-proposed-for-a-confirming-referendum-if-b-c-voters-choose-proportional-representation-494941/#|archive-date=4 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Opinion polls==\n\n===Question 1===\n\nReferendum-style binary question<br />Question: \"Based on what you know, please indicate which of these two broad options you prefer for BC\"\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Polling firm\n!Last date of polling\n!A new system of proportional representation\n!The current first-past-the-post system\n! {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|Angus Reid\n|June 20, 2017\n|59%\n|41%\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://angusreid.org/bc-post-election/|title=Snap Election? Snap out of it, say majority of British Columbians - Angus Reid Institute|date=2017-06-17|work=Angus Reid Institute|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023080258/http://angusreid.org/bc-post-election/#|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|Angus Reid\n|Sept 26, 2017\n|65%\n|35%\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://angusreid.org/horgan-ndp-electoral-reform-energy-projects/|title=British Columbians call on new provincial government to deliver electoral reform, energy projects - Angus Reid Institute|date=2017-09-25|work=Angus Reid Institute|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023080256/http://angusreid.org/horgan-ndp-electoral-reform-energy-projects/#|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|Angus Reid\n|December 31, 2017\n|57%\n|43%\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://angusreid.org/site-c-horgan/|title=Site C: By margin of two-to-one, BC residents say province made the right call to finish dam project - Angus Reid Institute|date=2018-01-11|work=Angus Reid Institute|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023080253/http://angusreid.org/site-c-horgan/#|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|Angus Reid\n|May 9, 2018\n|57%\n|43%\n|<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://angusreid.org/bc-ndp-one-year/# |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929194838/http://angusreid.org/bc-ndp-one-year/# |archive-date=29 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|Angus Reid\n|September 17, 2018\n|57%\n|43%\n||<ref name=\"Angus Reid Institute\">{{Cite news|url=http://angusreid.org/bc-electoral-reform-referendum/|title=Proportional Representation: BC residents split three ways over whether to change voting system - Angus Reid Institute|date=2018-09-27|work=Angus Reid Institute|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930125415/http://angusreid.org/bc-electoral-reform-referendum/#|archive-date=30 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://angusreid.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/2018.09.17-VotingSystems-National-ReleaseTables.pdf|title=National release tables - Angus Reid Survey September 9 2017|website=angusreid.org|access-date=26 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023080259/http://angusreid.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/2018.09.17-VotingSystems-National-ReleaseTables.pdf#|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|Mainstreet\n|November 8, 2018\n|49.5%\n|50.5%\n|<ref name=\"Mainstreet Nov 8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/392643708/Mainstreet-Bc-Nov8 |title=Mainstreet Research - BC UltraPoll Release|date=2018-11-08|work=Mainstreet|access-date=15 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n|}\n\nMultiple choice question allowing undecideds and opt-outs (options 3\u20135 will not be present on ballot)<br />Question: \"Based on how you feel right now, if you were to receive a voting package, which way would you vote on the first question?\"\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Polling firm !! Last date of polling !! The current first past the post voting system !! A proportional representation voting system\n!Undecided / Not sure\n!Would not vote on this particular question\n!Would ignore the voting package altogether!!{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| Angus Reid || September 18, 2018 || 31% || 33%\n|33%\n|1%\n|2%||<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://angusreid.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/2018.09.18-BC-Electoral-Reform-VoteIntention-ReleaseTables.pdf# |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023120010/http://angusreid.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/2018.09.18-BC-Electoral-Reform-VoteIntention-ReleaseTables.pdf# |archive-date=23 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Angus Reid Institute\"/>\n|-\n|Google Survey\n|November 6, 2018\n|19.7%\n|19.8%\n|43.5%\n|n/a\n|17.1\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tooclosetocall.ca/2018/11/exclusive-poll-referendum-on-electoral.html|title=Too Close To Call: Exclusive poll: The referendum on electoral reform in BC is a toss-up|last=Breguet|first=Bryan|work=Too Close To Call|access-date=20 November 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Question 2===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Polling firm !! Last date of polling !! Mixed-Member Proportional !! Rural\u2013Urban Proportional !! Dual Member Proportional !! Notes !! {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| Angus Reid || September 28, 2018 || 49% || 26%  || 24% ||{{Small|Percentage breakdown shows preference among decided voters; 54% of people polled report being undecided on which system to choose.}}||<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://angusreid.org/bc-electoral-reform-referendum/# |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929194852/http://angusreid.org/bc-electoral-reform-referendum/# |archive-date=29 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| Mainstreet Research || November 8, 2018 || 44.8% || 38.2%  || 17% ||{{Small|RUP has large lead in interior BC. MMP and RUP tied on Vancouver Island. MMP leading in Metro Vancouver.}}||<ref name=\"Mainstreet Nov 8\"/>\n|}\n\n==Results==\n\nOn December 20, 2018, [[Elections BC]] announced that 61.3% of ballots were cast to maintain the first-past-the-post voting system.<ref name=\"electionsbcresults\">\n{{ cite web | url=https://electionsbcca.blob.core.windows.net/electionsbcca/referendum/results.html | title=2018 Referendum Voting Results | website=Elections BC | date=2018-12-20 | accessdate=2018-12-20 }}</ref><ref name=\"electionsbcresultsPDF\">\n{{ cite web | url=https://electionsbcca.blob.core.windows.net/electionsbcca/referendum/2018REF-prov-summary.pdf | title=2018 Referendum on Electoral Reform - Provincial Results | website=Elections BC | date=2018-12-20 | accessdate=2018-12-20 }}</ref><ref>\n{{ cite web | url=https://www.thestar.com/vancouver/2018/12/20/no-wins-61-per-cent-of-the-vote-in-proportional-representation-referendum-elections-bc-announces.html | title='No' wins 61 per cent of the vote in proportional representation referendum, Elections BC announces | date=2018-12-20 | last=Ball | first=David | work=The Star | access-date=2018-12-20}}</ref><ref>\n{{ cite web | url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/b-c-s-electoral-reform-referendum-results-to-be-released-at-230-p-m | title=No change: B.C. voters back first-past-the-post system in electoral reform referendum | date=2018-12-20 | last=Eagland | first=Nick | work=Vancouver Sun | access-date=2018-12-20}}</ref><ref>\n{{ cite web | url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/electoral-reform-referendum-results-1.4954538 | title=B.C. votes to keep first-past-the-post electoral system | date=2018-12-20 | work=CBC News | access-date=2018-12-20 | quote=\"Elections BC announced the results Thursday, saying 61.3 per cent of ballots had been cast in favour of the status quo, while proportional representation got 38.7 per cent.\" }}</ref>\n\nA total of 1,391,423 ballots were considered. There were 1,378,753 valid votes for Question 1, and 831,760 valid votes for Question 2. 2,461 ballots were rejected.<ref name=\"electionsbcresults\" /><ref name=\"electionsbcresultsPDF\" />\n\n===Question 1===\n\nThe existing first-past-the-post voting system received a majority of votes with 61.30% (845,235) of the valid votes for Question 1.<ref name=\"electionsbcresults\" /><ref name=\"electionsbcresultsPDF\" /> As a result, no electoral reform was approved.\n\nQuestion 1: Which system should British Columbia use for provincial elections?\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!System\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|The current First Past the Post voting system\n|845,235\n|61.30%\n|-\n|A proportional representation voting system\n|533,518\n|38.70%\n|-\n!Total valid votes\n!1,378,753\n!100.0%\n|-\n|Invalid votes\n|10,209\n! rowspan=\"3\" |\n|-\n|Rejected ballots\n|2,461\n|-\n!Total ballots\n!1,391,423\n|}\n\n===Question 2===\n\nPer the Electoral Reform Referendum 2018 Regulation, STV rules were in effect to find the winner in Question 2 (although the question was moot as no electoral reform would take place as per the result of Question 1). Thus, when no system won a majority of first preferences, a second round of counting was required for Question 2. RUP had the fewest first preferences, so it was eliminated and its votes were transferred to the second preferences marked on the ballots.<ref name=\"electionsbcresults\" /><ref name=\"electionsbcresultsPDF\" /> In the second count, the mixed-member proportional voting system had the most support on Question 2.<ref name=\"electionsbcresults\" /><ref name=\"electionsbcresultsPDF\" />\n\nQuestion 2: If British Columbia adopts a proportional representation voting system, which of the following voting systems do you prefer?\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!\n! colspan=\"3\" | Round 1\n! colspan=\"2\" | Round 2\n|-\n!System\n!Votes\n!%\n!Transfers\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|Dual-Member Proportional (DMP)\n|244,973\n|29.45%\n| +43,095\n|288,068\n|36.95% \n|-\n|Mixed-Member Proportional (MMP)\n|343,038\n|41.24%\n| +148,592\n|491,630\n|63.05% \n|-\n|Rural\u2013Urban Proportional (RUP)\n|243,749\n|29.31%\n| -243,749\n! colspan=\"2\" |\n|-\n!Total continuing ballots\n!831,760\n!100.00%\n! -52,062\n!779,698\n!100.00% \n|-\n|Exhausted ballots\n|\n|\n|\n|52,062\n! rowspan=\"5\" |\n|-\n!Total valid votes\n!831,760\n!\n!\n!831,760\n|-\n|Invalid votes\n|557,202\n|\n|\n|557,202 \n|-\n|Rejected ballots\n|2,461\n|\n|\n|2,461 \n|-\n!Total ballots considered\n!1,391,423\n!\n!\n!1,391,423 \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://engage.gov.bc.ca/howwevote/ How We Vote Consultation website]\n* [https://elections.bc.ca/referenda/ Elections BC Referendum 2018 website]\n* [https://electionsbcca.blob.core.windows.net/electionsbcca/referendum/2018-Referendum-Voting-Results-By-ED.xlsx Voting results by electoral district] \u2013 from Elections BC\n* [https://voteprbc.ca/ Vote PR BC] \u2013 Official Proponent Group\n* [https://www.nobcprorep.ca/ No Pro Rep] \u2013 Official Opponent Group\n* [https://www.fairvote.ca/pr4bc/ Fair Vote Canada BC] \u2013 Organization supporting the adoption of proportional representation in BC\n* [https://www.facebook.com/rupforbc/ Rural\u2013Urban Proportional for BC] \u2013 Group supporting rural\u2013urban proportional representation\n\n{{British Columbia elections}}\n\n[[Category:2018 in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:2018 referendums]]\n[[Category:October 2018 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:November 2018 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Referendums in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Multiple-choice referendums]]\n[[Category:Electoral reform referendums in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|referendum on British Columbia's voting system}}\n{{Infobox multichoice referendum \n| name        = British Columbia electoral reform referendum \n| map         = British_Columbia_Electoral_Reform_Referendum_2018_-_Question_1_Results_by_Riding.svg\n| mapcaption = Question 1 results by electoral district (green: FPTP; red: PR)\n| mapdivision  = electoral district\n| title       = Which system should British Columbia use for provincial elections?\n| location    = [[British Columbia]], Canada\n| date        = {{Start date|2018|10|22}} \u2013 {{End date|2018|12|7}}\n| choice1 = The current First Past the Post voting system\n| percentage1 = 61.3\n| choice2 = A proportional representation voting system\n| percentage2 = 38.7\n| status = complete\n}}\n\nA referendum on [[electoral reform]] took place by [[postal ballot|mail-in ballot]] between October 22 and December 7, 2018, in the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Canadian province]] of [[British Columbia]]. This was British Columbia's third referendum on electoral reform since 2005.\n\nVoters were asked two questions: first, what electoral system should be used to determine election results\u2014the existing [[first-past-the-post]] (FPTP) system or a [[proportional representation]] (PR) system; and second, what type of proportional voting system should be used if PR is chosen. In the second question, voters were asked to rank three proportional representation voting systems: [[dual-member proportional representation]], [[mixed-member proportional representation]], and [[rural\u2013urban proportional representation]].\n\nThe referendum fulfilled an election commitment by the [[British Columbia New Democratic Party]] (NDP) during the 2017 election. Their platform promised a referendum and that the government would actively campaign for electoral reform.\n\nResults were released by [[Elections BC]] on December 20, 2018. British Columbians voted in favour of maintaining the first-past-the-post voting system rather than switching to a proportional representation voting system.\n\n==Background==\nBC has a long history of changing its electoral system. For BC's first election in 1871, the majority of ridings were elected using an \"at large\" system. This is the way city councillors are elected in BC to this day: a voter gets as many votes as there were people to be elected in the riding.<ref name=1871-1986>{{cite web |last=[[Elections BC|Elections British Columbia]] |title=Electoral History of British Columbia 1871\u20131986 |date=1988 |url=http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/1871-1986_ElectoralHistoryofBC.pdf |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613200446/http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/1871-1986_ElectoralHistoryofBC.pdf# |archive-date=13 June 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOver its history, BC modified its electoral system at least 15 times without a referendum.<ref name=1871-1986 /> It previously used an [[Instant-runoff voting|alternative voting system]] in the [[1952 British Columbia general election|1952 provincial election]] before abolishing it and reestablishing the previous mix of \"at large\" and first-past-the-post.<ref name=\"pdennis\">{{Cite book |title=The politics of voting : reforming Canada's electoral system |last=Pilon |first=Dennis |date=2007 |publisher=Emond Montgomery Publications |isbn=9781552392362 |location=Toronto |oclc=150223313}}</ref>{{rp|81\u201382}}<ref>{{cite web |last=[[Elections BC|Elections British Columbia]] |title=Electoral History of British Columbia 1871\u20131986 |date=1988 |url=http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/1871-1986_ElectoralHistoryofBC.pdf |access-date=21 June 2018 |pages=231\u2013232 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613200446/http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/1871-1986_ElectoralHistoryofBC.pdf# |archive-date=13 June 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> The first BC election done entirely under first-past-the-post came in 1991, after the last \"at-large\" voting districts had been abolished.<ref name=\"pdennis\"/>{{rp|76}}<ref>{{cite web |last=[[Elections BC]] |title=Electoral History of B.C. |date=2018 |url=http://elections.bc.ca/resources/learning-about-elections/electoral-history-of-bc/ |access-date=25 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626030841/http://elections.bc.ca/resources/learning-about-elections/electoral-history-of-bc/# |archive-date=26 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The multi-member at-large ridings were abolished after the 1986 election due to a Supreme Court of Canada ruling that found them unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite web |last=[[Elections BC]] |title=Electoral History of B.C. |date=2018 |url=http://elections.bc.ca/resources/learning-about-elections/electoral-history-of-bc/}}</ref>\n\n\n===Previous referendums===\nBefore the [[2001 British Columbia general election|2001 provincial election]], the [[British Columbia Liberal Party|BC Liberal Party]] committed to appoint a [[Citizens' Assembly on Electoral Reform (British Columbia)|Citizens' Assembly]] to investigate electoral reform, hold consultations, and prepare a report recommending whether a different [[electoral system]] should be adopted.<ref name=CAReport>{{cite web |title=Making Every Vote Count: The Case for Electoral Reform in British Columbia |url=http://www.citizensassembly.bc.ca:80/resources/final_report.pdf |date=December 2004 |access-date=15 June 2018 |author=[[Citizens' Assembly on Electoral Reform (British Columbia)|British Columbia Citizens' Assembly on Electoral Reform]] |publisher=Government of British Columbia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050513192722/http://www.citizensassembly.bc.ca/resources/final_report.pdf# |archive-date=13 May 2005}}</ref> The commitment was driven in part by the anomalous provincial election result in [[1996 British Columbia general election|1996]], in which the BC New Democratic Party won reelection as a majority government with 39.5% of the vote and 39 seats, despite gaining a 3% smaller share of the popular vote than the Liberals at 41.8%, which translated into 33 Liberal seats.<ref name=\"pdennis\"/>{{rp|90\u201391}} In December 2004, the Assembly released its report recommending that the province adopt [[BC-STV]], a BC-specific variant of the [[single transferable vote]] (STV) system.<ref name=CAReport /> On May 17, 2005, a [[2005 British Columbia electoral reform referendum|referendum]] was held in conjunction with the [[2005 British Columbia general election|2005 general election]], in which voters were asked whether the province should adopt the recommendation of the Assembly to replace the first-past-the-post electoral system with BC-STV, or maintain the current system. While 57.7% of the electorate voted in favour of BC-STV, including a majority of voters in 77 of 79 ridings, its support failed to reach the 60% threshold set by the government and it was not adopted.<ref>{{cite web |last=Elections BC |title=Statement of Votes \u2013 Referendum on Electoral Reform |date=May 17, 2005 |page=9 |url=http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/SOV-2005-ReferendumOnElectoralReform.pdf |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220152639/http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/SOV-2005-ReferendumOnElectoralReform.pdf# |archive-date=20 February 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2005 referendum, British Columbia held [[2009 British Columbia electoral reform referendum|a second referendum]] on electoral reform in conjunction with the [[2009 British Columbia general election|provincial election]] on May 12, 2009. It was the most recent referendum on electoral reform that has been held in British Columbia. As in 2005, voters in 2009 were asked to provide their opinions on the BC-STV electoral system proposed by the [[Citizens' Assembly on Electoral Reform (British Columbia)|British Columbia Citizen's Assembly on Electoral Reform]] to ensure more proportional representation in the [[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia|provincial Legislative Assembly]]. British Columbians were asked which electoral system should be used to elect legislators: the existing first-past-the-post electoral system or the proposed BC-STV system.\n\nThe adoption of BC-STV in the 2009 referendum was defeated, with 60.9% voting against the reform and 39.09% of voters supporting the change.<ref>{{cite web |last=Elections BC |title=Statement of Votes \u2013 Referendum on Electoral Reform |date=May 12, 2009 |page=20 |url=http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/2009Ref/2009-Ref-SOV.pdf |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423200639/http://elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/2009Ref/2009-Ref-SOV.pdf# |archive-date=23 April 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Intervening federal developments===\nDuring the [[2015 Canadian federal election|2015 federal election]], [[Justin Trudeau]] and the [[Liberal Party of Canada]] campaigned on the promise that it would be the last federal election under the first-past-the-post electoral system. The party's platform stated that a Liberal government would form an all-party Parliamentary committee, and introduce legislation within 18 months enacting electoral reform.<ref>{{cite web |title=Electoral reform |url=https://www.liberal.ca/realchange/electoral-reform/ |website=Real Change |publisher=Liberal Party of Canada |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621194408/https://www.liberal.ca/realchange/electoral-reform/# |archive-date=21 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"2part-question\">{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/news-pmn/canada-news-pmn/b-c-electoral-reform-referendum-includes-two-part-ballot-question|title=B.C. electoral reform referendum includes two-part ballot question|last=Meissner|first=Dirk|date=May 30, 2018|work=[[The National Post]]|access-date=4 June 2018}}</ref> On December 1, 2016, the [[Canadian House of Commons Special Committee on Electoral Reform|House of Commons of Canada Special Committee on Electoral Reform]] released its report recommending Canada hold a referendum to adopt a proportional representation voting system for federal elections.<ref name=\"fed-report\">{{cite report |author=Special Committee on Electoral Reform |date=December 1, 2016 |title=Strengthening Democracy in Canada: Principles, Process and Public Engagement for Electoral Reform |url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?DocId=8655791&Language=E&Mode=1&Parl=42&Ses=1 |publisher=Parliament of Canada |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408092349/http://www.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?Language=e&Mode=1&Parl=42&Ses=1&DocId=8655791# |archive-date=8 April 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Several months later, the government announced that it was no longer pursuing electoral reform.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stone |first=Laura |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/trudeau-abandons-electoral-reform/article33855925/ |title=Trudeau abandons electoral reform, breaking key campaign promise |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |access-date=6 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205160959/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/trudeau-abandons-electoral-reform/article33855925/# |archive-date=5 February 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Joanna |title=Trudeau abandons promise for electoral reform |url=http://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/trudeau-abandons-promise-for-electoral-reform/ |access-date=21 June 2018 |work=Maclean's |agency=The Canadian Press |date=February 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209174029/http://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/trudeau-abandons-promise-for-electoral-reform/# |archive-date=9 February 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Origin of third referendum===\nDuring the [[2017 British Columbia general election|2017 provincial election]], both the NDP and the [[Green Party of British Columbia|Green Party]] campaigned for PR and included the policy in their election platforms.<ref name=\"NDPplatform\">{{cite web |title=Platform 2017 |url=https://action.bcndp.ca/page/-/bcndp/docs/BC-NDP-Platform-2017.pdf |website=bcndp.ca |publisher=BC NDP |access-date=30 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510162021/https://action.bcndp.ca/page/-/bcndp/docs/BC-NDP-Platform-2017.pdf# |archive-date=10 May 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bc-election-aftermath-electoral-reform-1.4122921 |title=B.C. parties leave door open to electoral reform without a referendum |last=Omand |first=Geordon |work=[[CBC News]] |date=May 18, 2017 |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180604094829/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bc-election-aftermath-electoral-reform-1.4122921# |archive-date=4 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=BC Green Party |title=Change You Can Count On: Platform 2017 |date=2017 |url=https://www.bcgreens.ca/platform |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140957/https://www.bcgreens.ca/platform# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> On May 29, 2017, approximately three weeks after the election resulted in a [[British Columbia Liberal Party|BC Liberal]] [[minority government]], the NDP and Green caucuses signed a [[Confidence and supply|supply and confidence]] agreement.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bc-ndp-green-agreement-1.4136539 |title=B.C. Green Party agrees to support NDP in the legislature |last=McElroy |first=Justin |work=[[CBC News]] |date=May 29, 2017 |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180605094150/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bc-ndp-green-agreement-1.4136539# |archive-date=5 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The agreement included a section on PR, in which the parties agreed to put the issue to a referendum and that both parties would actively campaign for PR in the referendum.<ref>{{cite web |last=BC NDP Caucus |title=2017 Confidence and Supply Agreement between the BC Green Caucus and the BC New Democrat Caucus |date=May 30, 2017 |url=http://bcndpcaucus.ca/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2017/05/BC-Green-BC-NDP-Agreement_vf-May-29th-2017.pdf |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712183901/http://bcndpcaucus.ca/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2017/05/BC-Green-BC-NDP-Agreement_vf-May-29th-2017.pdf# |archive-date=12 July 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/whats-ahead-for-bc-politics-after-the-ndp-green-partyagreement/article35160029/ |title=The road ahead for B.C. politics |last=Hipolito |first=Chad |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=May 31, 2018 |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813154305/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/whats-ahead-for-bc-politics-after-the-ndp-green-partyagreement/article35160029/# |archive-date=13 August 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> On June 22, 2017, the Liberal government tabled its [[throne speech]], adopting the opposition parties' policy to hold a third referendum on electoral reform.<ref>{{cite web |last=Meissner |first=Dirk |title=B.C. Throne Speech: Clark's Liberals Promise Electoral Reform Referendum, Sales Tax Cut |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2017/06/22/b-c-throne-speech-clarks-liberals-promise-electoral-reform-re_a_22583513/ |access-date=11 June 2018 |date=June 23, 2017 |work=[[Huffington Post Canada]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141218/https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2017/06/22/b-c-throne-speech-clarks-liberals-promise-electoral-reform-re_a_22583513/# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Speech from the Throne |url=https://www.leg.bc.ca/parliamentary-business/legislation-debates-proceedings/41st-parliament/1st-session/throne-speech |access-date=11 June 2018 |date=June 22, 2017 |publisher=[[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141507/https://www.leg.bc.ca/parliamentary-business/legislation-debates-proceedings/41st-parliament/1st-session/throne-speech# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> On June 29, 2017, the BC Liberal government was defeated in a [[confidence and supply|confidence vote]]. [[Lieutenant Governor of British Columbia|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Judith Guichon]] then invited the NDP to form a minority government with Green support.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McElroy |first1=Justin |title=NDP Leader John Horgan to be next premier of British Columbia |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/horgan-government-guichon-2017-1.4185204 |access-date=30 June 2017 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630112221/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/horgan-government-guichon-2017-1.4185204# |archive-date=30 June 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> On November 30, 2017, the ''Electoral Reform Referendum 2018 Act'' was passed into law.<ref>{{Cite canlaw |short title=Electoral Reform Referendum 2018 Act |abbr=SBC |year=2017 |chapter=22 |link=http://www.bclaws.ca/civix/document/id/complete/statreg/17022_01}}</ref> It required the referendum to be held and authorized [[Executive Council of British Columbia|Cabinet]] to make various regulations.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hunter |first1=Justine |title=B.C. NDP, Greens flex partnership with swath of new policy achievements |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/bc-ndp-greens-flex-partnership-with-swath-of-new-policy-achievements/article37158183/ |date=November 30, 2017 |access-date=23 June 2018 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418220125/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/bc-ndp-greens-flex-partnership-with-swath-of-new-policy-achievements/article37158183/# |archive-date=18 April 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Consultation and implementation==\nBetween November 2017 and February 2018, [[Attorney General]] [[David Eby]] conducted a public consultation entitled \"How We Vote\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Meissner |first=Dirk |title=B.C. New Democrats invite public electoral reform vote; Liberals cry foul |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/politics/b-c-new-democrats-invite-public-electoral-reform-vote-liberals-cry-foul |date=November 23, 2017 |access-date=7 June 2018 |work=[[Vancouver Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612142419/http://vancouversun.com/news/politics/b-c-new-democrats-invite-public-electoral-reform-vote-liberals-cry-foul# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> On May 30, 2018, he released the report on the consultation and recommendations concerning how the referendum process should be conducted.<ref name=\"2018report\">{{cite web |last=Eby |first=David |date=May 30, 2018 |title=How We Vote 2018 Electoral Reform Referendum: Report and Recommendations of the Attorney General |url=https://engage.gov.bc.ca/app/uploads/sites/271/2018/05/How-We-Vote-2018-Electoral-Reform-Referendum-Report-and-Recommendations-of-the-Attorney-General.pdf |publisher=Government of British Columbia |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831060310/https://engage.gov.bc.ca/app/uploads/sites/271/2018/05/How-We-Vote-2018-Electoral-Reform-Referendum-Report-and-Recommendations-of-the-Attorney-General.pdf# |archive-date=31 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Tyee?s\">{{cite web |url=https://thetyee.ca/News/2018/05/30/Eby-Proposed-Electoral-Reform-Referendum-Questions/ |title=Eby Unveils Proposed Electoral Reform Referendum Questions |last=MacLeod |first=Andrew |work=[[The Tyee]] |date=May 30, 2018 |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612142804/https://thetyee.ca/News/2018/05/30/Eby-Proposed-Electoral-Reform-Referendum-Questions/# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Eagland |first=Nick |title=New Zealand gives B.C. a lesson on proportional representation |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/new-zealand-gives-b-c-a-lesson-on-proportional-representation |date=June 4, 2018 |access-date=6 June 2018 |work=[[Vancouver Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180609041248/http://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/new-zealand-gives-b-c-a-lesson-on-proportional-representation# |archive-date=9 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Cabinet accepted the recommendations shortly thereafter, in early June.<ref name=\"PremierStatement\">{{cite web |author=Office of the Premier |title=Premier's statement on recommendations for proportional representation referendum |date=June 7, 2018 |url=https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2018PREM0083-001137 |access-date=7 June 2018 |publisher=Government of British Columbia |type=Press release |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141900/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2018PREM0083-001137# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Fletcher |first=Tom |title=B.C. cabinet approves multiple-choice voting referendum |url=https://www.theprogress.com/news/b-c-cabinet-approves-multiple-choice-voting-referendum/ |access-date=7 June 2018 |date=June 7, 2018 |publisher=[[Black Press]] |work=The Chilliwack Progress |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612122653/https://www.theprogress.com/news/b-c-cabinet-approves-multiple-choice-voting-referendum/# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Later in June, Vote PR BC launched their campaign for proportional representation, canvassing in cities across the province.<ref>{{cite web |last=Grauer |first=Perrin |title=Campaign to change B.C. voting system hits the streets, with Ontario election in mind |url=https://www.thestar.com/vancouver/2018/06/10/campaign-to-change-bc-voting-system-hits-the-streets-with-ontario-election-in-mind.html |date=June 10, 2018 |access-date=11 June 2018 |work=[[StarMetro (newspaper)|StarMetro Vancouver]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140600/https://www.thestar.com/vancouver/2018/06/10/campaign-to-change-bc-voting-system-hits-the-streets-with-ontario-election-in-mind.html# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Ryan |first=Denise |title=Canvassers take case for B.C. electoral reform to commuters |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/canvassers-take-case-for-b-c-electoral-reform-to-commuters |date=June 10, 2018 |access-date=11 June 2018 |work=[[Vancouver Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140431/http://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/canvassers-take-case-for-b-c-electoral-reform-to-commuters# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Elections BC]] reviewed the referendum questions in June. On June 18, Chief Electoral Officer Anton Boegman wrote to the [[Speaker of the Legislative Assembly of British Columbia|Speaker of the Legislative Assembly]] advising that in his view both questions were simple and clear enough for voters to understand. He also made recommendations for small changes to the questions.<ref>{{cite web |last=Boegman |first=Anton |title=Letter to the Speaker of the Legislative Assembly |url=http://elections.bc.ca/docs/referendum/REF-2018-LTR-CEO-speaker-response.pdf |date=June 18, 2018 |access-date=19 June 2018 |work=[[Elections BC]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619214100/http://elections.bc.ca/docs/referendum/REF-2018-LTR-CEO-speaker-response.pdf# |archive-date=19 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Press Progress |title=Elections BC Just Blew a Giant Hole in the Big Money Campaign Attacking Electoral Reform |url=https://pressprogress.ca/elections-bc-just-blew-a-giant-hole-in-the-big-money-campaign-attacking-electoral-reform/ |date=June 19, 2018 |access-date=19 June 2018 |work=Press Progress |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620001245/https://pressprogress.ca/elections-bc-just-blew-a-giant-hole-in-the-big-money-campaign-attacking-electoral-reform/# |archive-date=20 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>  On June 22, 2018, the government released the regulations governing the referendum.<ref name=\"regulation\">{{cite web |url=https://engage.gov.bc.ca/app/uploads/sites/271/2018/06/ReferendumRegulation2018.pdf |title=Electoral Reform Referendum 2018 Regulation, Reg. 313/2018 |date=June 22, 2018 |access-date=23 June 2018 |work=govTogetherBC |publisher=Government of British Columbia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623210203/https://engage.gov.bc.ca/app/uploads/sites/271/2018/06/ReferendumRegulation2018.pdf |archive-date=23 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The regulations adopted the changes to the question proposed by the Chief Electoral Officer, and set down other rules governing the campaign.<ref>{{cite web |last=[[The Canadian Press]]|title=Electoral reform vote in B.C. includes $500,000 each for pro and con groups |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-electoral-reform-vote-in-bc-includes-500000-each-for-pro-and-con/|date=June 22, 2018 |access-date=23 June 2018|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Little|first=Simon|title=B.C. lays out rules for fall referendum on changing the way politicians are elected|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4292443/proportional-representation-referendum-rules/|date=June 22, 2018|access-date=23 June 2018|work=[[Global News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623023255/https://globalnews.ca/news/4292443/proportional-representation-referendum-rules/#|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===ICBA lawsuit===\n\nOn June 28, 2018, the Independent Contractors and Business Association (ICBA)\u2014a lobby group for the construction industry\u2014 filed a lawsuit seeking an injunction to stop the referendum, or alternatively, to strike down the campaign financing rules governing the referendum.<ref>{{cite web |title=About ICBA |url=https://icba.ca/about-icba/ |access-date=29 June 2018 |publisher=Independent Contractors and Business Association |website=icba.ca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629211710/https://icba.ca/about-icba/# |archive-date=29 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=LawsuitFiled>{{cite web|last=Mulgrew|first=Ian|title=Injunction sought to halt B.C. proportional representation vote|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/injunction-sought-to-halt-b-c-proportional-representation-vote|date=June 29, 2018|access-date=29 June 2018|work=[[Vancouver Sun]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629024007/http://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/injunction-sought-to-halt-b-c-proportional-representation-vote#|archive-date=29 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The lawsuit contains various complaints about the process, the referendum, and the systems on the ballot.<ref name=LawsuitFiled /> In response, NDP MLA [[Bob D'Eith]] called the lawsuit an attempt to stop people from having a choice in their electoral system, and said ICBA does not want \"ordinary people to have a stronger voice in the elections and I think they're desperate to hang on to the status quo\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Kretzel|first=Lasia|title=ICBA, Union seek injunction on proportional representation referendum|url=https://www.news1130.com/2018/06/29/icba-union-seek-injunction-proportional-representation-referendum/|date=June 29, 2018|access-date=1 July 2018|work=[[News 1130]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701165030/https://www.news1130.com/2018/06/29/icba-union-seek-injunction-proportional-representation-referendum/#|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Attorney General of British Columbia|Ministry of the Attorney General]] is defending the legislation in court.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bains|first=Camille|title=B.C. referendum campaign launches as groups file petition to stop process|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-bc-referendum-campaign-launches-as-groups-file-petition-to-stop/|date=July 1, 2018|access-date=2 July 2018|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704225722/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-bc-referendum-campaign-launches-as-groups-file-petition-to-stop/#|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The official campaign began July 1, 2018.<ref name=\"regulation\" />\n\nOn July 17, 2018, ICBA's court application for an early trial date was dismissed by Justice Miriam Gropper of the [[British Columbia Supreme Court]], in order to allow the government time to respond. Following the hearing, ICBA's lawyer, Peter Gall, told reporters ICBA would be seeking an interim injunction.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mulgrew|first=Ian|title=B.C. electoral system referendum foes lose first round|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/politics/b-c-electoral-system-referendum-foes-lose-first-round|date=July 18, 2018|access-date=19 July 2018|work=[[Vancouver Sun]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718205834/https://vancouversun.com/news/politics/b-c-electoral-system-referendum-foes-lose-first-round#|archive-date=18 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn July 24, ICBA filed an application seeking an interim injunction to halt campaign financing rules and prevent ballots from being counted. The application was heard by Justice Gropper on August 7. In her decision handed down several weeks later, she dismissed the application calling ICBA's allegations about the referendum \"rhetoric\", \"conjecture\" and \"exaggeration\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Fraser |first=Keith |title=Judge refuses to stop B.C.'s referendum on proportional representation voting system |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/judge-refuses-to-stop-b-c-s-referendum-on-proportional-representation-voting-system |date=August 28, 2018 |access-date=28 August 2018 |work=[[Vancouver Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829013223/https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/judge-refuses-to-stop-b-c-s-referendum-on-proportional-representation-voting-system# |archive-date=29 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Ball |first=David |title=Judge quashes attempt to halt mailing of ballots for B.C.'s referendum on electoral reform |url=https://www.thestar.com/vancouver/2018/08/28/judge-quashes-attempt-to-halt-mailing-of-ballots-for-bcs-referendum-on-electoral-reform.html |date=August 28, 2018 |access-date=29 August 2018 |work=[[StarMetro (newspaper)|The Star Vancouver]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829073738/https://www.thestar.com/vancouver/2018/08/28/judge-quashes-attempt-to-halt-mailing-of-ballots-for-bcs-referendum-on-electoral-reform.html# |archive-date=29 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite CanLII |litigants=ICBA v British Columbia |year=2018 |court=bcsc |num=1597 |courtname=auto}}</ref> In mid-September, the ICBA announced that they will be seeking leave to appeal Justice Gropper's ruling on the interim injunction.<ref>{{cite web |last=Yuzda |first=Liza |title=ICBA seeking appeal on proportional representation referendum injunction request |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4446641/icba-seeking-appeal-on-proportional-representation-referendum-injunction-request/ |date=September 13, 2018 |access-date=13 September 2018 |work=[[Global News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180913211133/https://globalnews.ca/news/4446641/icba-seeking-appeal-on-proportional-representation-referendum-injunction-request/# |archive-date=13 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> That same month, the [[British Columbia Government and Service Employees' Union]] was granted [[Intervention (law)|intervenor status]] by the court, siding against the ICBA.<ref>{{cite web |last=Macdonald |first=Gord |title=BCGEU joins legal fight over proportional representation referendum |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4495631/bcgeu-legal-fight-proportional-representation-referendum/ |date=September 28, 2018 |access-date=5 November 2018 |work=[[Global News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929113346/https://globalnews.ca/news/4495631/bcgeu-legal-fight-proportional-representation-referendum/# |archive-date=29 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe appeal of Justice Gropper's judgement concerning the interim injunction was heard on November 2. Justice Fitch of the [[British Columbia Court of Appeal]] dismissed the appeal, finding that there was no merit to the ICBA's argument.<ref>{{cite CanLII |litigants=ICBA v British Columbia |year=2018 |court=bcca |num=429 |courtname=auto}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=[[The Canadian Press]] |title=Top B.C. court rejects group's attempt to stop electoral reform referendum |url=https://theprovince.com/news/local-news/top-court-rejects-groups-attempt-to-stop-b-c-electoral-reform-referendum/wcm/be8876e2-5e41-4e4c-a6ce-cce680bbc313 |date=November 2, 2018 |access-date=2 November 2018 |work=[[The Province]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103003643/https://theprovince.com/news/local-news/top-court-rejects-groups-attempt-to-stop-b-c-electoral-reform-referendum/wcm/be8876e2-5e41-4e4c-a6ce-cce680bbc313# |archive-date=3 November 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Ballot structure and details==\nVoters were asked two questions in the referendum. The first revolved around what electoral system should be used to determine election results: the existing first-past-the-post system or a proportional representation system. The second question explored what type of proportional voting system should be used if PR is chosen. This involved voters ranking three proportional representation voting systems: [[dual-member proportional representation]], [[mixed-member proportional representation]], and [[rural\u2013urban proportional representation]].<ref name=\"2part-question\" /><ref name=announcement>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/electoral-reform-referendum-question-eby-1.4683919 |title=B.C. to choose between 4 systems for electoral reform referendum |last=McElroy |first=Justin |work=[[CBC News]] |date=May 30, 2018 |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180604094840/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/electoral-reform-referendum-question-eby-1.4683919# |archive-date=4 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"systems\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/pr-electoral-reform-questions-1.4688604 |title=Know your voting systems: three types of electoral reform on B.C.'s ballot |last=McElroy |first=Justin |work=[[CBC News]] |date=June 2, 2018 |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603182847/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/pr-electoral-reform-questions-1.4688604# |archive-date=3 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*Question 1: Which system should British Columbia use for provincial elections? (Vote for only one.)\n**The current First Past the Post voting system\n**A proportional representation voting system\n*Question 2: If British Columbia adopts a proportional representation voting system, which of the following voting systems do you prefer? (Rank in order of preference. You may choose to support one, two or all three of the systems.)\n**Dual-member proportional (DMP)\n**Mixed-member proportional (MMP)\n**Rural\u2013urban proportional (RUP)\n\n==Proportional voting systems on the ballot==\nThe referendum asked voters to rank three proportional representation voting systems in order of preference: Voters ranked one, two, or all three systems.<ref name=\"2018report\" />\n* [[dual-member proportional representation]] (DMP)\n* [[mixed-member proportional representation]] (MMP)\n* [[rural\u2013urban proportional representation]] (RUP)\n\n===Dual-member proportional (DMP)===\nDual-member proportional is an electoral system designed to produce proportional election results across a region by electing two [[legislator|representatives]] in each of the region's [[electoral district|districts]].<ref name=\"dmpreport\">{{cite web |url=https://dmpforcanada.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/dmp-report-updated-april-4-2016.pdf |title=Dual-Member Mixed Proportional: A New Electoral System for Canada |author=Sean Graham |date=April 4, 2016 |access-date=18 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020142244/https://dmpforcanada.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/dmp-report-updated-april-4-2016.pdf# |archive-date=20 October 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.assembly.pe.ca/sittings/2015fall/reports/23_1_2015-27-11-report.pdf |title=Recommendations in Response to the White Paper on Democratic Renewal |author=PEI Special Committee on Democratic Renewal |date=November 27, 2015 |access-date=18 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822171727/http://www.assembly.pe.ca/sittings/2015fall/reports/23_1_2015-27-11-report.pdf# |archive-date=22 August 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> The first seat in every district is awarded to the candidate who receives the most votes, similar to first-past-the-post voting. The second seat is awarded to one of the remaining district candidates so that proportionality is achieved across the region, using a calculation that aims to award parties their seats in the districts where they had their strongest performances.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/dual-member-proportional-dmp/ |title=Dual Member Proportional (DMP) |website=elections.bc.ca |publisher=Elections BC |access-date=20 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821093854/https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/dual-member-proportional-dmp/# |archive-date=21 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDMP was invented in 2013 by a [[University of Alberta]] mathematics student named Sean Graham.<ref name=\"DmpErreMeeting\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ourcommons.ca/DocumentViewer/en/42-1/ERRE/meeting-33/evidence |title=Meeting No. 33 Evidence |author=[[Canadian House of Commons Special Committee on Electoral Reform]] |date=29 September 2016 |access-date=18 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618102546/https://www.ourcommons.ca/DocumentViewer/en/42-1/ERRE/meeting-33/evidence# |archive-date=18 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The system was intended as a possible replacement for first-past-the-post voting in [[Elections in Canada|Canadian national and provincial elections]]. Whereas campaigns to adopt MMP representation or the single transferable vote had recently been defeated in a number of [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Canadian provinces]] (such as the 2005 and 2009 British Columbia referendums, the [[2005 Prince Edward Island electoral reform referendum|2005 Prince Edward Island referendum]], and the [[2007 Ontario electoral reform referendum|2007 Ontario referendum]]), the intent behind DMP was to gain broader acceptance by retaining salient features of first-past-the-post voting. These features include a one-vote ballot, relatively small districts (compared with STV), and a single tier of local representatives (in contrast to MMP).<ref name=\"DmpMediaEndorse\">{{cite news |url=http://www.theguardian.pe.ca/opinion/editorials/editorial-we-endorse-dmp-option-in-plebiscite-111292/ |title=Editorial: We endorse DMP option in plebiscite |author=[[The Guardian]] |date=October 29, 2016 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=18 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618102408/http://www.theguardian.pe.ca/opinion/editorials/editorial-we-endorse-dmp-option-in-plebiscite-111292/# |archive-date=18 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Mixed-member proportional===\nMixed-member proportional is a [[mixed electoral system]] in which voters get two votes: one to decide the [[legislator|representative]] for their single-seat [[electoral district|constituency]], and one for a political party. Seats in the legislature are filled firstly by candidates in local ridings, and secondly, by party candidates based on the percentage of nationwide or region-wide votes that each party received.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/mixed-member-proportional-mmp/ |title=Mixed Member Proportional (MMP) |publisher=[[Elections BC]] |website=elections.bc.ca |access-date=20 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821093857/https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/mixed-member-proportional-mmp/# |archive-date=21 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, MMP was recommended by the [[Law Commission of Canada]] to be adopted for federal elections.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://publications.gc.ca/collections/Collection/J31-61-2004E.pdf |title=Voting Counts: Electoral Reform for Canada |author=[[Law Commission of Canada]] |date=2004 |publisher=[[Minister of Public Services and Procurement|Minister of Public Works and Government Services]] |access-date=19 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020142238/http://publications.gc.ca/collections/Collection/J31-61-2004E.pdf# |archive-date=20 October 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=ElectoralGame /> In 2007, Ontario held a [[2007 Ontario electoral reform referendum|provincial referendum]] to adopt the system, which failed to pass.<ref name=ElectoralGame>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/ontario-election-electoral-system-alternatives-1.4709074 |title=The electoral game: What would Ontario results look like under a different voting system? |last1=Ouellet |first1=Val\u00e9rie |last2=Dubinsky |first2=Zach |date=June 16, 2018 |access-date=19 June 2018 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618183146/http://www.cbc.ca/news/ontario-election-electoral-system-alternatives-1.4709074# |archive-date=18 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, [[Prince Edward Island]] (PEI) voted to adopt MMP in a [[2016 Prince Edward Island electoral reform referendum|non-binding referendum]].<ref name=\"cbc results\">{{cite news |last1=Bradley |first1=Susan |title=P.E.I. plebiscite results favour mixed member proportional representation |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/mixed-member-proportional-representation-in-plebiscite-1.3840172 |accessdate=8 November 2016 |work=CBC News |date=8 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129004505/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/mixed-member-proportional-representation-in-plebiscite-1.3840172# |archive-date=29 November 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> PEI will hold [[Next Prince Edward Island electoral reform referendum|another referendum]] on the issue during the next provincial election.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/pei-referendum-act-passes-legislature-1.4703182 |title=Much-amended P.E.I. referendum legislation passes |last=CBC News |date=June 12, 2018 |work=[[CBC News]] |access-date=13 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613171020/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/pei-referendum-act-passes-legislature-1.4703182# |archive-date=13 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA form of MMP is used for national elections in [[Electoral system of New Zealand#MMP in New Zealand|New Zealand]] and Germany, and in the United Kingdom for elections to the [[Devolution in the United Kingdom|devolved parliaments]] of [[Elections in Scotland#Scottish Parliament|Scotland]] and Wales (where the system is referred to as the [[Additional Member System]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/new-zealand-democracy-1.4720787|title=Why New Zealand's former prime minister believes proportional representation works better |last=Humphrey|first=Matt|date=June 25, 2018 |work=[[CBC News]] |access-date=25 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fairvote.ca/mixed-member-proportional/ |title=Mixed Member Proportional |author=[[Fair Vote Canada]] |date=2018 |work=Fair Vote Canada |access-date=25 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724151104/https://www.fairvote.ca/mixed-member-proportional/# |archive-date=24 July 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Rural\u2013urban proportional (RUP)===\n[[File:Preferential ballot.svg|thumb|Simplified example of an STV ranked ballot used in an urban or semi-urban area under rural\u2013urban proportional (RUP). RUP is the only system that lets voters rank individual candidates in order of preference.]]\nRural\u2013urban proportional is a hybrid-proportional system designed by [[Fair Vote Canada]] to meet the challenges of Canada's geography.<ref name=\"fairvote-ru\">{{cite web|last=[[Fair Vote Canada]]|url=https://www.fairvote.ca/rural-urban-proportional/|title=Rural\u2013Urban Proportional|work=Fair Vote Canada|date=2018|access-date=25 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724151135/https://www.fairvote.ca/rural-urban-proportional/#|archive-date=24 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"fed-report\" /> As put forward for the BC referendum, it would use mixed-member proportional representation (MMP) in rural areas and the single transferable vote (STV) in urban and semi-urban areas.<ref name=\"systems\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/rural-urban-proportional-rup/ |title=Rural-Urban Proportional (RUP) |publisher=[[Elections BC]] |website=elections.bc.ca |access-date=20 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821093858/https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/rural-urban-proportional-rup/# |archive-date=21 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4242810/british-columbians-will-vote-on-our-electoral-system-here-are-the-4-options/ |title=British Columbians will vote on our electoral system \u2014 Here are the 4 options |last=Zussman |first=Richard |work=[[Global News]] |date=May 30, 2018 |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615004254/https://globalnews.ca/news/4242810/british-columbians-will-vote-on-our-electoral-system-here-are-the-4-options/# |archive-date=15 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Sweden, Denmark and Iceland use voting models with similar hybrid approaches. In Canada from the 1920s to the 1950s, the provinces of Alberta and Manitoba used a hybrid rural\u2013urban system where STV was used in large cities and the [[instant-runoff voting|alternative vote]] was used in single-member rural districts.<ref name=\"pdennis\"/>{{rp|81\u201382}}<ref name=\"fairvote-ru\"/><ref>{{Cite book| publisher = University of Michigan Press| isbn = 978-0-472-11159-6| editor1-last = Bowler| editor1-first = Shaun| editor2-last = Grofman| editor2-first = Bernard| title = Elections in Australia, Ireland, and Malta under the Single Transferable Vote| date = 2000| doi = 10.3998/mpub.16507| jstor = 10.3998/mpub.16507}}</ref>\n\nThe hybrid approach taken by rural\u2013urban proportional reflects lessons learned from previous attempts to pass electoral reform.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-bcs-proportional-representation-voting-system-options-include-two |title=BC's proportional representation voting system options include two that are lesser known |last=Dhillon |first=Sunny |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=June 17, 2018 |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621183227/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-bcs-proportional-representation-voting-system-options-include-two/# |archive-date=21 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> A major advantage of rural\u2013urban proportional as designed is that it requires creating far fewer top-up seats to achieve proportionality than MMP. Under rural\u2013urban PR, no more than 10\u201315% of seats \u2013 versus 40% of seats under MMP \u2013 would need to be set aside as top-up seats to achieve proportionality, because the results from the urban and semi-urban areas would already be proportional owing to their voting having been conducted using STV.\n\nFor rural areas, rural\u2013urban proportional is advantageous because existing first-past-the-post rural ridings need to grow only 15% larger to facilitate extra regional top-up seats under it, compared to 67% larger if MMP was chosen or double in size if DMP was chosen.<ref name=\"fairvote-ru\" />\n\nRUP is the only PR system of the three that lets voters rank individual candidates in order by preference. The use of STV ranked ballots means that all candidates must compete with one another for a voter's coveted first place ranking, including candidates running for the same party. Voters can rank long-shot independent candidates or candidates from unpopular parties first without fear of wasting their vote, because votes for badly performing candidates will be transferred during counting\u2014based on each voter's preferences\u2014to candidates who have yet to be eliminated, until all seats are won.\n\nIn its scorecard of proportional voting systems, Fair Voting BC gave rural\u2013urban proportional its highest ranking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fairvotingbc.com/scorecard/|title=Scorecard|author=Fair Voting BC|access-date=3 July 2018|publisher=Fair Voting BC|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704092834/https://fairvotingbc.com/scorecard/#|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> During the [[Government of Canada|Canadian government's]] 2016 consultation on electoral reform at the federal level,<ref name=\"fed-report\" /> both the [[New Democratic Party|New Democratic Party of Canada]] and [[Green Party of Canada]] recommended Canada adopt either RUP or MMP.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/wherry-electoral-reform-committee-1.3866879|title=Minister 'disappointed' as electoral reform committee recommends referendum on proportional representation|last1=Wherry|first1=Aaron|last2=Tasker|first2=John Paul|work=[[CBC News]]|date=December 1, 2016|access-date=25 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412133850/http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/wherry-electoral-reform-committee-1.3866879#|archive-date=12 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Campaign==\nThe official campaign began July 1, 2018.<ref name=\"regulation\" /> Groups had until July 6 to apply to Elections BC to be named the official proponent or opponent groups and receive $500,000 in public funding.<ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Referendum Funding |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referenda/2018-referendum-funding/ |access-date=26 June 2018 |publisher=Elections BC |website=elections.bc.ca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627034318/https://elections.bc.ca/referenda/2018-referendum-funding/# |archive-date=27 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>  On July 12, Elections BC announced that Vote PR BC would be the official proponent group and No BC Proportional Representation Society would be the official opponent group.<ref>{{cite news |last=[[The Canadian Press]] |title=Yes and No groups selected before B.C.'s electoral reform referendum |url=https://bc.ctvnews.ca/yes-and-no-groups-selected-before-b-c-s-electoral-reform-referendum-1.4010867 |date=July 12, 2018 |access-date=14 July 2018 |work=[[CTV News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713191957/https://bc.ctvnews.ca/yes-and-no-groups-selected-before-b-c-s-electoral-reform-referendum-1.4010867# |archive-date=13 July 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Referendum Funding |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referenda/2018-referendum-funding/ |access-date=14 July 2018 |publisher=Elections BC |website=elections.bc.ca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627034318/https://elections.bc.ca/referenda/2018-referendum-funding/# |archive-date=27 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Other individuals, groups and political parties are permitted to register as referendum advertisers with Elections BC, but are not eligible for public funds.<ref name=\"regulation\" />\n\nThe NDP and Green Party campaigned for proportional representation. [[Sonia Furstenau]], a Green [[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia|MLA]], held town halls about electoral reform in cities across the province in July and August.<ref>{{cite news |last=Slack |first=Jeff |title=Green Party MLA holding forum on Electoral Reform in PG |url=https://www.myprincegeorgenow.com/80016/green-party-mla-holding-forum-on-electoral-reform-in-pg/ |date=July 19, 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |work=My Prince George Now |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908015902/https://www.myprincegeorgenow.com/80016/green-party-mla-holding-forum-on-electoral-reform-in-pg/# |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Staff |title=Green MLA Furstenau visits Nelson-Creston riding |url=http://thenelsondaily.com/news/green-mla-furstenau-visits-nelson-creston-riding#.W5LKksInaUk |date=August 21, 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |work=Nelson Daily |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908092736/http://thenelsondaily.com/news/green-mla-furstenau-visits-nelson-creston-riding#.W5LKksInaUk#.W5LKksInaUk |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Eckford |first=Sean |title=Simons and Green MLAs discuss PR, cooperation |url=https://www.coastreporter.net/news/local-news/simons-and-green-mlas-discuss-pr-cooperation-1.23412249 |date=August 24, 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |work=Coast Reporter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908092817/https://www.coastreporter.net/news/local-news/simons-and-green-mlas-discuss-pr-cooperation-1.23412249# |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Premier of British Columbia|BC Premier]] [[John Horgan]] launched the NDP's referendum campaign in early September, saying \"Proportional representation means exactly what it says. Whatever proportion, or share, of the vote a party wins, they get that many seats in government.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Palmer |first=Vaughn |title=Horgan selling positives of electoral change, but there are negatives |url=https://vancouversun.com/opinion/columnists/vaughn-palmer-horgan-selling-positives-of-electoral-change-but-there-are-negatives |date=September 7, 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |work=[[Vancouver Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907082937/https://vancouversun.com/opinion/columnists/vaughn-palmer-horgan-selling-positives-of-electoral-change-but-there-are-negatives# |archive-date=7 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Andrew Wilkinson]], BC Liberal leader, opposed the referendum and a change to a proportional representation system.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smyth |first=Mike |title=B.C. Liberals declare all-out war on proportional representation |url=https://theprovince.com/opinion/columnists/mike-smyth-liberals-declare-all-out-war-on-proportional-representation |date=June 3, 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |work=[[The Province]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908092836/https://theprovince.com/opinion/columnists/mike-smyth-liberals-declare-all-out-war-on-proportional-representation# |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nElections BC mailed a referendum information card to every household in the province between September 10 and 28, and a voter's guide between October 15 and 26.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fletcher |first=Tom |title=Voter registration push begins for B.C. referendum |url=https://www.castlegarnews.com/news/voter-registration-push-begins-for-b-c-referendum/ |date=September 10, 2018 |access-date=10 September 2018 |work=Castlegar News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911045135/https://www.castlegarnews.com/news/voter-registration-push-begins-for-b-c-referendum/# |archive-date=11 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=EBCmail /> Voters received their referendum voting package in the mail between October 22 and November 2.<ref name=EBCmail>{{cite web |title=Referendum Resources |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/referendum-resources/ |access-date=11 September 2018 |publisher=Elections BC |website=elections.bc.ca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908015803/https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/referendum-resources/# |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In early September, the members of the [[Canadian Union of Postal Workers]] voted in favour of job action. The strike resulted in Elections BC extending the voting deadline by a week.<ref name=\"extension\" />\n\nIn early November, Horgan announced that he had cast his ballot for proportional representation, and that his first choice was MMP.<ref>{{cite news |last=CBC News |title=John Horgan: I voted for mixed-member proportional in electoral reform referendum |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/john-horgan-i-voted-for-mixed-member-proportional-in-electoral-reform-referendum-1.4888430 |date=November 1, 2018 |access-date=5 November 2018 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104053556/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/john-horgan-i-voted-for-mixed-member-proportional-in-electoral-reform-referendum-1.4888430# |archive-date=4 November 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>  Vote PR BC, the official proponent group, flew Andrew Coyne to Vancouver to give a talk endorsing PR, where Coyne announced he supported Rural\u2013Urban Proportional.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/voteprbc/photos/a.228311341063875/337164366845238/|title=Tomorrow noted political commentator @ACoyne joins us for a lively discussion on Pro Rep. Are you planning on taking part? RSVP here to attend: #PR4BC #ProRep #BCPoli|date=October 24, 2018|website=Facebook|access-date=8 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nationalpost.com/opinion/andrew-coyne-which-electoral-system-for-b-c-any-option-is-better-than-the-status-quo |title=Andrew Coyne: Which electoral system for B.C.? Any option is better than the status quo |last=Coyne |first=Andrew |date=2018-10-30 |work=National Post |access-date=12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Debate ===\nIn late September, Andrew Wilkinson challenged John Horgan to a debate concerning the referendum, a challenge which Horgan accepted. The debate took place on November 8 at 7:00{{Nbsp}}pm. It was broadcast on [[CBC News]] and [[Global News]].<ref>{{cite news |last=CBC News |title=B.C. premier, opposition leader to face off in electoral reform debate |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/events/premier-opposition-leader-electoral-reform-debate-1.4883872 |date=October 30, 2018 |access-date=31 October 2018 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030223159/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/events/premier-opposition-leader-electoral-reform-debate-1.4883872# |archive-date=30 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Official campaign organizations===\nOfficial campaign organizations include the official proponent and opponent groups along with referendum advertising sponsors.<ref name=RefSponsors>{{cite web |title=2018 Referendum Advertising Sponsors |url=https://elections.bc.ca/docs/referendum/2018-Referendum-Advertising-Sponsors.pdf |accessdate=8 December 2018 |publisher=Elections BC |website=elections.bc.ca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181208221641/https://elections.bc.ca/docs/referendum/2018-Referendum-Advertising-Sponsors.pdf |archive-date=8 December 2018 |url-status=live  |date=December 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Official proponent and opponent groups====\n\n* Proponent: Vote PR BC\n* Opponent: No BC Proportional Representation Society\n\n====Referendum advertising sponsors====\n* Asian Environmental Association\n* [[British Columbia Conservative Party]]\n* [[British Columbia Government and Service Employees' Union]]\n* British Columbia Liberal Party\n* British Columbia New Democratic Party\n* Committee for Voting Equity in BC\n* [[Communist Party of British Columbia]]\n* [[Dogwood Initiative]]\n* Fair Vote Canada BC\n* Fraser Valley East Against Proportional Representation\n* Green Party Political Association of British Columbia\n* KnowB4UVote.com Society\n* [[LeadNow]]\n* No Pro Rep Fraser Valley East \n* Rural\u2013Urban Proportional for BC\n* Wake Up BC\n* Wildsight\n* Wise Vote BC\n* YES or NO, Rural Urban First\n\n==Voting period extension==\nOn November 23, 2018, due to a postal strike, Elections BC extended the voting period deadline by a week \u2013 from November 30, 2018, to December 7, 2018.<ref name=\"extension\">{{cite news |title=Voting period for electoral reform referendum extended due to postal strike |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/electoral-referendum-deadline-extended-1.4918055 |access-date=23 November 2018 |work=CBC News |date=November 23, 2018}}</ref> The deadline to register to vote remained midnight on November 23, 2018. Voters who were sent a voting package but did not receive it, or who need a replacement voting package, could request a replacement package up to December 7. All ballots must have been received by Elections BC by 4:30{{Nbsp}}pm on December 7.<ref>https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/how-to-vote</ref> In response to a question from a constituent on [[Twitter]], Elections BC clarified that ballots received by Elections BC's Referendum Service Offices or Service BC Centres up to and including 4:30{{Nbsp}}pm on December 7, 2018, but which had not been physically transferred to Elections BC's counting centre, would be accepted and counted as valid ballots.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=ElectionsBC |number=1073637787738357761 |date=December 14, 2018 |access-date=December 19, 2018 |author=Elections BC |author-link=Elections BC |title=Hi Doug \u2013 Yes, completed voting packages received by Elections BC by mail or in person at a Referendum Service Office or Service BC Centre by 4:30 p.m. on December 7, 2018 were accepted for counting.}}</ref>\n\n==Post-referendum plans==\n\nThe government had plans for the required next steps had proportional representation passed. However, as it did not pass, the government will not implement any of these steps.  Had a proportional system been adopted, the independent [[British Columbia Electoral Boundaries Commission|BC Electoral Boundaries Commission]] would have determined the number and location of new electoral districts. A legislative committee would have been tasked with determining whether the number of members of the Legislative Assembly should increase, and if so by how many (to a maximum of an additional eight). Some other aspects of how the new system would have worked would have also needed to be determined by a legislative committee.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/what-are-we-voting-on/ |title=What happens after the referendum? |website=elections.bc.ca |publisher=[[Elections BC]] |access-date=24 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825073911/https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/what-are-we-voting-on/# |archive-date=25 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIf a form of proportional representation had been adopted, the government had also committed to holding a further confirming referendum after two general elections.<ref name=\"2018report\" /><ref name=\"PremierStatement\" /> Voters in that future referendum would have had the option of maintaining the form of proportional representation adopted or switching back to the first-past-the-post electoral system.<ref name=\"Tyee?s\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4259321/bc-electoral-reform-referendum-format/|title=B.C. cabinet confirms format of electoral reform referendum|last=Zussman|first=Richard|work=[[Global News]]|date=June 7, 2018|access-date=25 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612165225/https://globalnews.ca/news/4259321/bc-electoral-reform-referendum-format/#|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 2, 2018, the government introduced legislation to enact the requirement for this second referendum into law. If a change from the first-past-the-post system had been adopted in 2018, the bill would have required a second referendum on electoral reform to occur within 13 months of the second provincial general election held under the chosen proportional representation voting system (no later than November 30, 2026). As voters decided to keep the existing first-past-the-post system, this second referendum will not take place.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4509590/b-c-government-second-referendum-electoral-reform/ |title=B.C. Government to legislate a second referendum on electoral reform if new system passes |last=Zussman |first=Richard |work=[[Global News]] |date=October 2, 2018 |access-date=3 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002223022/https://globalnews.ca/news/4509590/b-c-government-second-referendum-electoral-reform/# |archive-date=2 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cheknews.ca/legislation-proposed-for-a-confirming-referendum-if-b-c-voters-choose-proportional-representation-494941/|title=Legislation proposed for a confirming referendum if B.C. voters choose proportional representation|last=CHEK News|work=[[CHEK-DT|CHEK News]]|date=October 2, 2018|access-date=3 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004103735/https://www.cheknews.ca/legislation-proposed-for-a-confirming-referendum-if-b-c-voters-choose-proportional-representation-494941/#|archive-date=4 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Opinion polls==\n\n===Question 1===\n\nReferendum-style binary question<br />Question: \"Based on what you know, please indicate which of these two broad options you prefer for BC\"\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Polling firm\n!Last date of polling\n!A new system of proportional representation\n!The current first-past-the-post system\n! {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|Angus Reid\n|June 20, 2017\n|59%\n|41%\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://angusreid.org/bc-post-election/|title=Snap Election? Snap out of it, say majority of British Columbians - Angus Reid Institute|date=2017-06-17|work=Angus Reid Institute|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023080258/http://angusreid.org/bc-post-election/#|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|Angus Reid\n|Sept 26, 2017\n|65%\n|35%\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://angusreid.org/horgan-ndp-electoral-reform-energy-projects/|title=British Columbians call on new provincial government to deliver electoral reform, energy projects - Angus Reid Institute|date=2017-09-25|work=Angus Reid Institute|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023080256/http://angusreid.org/horgan-ndp-electoral-reform-energy-projects/#|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|Angus Reid\n|December 31, 2017\n|57%\n|43%\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://angusreid.org/site-c-horgan/|title=Site C: By margin of two-to-one, BC residents say province made the right call to finish dam project - Angus Reid Institute|date=2018-01-11|work=Angus Reid Institute|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023080253/http://angusreid.org/site-c-horgan/#|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|Angus Reid\n|May 9, 2018\n|57%\n|43%\n|<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://angusreid.org/bc-ndp-one-year/# |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929194838/http://angusreid.org/bc-ndp-one-year/# |archive-date=29 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|Angus Reid\n|September 17, 2018\n|57%\n|43%\n||<ref name=\"Angus Reid Institute\">{{Cite news|url=http://angusreid.org/bc-electoral-reform-referendum/|title=Proportional Representation: BC residents split three ways over whether to change voting system - Angus Reid Institute|date=2018-09-27|work=Angus Reid Institute|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930125415/http://angusreid.org/bc-electoral-reform-referendum/#|archive-date=30 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://angusreid.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/2018.09.17-VotingSystems-National-ReleaseTables.pdf|title=National release tables - Angus Reid Survey September 9 2017|website=angusreid.org|access-date=26 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023080259/http://angusreid.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/2018.09.17-VotingSystems-National-ReleaseTables.pdf#|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|Mainstreet\n|November 8, 2018\n|49.5%\n|50.5%\n|<ref name=\"Mainstreet Nov 8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/392643708/Mainstreet-Bc-Nov8 |title=Mainstreet Research - BC UltraPoll Release|date=2018-11-08|work=Mainstreet|access-date=15 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n|}\n\nMultiple choice question allowing undecideds and opt-outs (options 3\u20135 will not be present on ballot)<br />Question: \"Based on how you feel right now, if you were to receive a voting package, which way would you vote on the first question?\"\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Polling firm !! Last date of polling !! The current first past the post voting system !! A proportional representation voting system\n!Undecided / Not sure\n!Would not vote on this particular question\n!Would ignore the voting package altogether!!{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| Angus Reid || September 18, 2018 || 31% || 33%\n|33%\n|1%\n|2%||<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://angusreid.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/2018.09.18-BC-Electoral-Reform-VoteIntention-ReleaseTables.pdf# |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023120010/http://angusreid.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/2018.09.18-BC-Electoral-Reform-VoteIntention-ReleaseTables.pdf# |archive-date=23 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Angus Reid Institute\"/>\n|-\n|Google Survey\n|November 6, 2018\n|19.7%\n|19.8%\n|43.5%\n|n/a\n|17.1\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tooclosetocall.ca/2018/11/exclusive-poll-referendum-on-electoral.html|title=Too Close To Call: Exclusive poll: The referendum on electoral reform in BC is a toss-up|last=Breguet|first=Bryan|work=Too Close To Call|access-date=20 November 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Question 2===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Polling firm !! Last date of polling !! Mixed-Member Proportional !! Rural\u2013Urban Proportional !! Dual Member Proportional !! Notes !! {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| Angus Reid || September 28, 2018 || 49% || 26%  || 24% ||{{Small|Percentage breakdown shows preference among decided voters; 54% of people polled report being undecided on which system to choose.}}||<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://angusreid.org/bc-electoral-reform-referendum/# |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929194852/http://angusreid.org/bc-electoral-reform-referendum/# |archive-date=29 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| Mainstreet Research || November 8, 2018 || 44.8% || 38.2%  || 17% ||{{Small|RUP has large lead in interior BC. MMP and RUP tied on Vancouver Island. MMP leading in Metro Vancouver.}}||<ref name=\"Mainstreet Nov 8\"/>\n|}\n\n==Results==\n\nOn December 20, 2018, [[Elections BC]] announced that 61.3% of ballots were cast to maintain the first-past-the-post voting system.<ref name=\"electionsbcresults\">\n{{ cite web | url=https://electionsbcca.blob.core.windows.net/electionsbcca/referendum/results.html | title=2018 Referendum Voting Results | website=Elections BC | date=2018-12-20 | accessdate=2018-12-20 }}</ref><ref name=\"electionsbcresultsPDF\">\n{{ cite web | url=https://electionsbcca.blob.core.windows.net/electionsbcca/referendum/2018REF-prov-summary.pdf | title=2018 Referendum on Electoral Reform - Provincial Results | website=Elections BC | date=2018-12-20 | accessdate=2018-12-20 }}</ref><ref>\n{{ cite web | url=https://www.thestar.com/vancouver/2018/12/20/no-wins-61-per-cent-of-the-vote-in-proportional-representation-referendum-elections-bc-announces.html | title='No' wins 61 per cent of the vote in proportional representation referendum, Elections BC announces | date=2018-12-20 | last=Ball | first=David | work=The Star | access-date=2018-12-20}}</ref><ref>\n{{ cite web | url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/b-c-s-electoral-reform-referendum-results-to-be-released-at-230-p-m | title=No change: B.C. voters back first-past-the-post system in electoral reform referendum | date=2018-12-20 | last=Eagland | first=Nick | work=Vancouver Sun | access-date=2018-12-20}}</ref><ref>\n{{ cite web | url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/electoral-reform-referendum-results-1.4954538 | title=B.C. votes to keep first-past-the-post electoral system | date=2018-12-20 | work=CBC News | access-date=2018-12-20 | quote=\"Elections BC announced the results Thursday, saying 61.3 per cent of ballots had been cast in favour of the status quo, while proportional representation got 38.7 per cent.\" }}</ref>\n\nA total of 1,391,423 ballots were considered. There were 1,378,753 valid votes for Question 1, and 831,760 valid votes for Question 2. 2,461 ballots were rejected.<ref name=\"electionsbcresults\" /><ref name=\"electionsbcresultsPDF\" />\n\n===Question 1===\n\nThe existing first-past-the-post voting system received a majority of votes with 61.30% (845,235) of the valid votes for Question 1.<ref name=\"electionsbcresults\" /><ref name=\"electionsbcresultsPDF\" /> As a result, no electoral reform was approved.\n\nQuestion 1: Which system should British Columbia use for provincial elections?\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!System\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|The current First Past the Post voting system\n|845,235\n|61.30%\n|-\n|A proportional representation voting system\n|533,518\n|38.70%\n|-\n!Total valid votes\n!1,378,753\n!100.0%\n|-\n|Invalid votes\n|10,209\n! rowspan=\"3\" |\n|-\n|Rejected ballots\n|2,461\n|-\n!Total ballots\n!1,391,423\n|}\n\n===Question 2===\n\nPer the Electoral Reform Referendum 2018 Regulation, STV rules were in effect to find the winner in Question 2 (although the question was moot as no electoral reform would take place as per the result of Question 1). Thus, when no system won a majority of first preferences, a second round of counting was required for Question 2. RUP had the fewest first preferences, so it was eliminated and its votes were transferred to the second preferences marked on the ballots.<ref name=\"electionsbcresults\" /><ref name=\"electionsbcresultsPDF\" /> In the second count, the mixed-member proportional voting system had the most support on Question 2.<ref name=\"electionsbcresults\" /><ref name=\"electionsbcresultsPDF\" />\n\nQuestion 2: If British Columbia adopts a proportional representation voting system, which of the following voting systems do you prefer?\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!\n! colspan=\"3\" | Round 1\n! colspan=\"2\" | Round 2\n|-\n!System\n!Votes\n!%\n!Transfers\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|Dual-Member Proportional (DMP)\n|244,973\n|29.45%\n| +43,095\n|288,068\n|36.95% \n|-\n|Mixed-Member Proportional (MMP)\n|343,038\n|41.24%\n| +148,592\n|491,630\n|63.05% \n|-\n|Rural\u2013Urban Proportional (RUP)\n|243,749\n|29.31%\n| -243,749\n! colspan=\"2\" |\n|-\n!Total continuing ballots\n!831,760\n!100.00%\n! -52,062\n!779,698\n!100.00% \n|-\n|Exhausted ballots\n|\n|\n|\n|52,062\n! rowspan=\"5\" |\n|-\n!Total valid votes\n!831,760\n!\n!\n!831,760\n|-\n|Invalid votes\n|557,202\n|\n|\n|557,202 \n|-\n|Rejected ballots\n|2,461\n|\n|\n|2,461 \n|-\n!Total ballots considered\n!1,391,423\n!\n!\n!1,391,423 \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://engage.gov.bc.ca/howwevote/ How We Vote Consultation website]\n* [https://elections.bc.ca/referenda/ Elections BC Referendum 2018 website]\n* [https://electionsbcca.blob.core.windows.net/electionsbcca/referendum/2018-Referendum-Voting-Results-By-ED.xlsx Voting results by electoral district] \u2013 from Elections BC\n* [https://voteprbc.ca/ Vote PR BC] \u2013 Official Proponent Group\n* [https://www.nobcprorep.ca/ No Pro Rep] \u2013 Official Opponent Group\n* [https://www.fairvote.ca/pr4bc/ Fair Vote Canada BC] \u2013 Organization supporting the adoption of proportional representation in BC\n* [https://www.facebook.com/rupforbc/ Rural\u2013Urban Proportional for BC] \u2013 Group supporting rural\u2013urban proportional representation\n\n{{British Columbia elections}}\n\n[[Category:2018 in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:2018 referendums]]\n[[Category:October 2018 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:November 2018 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Referendums in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Multiple-choice referendums]]\n[[Category:Electoral reform referendums in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Iamthinking2202", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMixed-member proportional:Updated status of Prince Edward Island MMP ref, they narrowly said no", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2018_British_Columbia_electoral_reform_referendum"}
{"title_page": "Language arts", "text_new": "{{for|the Buck 65 album|Language Arts (album)}}\n\n{{None}}\n'''Language arts''' (also known as [[English language|English]] language arts or ELA) is the study and improvement of the arts of language. Traditionally, the primary divisions in language arts are [[literature]] and language, where language in this case refers to both [[linguistics]], and specific [[language]]s.<ref>\"The Road to [[Middle-earth|Middle-Earth]]\", T. A. Shippey</ref> Language arts instruction typically consists of a combination of [[Reading (process)|reading]], [[writing]] (composition), [[speaking]], and listening. In schools, language arts is taught alongside [[science]], [[mathematics]], and [[social studies]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://teach.com/what/teachers-know/english-and-language-arts/|title=English and Language Arts Teacher|access-date=2017-12-24|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Reading==\n[[Reading (process)|Reading]], by definition, is the ability and knowledge of a language that allows comprehension by grasping the meaning of written or printed characters, words, or sentences. Reading involves a wide variety of print and non-print texts that helps a reader gain an understanding of the material that is being read. Reading of texts that are often included in educational curriculum include [[fiction]], [[nonfiction]], classic, and also contemporary works. Reading goes beyond calling words to understanding the information presented in a written or a visual context.\n\n==Composition==\nComposition is defined as the combination of distinct parts or elements to form a whole and the manner in which these elements are combined or related.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=composition|url=https://www.thefreedictionary.com/composition|journal=The Free Dictionary}}</ref> The following are examples of composing in language arts:\n* The art or act of composing a [[literary]] work (i.e. novels, speeches, poems)\n* A short [[essay]], especially one written as an academic exercise. An essay is a short literary composition on a particular [[Theme (literature)|theme]] or subject, usually in [[prose]] and generally analytic, speculative, or interpretative. There are many types of short essays, including:\n**[[Five-paragraph essay]]\n**Argumentative essay\n**Cause and effect essay\n**Comparative essay\n\nCompositions may also include:\n* [[Narrative]] essays\n* [[Expository]] essays\n* [[Persuasive]] essays\n* [[Technical writing]] essays\n* [[Research]] essays\n* [[Book|Books]]\n* [[Vignette (literature)|Vignettes]] \n* [[Poetry|Poems]]\n\n== Speaking ==\nOration and live delivery are often key components of language arts programs. This can include dramatic interpretation, speeches, oral interpretation of poetry, and the like. Speaking is a valuable way to enhance concepts of persuasion, and develop linguistic skills.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://englishlive.ef.com/blog/study-tips/five-reasons-speaking-english-great-way-learn/|title=Five reasons why speaking English is a great way to learn it|website=englishlive.ef.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref>\n\n== Listening ==\nListening can be considered the basis for development of speaking, reading, and writing skills. It is the act of understanding spoken language, and is often paired with speaking.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Rhetoric]]\n* [[The three Rs]]\n* [[Trivium (education)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Language Arts}}\n[[Category:Communication design]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Buck 65 album|Language Arts (album)}}\n\n{{None}}\n'''Language arts''' (also known as [[English language|English]] language arts or ELA) is the study and improvement of the arts of language. Traditionally, the primary divisions in language arts are [[literature]] and language, where language in this case refers to both [[linguistics]], and specific [[language]]s.<ref>\"The Road to [[Middle-earth|Middle-Earth]]\", T. A. Shippey</ref> Language arts instruction typically consists of a combination of [[Reading (process)|reading]], [[writing]] (composition), [[speaking]], and listening. In schools, language arts is taught alongside [[science]], [[mathematics]], and [[social studies]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://teach.com/what/teachers-know/english-and-language-arts/|title=English and Language Arts Teacher|access-date=2017-12-24|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Reading==\n[[Reading (process)|Reading]], by definition, is the ability and knowledge of a language that allows comprehension by grasping the meaning of written or printed characters, words, or sentences. Reading involves a wide variety of print and non-print texts that helps a reader gain an understanding of the material that is being read. Reading of texts that are often included in educational curriculum include [[fiction]], [[nonfiction]], classic, and also contemporary works. Reading goes beyond calling words to understanding the information presented in a written or a visual context.\n\n==Composition==\nComposition is defined as the combination of distinct parts or elements to form a whole and the manner in which these elements are combined or related.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=composition|url=https://www.thefreedictionary.com/composition|journal=The Free Dictionary}}</ref> The following are examples of composing in language arts:\n* The art or act of composing a [[literary]] work (i.e. novels, speeches, poems)\n* A short [[essay]], especially one written as an academic exercise. An essay is a short literary composition on a particular [[Theme (literature)|theme]] or subject, usually in [[prose]] and generally analytic, speculative, or interpretative. There are many types of short essays, including:\n**[[Five-paragraph essay]]\n**Argumentative essay\n**Cause and effect essay\n**Comparative essay\n\nCompositions may also include:\n* [[Narrative]] essays\n* [[Expository]] essays\n* [[Persuasive]] essays\n* [[Technical writing]] essays\n* [[Research]] essays\n* [[Book|Books]]\n* [[Vignette (literature)|Vignettes]] \n* [[Poetry|Poems]]\n\n== Speaking ==\nOration and live delivery are often key components of language arts programs. This can include through dramatic interpretation, speeches, oral interpretation of poetry, and the like. Speaking is a valuable way to enhance concepts of persuasion, and develop linguistic skills.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://englishlive.ef.com/blog/study-tips/five-reasons-speaking-english-great-way-learn/|title=Five reasons why speaking English is a great way to learn it|website=englishlive.ef.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref>\n\n== Listening ==\nListening can be considered the basis for development of speaking, reading, and writing skills. It is the act of understanding spoken language, and is often paired with speaking.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Rhetoric]]\n* [[The three Rs]]\n* [[Trivium (education)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Language Arts}}\n[[Category:Communication design]]\n", "name_user": "Klbrain", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSpeaking:grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Language_arts"}
